<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PressForPoles     11-21 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Press For Poles,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Daily Offers Polish Paper Old Printing Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The respected French daily Le Monde has agreed to
loan an old rotary printing press to the independent Polish daily
Gazeta Wyborcza free of charge for a decade.
   Adam Michnik, editor of the Warsaw paper that began publishing
in May and now has a circulation of 500,000, signed the contract
Monday with Andre Fontaine, editor of Le Monde.
   The French paper revised its format last September and began
printing at an ultra-modern facility in a Paris suburb. Under the
agreement, Le Monde also will loan Gazeta Wyborcza some modern
photogravure equipment.
   The old press, capable of printing up to 55,000 copies an hour,
served Le Monde for more than 25 years. The $300,000 cost of
dismantling and moving the machine to Warsaw will be paid for
through a special subscription drive.
   Before signing the contract, Michnik pinned a Solidarity pin on
Fontaine's lapel and the French editor recalled an article Michnik
had written for the Paris daily when Solidarity was outlawed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
