<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-FrenchChefs     11-21 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-French Chefs,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bocuse, Robuchon and Girardet Named ``Chefs of Century.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superstar French chefs Paul Bocuse and Joel
Robuchon, and the Swiss Fredy Girardet have been named ``chefs of
the century'' by the Gault-Millau guidebook.
   The honor also was a return to grace for Bocuse because the
quide gave him back his fourth toque or chef's hat. The toque is
Gault-Millau's symbol for excellence and Bocuse was demoted to
three toques by last year's guide.
   According to the guidebook's president and editor, Christian
Millau, Bocuse's problem last year was turning out the same basic
menu for years, while other chefs were getting ahead with new ideas.
   Known as the ``emperor of cuisine,'' Bocuse also was criticized
for travelling around the world rather than tending to his stock
pots at his restaurant near Lyon.
   Bocuse accused Millau of always bringing his dog to the
restaurant and not asking for the bill. But the spat simmered down
as Millau and Bocuse kissed and made up.
   ``I was very happy to be named a chef of the century, and we've
settled our differences,'' said Bocuse. ``But the century isn't
over yet,'' he added. ``I think there's room for more of us up
there.''
   He said he was flattered to be in the company of two legendary
chefs who were posthumously named ``chefs of the century:'' Auguste
Escoffier and Fernand Point. ``Escoffier was the master of us
all,'' said Bocuse. ``And Point was the first chef-owner, who ran
his own show. Before that chefs were hidden away, as restaurants
were owned by maitre d's or entrepreneurs.''
   ``Bocuse deserves his place at the top,'' said Millau, who said
his guidebook was celebrating its 20th anniversary. ``He is an
exceptional personality who has done more than anybody else to
promote French cuisine abroad.''
   ``But I consider Robochon and Girardet more creative and
visionary chefs,'' added Millau. ``Especially Robuchon, who has
known how to marry traditional cuisine with new tastes.''
   Robuchon made quite a name for himself by bringing back the
mashed potato as a gourmet favorite _ on menus with other
specialties like sweet-sour ``migononettes'' of venison and hot
foie gras with cream of lentils.
   All three ``chefs of the century'' are regularly awarded the top
three stars in the Michelin, considered the bible of guidebooks.
   Gault-Millau, nearly as well-known in France as the Michelin,
has a circulation of about 200,000 versus 720,000 for the Michelin,
the venerable guidebook that was first published in 1900.
   Gault-Millau is avidly read for its picturesque and peppery
commentaries, a different style from the Michelin, whose terse
listing is a very serious reference for gastronomes in a country
that takes its gastronomy seriously.
   At least 1,200 French chefs and 15,000 guests packed an
exhibition hall last week at the futuristic La Defense area west of
Paris for the Gault-Millau awards followed by a tasting of regional
food and wines.
   ``I have special prizes for our top chefs,'' announced Millau,
``provided they promise not to eat them.'' He presented each with a
live Bresse rooster, a symbol of France raised in the region known
for producing its most succulent poultry. Bocuse looked his fowl
right in the eye, claiming to hypnotize it.
   In the highest category of four toques and a grade of 19.5 out
of 20 Gault-Millau listed 13 restaurants for 1990, adding three new
establishments: the Auberge de l'Eridon at Annecy, the Auberge de
l'Ill, at Illhaeusern in Alsace and the Cote d'Or at Saulieu in
Burgundy country.
   No restaurants fell from the four-toque category this year, but
three famous gourmet meccas were demoted from three toques to two:
Le Grand Vefour, Laurent and La Maree, all in Paris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
