<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     11-21 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Little Mermaid' Wins `Animation Showdown'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disney's ``The Little Mermaid'' slithered by
MGM-UA's ``All Dogs Go to Heaven'' at the box office last weekend
in the animation showdown of the year.
   The weekend's top film, though, was Eddie Murphy's
self-congratulatory ``Harlem Nights,'' according to figures
released Monday.
   ``The Little Mermaid,'' which some critics have labeled an
instant classic, finished in third place in its premiere weekend,
setting a record for an animated film with a per-screen average of
$6,068 a theater, Disney said.
   Its opening weekend of $6.1 million was 50 percent better than
last year's ``Oliver and Co.,'' which became the all-time
top-grossing animated film with a domestic gate of $53.3 million.
   Disney said half of ``Mermaid's'' viewers were adults and
teen-agers unaccompanied by children.
   ``Harlem Nights,'' which bears the distinction of mentioning its
star's name five times in the opening credits, was the
third-biggest Thanksgiving-Christmas release ever, taking in $16.1
million last weekend.
   The biggest fall films are ``Rocky IV,'' which debuted with $20
million in 1985 and ``Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home,'' which
collected $16.9 million in 1986.
   Overall business for last weekend's top 10 films was $52
million, up 47 percent from a year ago, Entertainment Data Inc.
said.
   ``Look Who's Talking,'' the love-over-diapers comedy featuring
John Travolta, Kirstie Alley and the voice of Bruce Willis, landed
in second last weekend with $8.5 million. Down 25 percent from the
previous week, ``Look Who's Talking'' nonetheless passed $85
million.
   The ensemble drama ``Steel Magnolias'' finished in fourth with
$5.4 million and a strong per-screen average of $11,303 in a
somewhat limited release. The film stars Dolly Parton, Sally Field
and Shirley MacLaine, among others.
   In fifth was ``All Dogs Go to Heaven,'' the new animated film
from Don Bluth. Featuring the voice of Burt Reynolds, ``All Dogs''
opened to $4.7 million. Its per-screen average was $2,988.
   ``Dad,'' the drama starring Jack Lemmon and Ted Danson, fell 30
percent to sixth place on receipts of $3.1 million. In seventh was
``Prancer,'' the story of a wounded reindeer who may _ or may not _
be traveling with a big guy in a red suit. ``Prancer'' grossed $2.9
million.
   ``The Bear'' was eighth with $2.8 million; ``Crimes and
Misdemeanors'' finished ninth with $1.5 million; and ``Staying
Together'' plummeted to 10th with $939,208, down 54 percent from
last week.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by
Entertainment Data and Exhibitor Relations Co. Figures are based on
a combination of actual box-office receipts and studio projections
where actual figures are not immediately available.
   1. ``Harlem Nights,'' Paramount, $16.1 million weekend gross,
2,180 screens, $7,384 per screen, $16.1 million total gross, one
week in release.
   2. ``Look Who's Talking,'' Tri-Star, $8.5 million, 1,651
screens, $5,171 per screen, $85.1 million, six weeks.
   3. ``The Little Mermaid,'' Disney, $6.1 million, 994 screens,
$6,068 per screen, $6.1 million, one week.
   4. ``Steel Magnolias,'' Tri-Star, $5.4 million, 480 screens,
$11,303 per screen, $5.4 million, one week.
   5. ``All Dogs Go to Heaven,'' MGM-UA, $4.7 million, 1,577
screens, $2,988 per screen, $4.7 million, one week.
   6. ``Dad,'' Universal, $3.1 million, 1,123 screens, $2,800 per
screen, $10.8 million, four weeks.
   7. ``Prancer,'' Orion, $2.9 million, 1,713 screens, $1,701 per
screen, $2.9 million, one week.
   8. ``The Bear,'' Tri-Star, $2.8 million, 1,054 screens, $2,648
per screen, $20.1 million, four weeks.
   9. ``Crimes and Misdemeanors,'' Orion, $1.5 million, 503
screens, $2,884 per screen, $11.1 million, six weeks.
   10. ``Staying Together,'' Hemdale, $939,208, 1,004 screens, $935
per screen, $3.4 million, two weeks.
</TEXT>
