<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     11-21 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Urges Investigation of Former HUD Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal housing official appears to
have repeatedly violated ethics laws by using her government
contacts to help her private business, a congressional report says.
   The report endorsed by the House Government Operations Committee
and released Monday urges the Justice Department to investigate
June Koch, a former official at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   The report, based on a General Accounting Office investigation
and subsequent review by a House subcommittee that investigated
Reagan-era scandals at HUD, alleges Koch used her influence on HUD
officials to benefit the consulting firm she has headed since
leaving HUD two years ago.
   The firm helps U.S. companies seeking trade with the Soviet
Union. While at HUD Koch was involved in a number of efforts to
encourage U.S. companies' participation in the Soviet Union's
construction industry.
   ``It is clear that Ms. Koch traded on her position at HUD to
gain benefits and access for herself and her clients,'' said the
report.
   The Justice Department is not bound by the recommendation but
generally conducts preliminary reviews of matters referred to it by
Congress or government agencies.
   Koch was not in her office Monday, according to a receptionist
at the Virginia-based consulting firm, Construction, Marketing and
Trading. In April testimony to the subcommittee and in a subsequent
interview, she denied any wrongdoing.
   Koch was HUD's assistant secretary for policy development from
1984 to 1987. Her duties included arranging HUD participation in a
number of trade issues involving the Soviet Union, including agency
participation in a Moscow trade fair the GAO found was a waste of
HUD money.
   She left the agency in 1987 and founded the consulting firm,
whose clients included 10 companies that participated in the
HUD-sponsored Soviet trip. She also was retained as a consultant to
then-HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce on Soviet-related matters.
   The report said Koch took a number of steps that appeared
designed to benefit her business and clients in alleged violation
of laws that prevent former government officials from improperly
using their government contacts for private gain.
   Among the steps cited in the report were contacting HUD
officials and allegedly pressuring them to change the itineraries
for visiting Soviet delegations so that they could meet with her
clients.
   ``Ms. Koch enjoyed access to HUD and to visiting Soviet
delegations that was not generally offered to others,'' the report
said. ``Such access gave Ms. Koch and her clients an advantage over
competitors who might be interested in developing Soviet trade
relations.''
   Koch had received permission from HUD's general counsel to serve
as a consultant at the same time her company was involved in Soviet
trade issues, but the HUD attorneys had advised agency officials to
closely monitor her activities to prevent any conflicts.
   However, the report said HUD failed to monitor her activities.
It recommended that HUD and other government agencies avoid even
the appearance of conflicts by refusing to hire former officials as
consultants in areas in which the former officials now are involved
in the private sector.
</TEXT>
