<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-21 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0271</SECOND>
<UNK>Dollar Down, Stocks Reach Record</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at a
record high.
   The dollar closed at 144.43 yen, down 0.24 yen from Monday's
close of 144.67 yen. It opened at 144.30 yen and moved between
144.30 yen and 144.48 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 166.29 points, or 0.46
percent, closing at 36,059.87, a record high. It had lost 70.16
points Monday. Tuesday's close was the first beyond 36,000 line.
   Stock dealers attributed the index's recovery to the yen's
stability in foreign exchange.
   Kazuhiko Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co. said
buying by investment trust companies also contributed largely to
the Nikkei's moderate gain.
   ``Following yesterday's temporary loss, market players were once
again gaining buying incentives,'' he said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving tightly
amid concern over the dollar-selling intervention of the Bank of
Japan, traders said.
   The central bank sold about $200 million Monday to halt the
dollar's rise against the yen.
   While many market players were reluctant to buy the dollar,
institutional investors picked up the currency as it fell near the
144.30-yen line, said a trader with a major commercial bank.
   Another trader with the Bank of Tokyo said the Tokyo market was
taking a wait-and-see attitude before the release of the U.S.
consumer price index figure for October later Tuesday.
   The trader said there will be no major impact on the market if
the CPI growth is about 0.4 percent.
</TEXT>
