<FIRST>r w PM-AirBags     11-21 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Bags,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release noon EST; Time set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Safety Groups Rank Car Manufacturers on Air Bag Installation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Asian carmakers rank at the bottom in
providing and promoting air bags in their 1990 cars, a coalition of
auto safety and consumer groups said today.
   The groups ranked Chrysler Corp. at the top among 12 major
manufacturers selling cars in the United States, followed by
Mercedes Benz. Chrysler is putting air bags in the driver's side of
92 percent of its 1990 models.
   Three million of the 10 million 1990 cars expected to be sold in
the United States will have air bags under federal rules, according
to a report compiled by Public Citizen, the Center for Auto Safety
and Motor Voters.
   But some drivers may not know what they've got, said Joan
Claybrook, president of the Ralph Nader-founded Public Citizen and
former head of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
   ``NHTSA's engine seems to be stuck in neutral on air bags,''
said Ms. Claybrook. She said the agency needs to promote air bags
and closely monitor their use to perfect the various systems being
installed in new cars.
   ``People should know when they buy the car that this system is
going to inflate,'' Ms. Claybrook said in an interview, adding some
drivers have been surprised by air bags they didn't know were in
their cars until they crashed.
   The three safety groups were releasing data on air bag
installation and promotion at a news conference today.
   Hyundai and Subaru, which do not have air bags in any models,
ranked at the bottom of the auto safety groups' ``report card,''
followed by Honda.
   Other low-ranking manufacturers included Mazda and Nissan, which
placed 8th and 9th.
   Volkswagen was 7th, preceded by Toyota in 6th place and General
Motors in 5th. Ford and Volvo tied for 3rd place, behind Chrysler
and Mercedes.
   Air bags were first installed in 10,000 General Motors cars in
the mid-1970s but were not used again until they were introduced in
some Fords in 1985.
   Auto safety proponents have been pushing for both air bags and a
lap and shoulder belts for all front-seat occupants.
   Federal rules applying to the 1990 models require either
driver's side air bags or another passive restraint system for both
front seats in all new cars sold in the United States. Some
manufacturers have opted for seat belts that automatically encircle
front seat occupants as they step into the car.
   The safety groups ranked car builders according to the number of
1990 models equipped with the safety devices as standard equipment,
plans for future installation of air bags, protection devices used
in all car seating positions and information provided to dealers
and the contents of company ads.
   Clarence Ditlow, executive director of the Center for Auto
Safety, said auto dealers are not giving customers proper
information about air bags.
   He said Honda dealers told consumer surveyors air bags might
blow up in the driver's face, which he called ``a stunning piece of
misinformation.''
   A spokeswoman for Honda, Toni Harrington, said she had never
heard of such a claim being made by Honda dealers.
   ``We would not be putting air bags in our cars if they were not
considered safe,'' she said. Honda offers air bags only in its
top-line Legends but plans to add them to other models, Ms.
Harrington said.
   Rosemary Dunlop, of Motor Voters, said the groups are most
concerned about the lack of availability of air bags in
lower-priced models.
   ``These cars are most likely to be purchased by young drivers
most likely to be involved in a crash,'' she said.
   The groups said all manufacturers have done poorly in providing
air bags for vehicles other than passenger cars.
   No company plans installation of air bags in vans until the 1993
models, when both Ford and Chrysler will introduce them in minivans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
