<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-21 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed above
the 36,000-point level for the first time today, while the dollar
edged down against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 144.43 yen, down 0.24 yen from Monday's
close of 144.67 yen. The U.S. currency opened at 144.30 yen, its
low for the day, and ranged as high as 144.48 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 166.29 points, or 0.46
percent, closing at 36,059.87, yet another high. The index
previously has jumped momentarily over the 36,000-point mark in the
course of trading, but today's close was the first beyond the
36,000-line.
   Nomura Securities analyst Yoshiro Inoue said the yen's stability
against the dollar reassured Japanese investors and encouraged them
to buy.
   Interest in a wide variety of issues also helped the index rise,
despite intermittent selling by investment trust companies for
profit-taking, he said.
   Among the winners were real estate, construction and electrical
issues, including Sony and Pioneer.
   An estimated 800 million shares changed hands on the market's
first section, up from Monday's 700 million shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate stayed within a narrow
range because of a lack of fresh market-affecting news, said a Bank
of Tokyo trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Only the British pound showed any major fluctuations today, he
said. Market players sold the British currency following rumors
that the Bank of England might intervene in the market, he said.
   But investors were leery of letting the dollar approach the
144.50-yen mark because of fear of prompting dollar-selling by the
Bank of Japan, the trader added.
   Japan's central bank reportedly sold about $200 million on
Monday to stem the dollar's rise.
   Spot trading volume was estimated at $3.77 billion.
</TEXT>
