<FIRST>r a PM-RobotStore     11-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robot Store,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robot Serves up CDs at Completely Automated Music Store</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: GMFanuc is cq in final graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 400-pound, bright yellow mechanical arm
replaces the human touch at the Robot Music Store, where customers
sample and buy compact discs entirely by machine.
   The robot system plays 30-second samples of song for its
customers, takes their orders and accepts payment by cash or credit
card. It also hands over the merchandise, returns change and
receipts, restocks shelves and places its own inventory orders.
   Developers claim the shop, which opened Monday, is the first
fully automated retail store.
   ``Anyone who can operate a CD machine can operate this,'' said
Dave Carroll, who, along with Bob Cahlander, founded Robot
Manufacturing Center Inc. more than three years ago in Red Wing, 40
miles southeast of Minneapolis. The company's robot frying cooks
are being tested in two McDonald's outlets.
   The ``store'' is something like a giant vending machine in the
open court shopping area of a large office building. CDs are
stacked on shelves on the inside walls of a transparent enclosure
covering 140 square feet and standing about 8 feet high. On the
outside are four earphone sets, a video screen for customers to
punch in transactions and fixtures to take in the money or credit
cards and deliver CDs and change.
   At the center of the operation is the robot arm that can rotate
around the enclosure to grab a customer's selection and deliver it.
   Carroll and Cahlander said they will test the idea in
Minneapolis to see if it is profitable and whether customers like
buying from a machine instead of a human.
   Initial reaction was mixed. Heather Jenkel, waiting to get a
closer look at the robot before buying, said she liked the idea of
being able to listen to the music before making a purchase, but
prefers to deal with a person.
   ``I like someone to be able to talk to me and tell me `Ya, I
heard this and I think it's great,''' Jenkel said.
   Monday's test of the technology was marred by one glitch. The
robot arm was shut down for a five-minute repair after it had
trouble dispensing a classical CD, said Cahlander. The arm will
have to be retooled to pick up CDs with boxes of varying sizes, he
said.
   Using the machine is much like banking at an automatic teller.
   If customers have trouble, there is a toll-free telephone number
to call for help, Carroll said.
   If similar machines are in use, ``nobody else has talked about
it,'' said Eric Mittelstadt, president and chief executive officer
of GMFanuc Robotics Corp., maker of the basic robot unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
