<HEAD>Energy Department Says Project Still On Track Despite `Conceptual
Flaw'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department is telling scientists
designing the super collider to keep the particle accelerator
within the original standards and at its $5.9 billion price tag,
despite a ``conceptual flaw.''
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore said the agency has no
plans to move the collider from Texas, contrary to a published
report that suggested a change in the SSC design could result in a
smaller, less powerful collider that would be unsuitable for its
chosen Ellis County site.
   ``As far as we're concerned, nothing's changed,'' Moore said
Monday after meeting with two Texas Republicans, Sen. Phil Gramm
and Rep. Joe Barton. ``We have no official reports, requests,
proposals any different than we're going to build the super
collider right there in Texas for $5.9 billion.''
   The Washington Post, in a front page story Sunday, quoted
unnamed U.S. officials and independent scientists who said
extensive modifications could reopen the battle for the particle
accelerator by allowing other states to argue that Texas is no
longer the ideal site.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Report: Rural Emergency Services Plagued by Lack of Resources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More federal money and better state planning
could ease some of the problems that plague emergency medical
services in rural areas, according to a congressional research
report.
   The report, released Monday by the Office of Technology, said
emergency medical services in many rural areas suffer from
personnel shortages, inadequate training, outdated equipment and
lack of financial and medical resources.
   Federal funds for emergency medical services reached about $30
million annually after passage of the 1973 EMS Systems Act, but
began to decline in 1981 when the money was folded into block grant
programs. In 1988, about $18 million in federal funds went to the
states for such services.
</TEXT>
