<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Elections     11-21 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Elections,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballots, Pigeons, Police Readied for India's Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of ballot boxes, thousands of
gallons of ink, batallions of police, and even homing pigeons were
transported to polling centers today for elections in the world's
most populous democracy.
   Opinion polls indicate Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress
Party could lose power in the voting, which begins Wednesday. It
faces a loose-knit opposition coalition of five parties led by
Vishwanath Pratap Singh, once among Gandhi's closest allies.
   The voting for a new Parliament follows a hectic, often bitter
three-week campaign highlighted by charges of government
corruption. It was punctuated by violence that left 27 people dead
across the nation.
   Fifteen of India's 25 states and five of its seven
federally-ruled territories vote Wednesday. The rest of the country
goes to the polls Friday and Sunday.
   At least 3.7 million government officials will supervise voting
at 600,000 polling centers. A total of 524 seats in the Lok Sabha,
or the House of the People, are at stake and there are 6,090
candidates. Nearly 500 million people are eligible to vote.
   With only a literacy rate of 36 percent in a nation of 880
million people, voters will choose candidates by stamping symbols
representing each candidate. The left forefinger of each voter is
then marked with indelible ink to signify that he or she has voted.
   In the eastern regions in Orissa state, authorities have trained
pigoens to carry messages from remote regions to the state police
control.
   The paramilitary Central Reserve Police issued instructions to
carefully watch people wearing shawls or blankets ``in case they
are carrying weapons or bombs underneath.''
   At least 100,000 people from the force will be deployed in
addition to regular police.
   Gandhi, a former airline pilot, succeeded his mother, Indira
Gandhi, after she was assassinated by two Sikh bodyguards on Oct.
31, 1984. Two months later, he and the Congress Party won an
unprecedented 415 of the 543 seats in Parliament.
   But his government has been haunted for more than two years by
charges of high-level corruption, and his popularity has plunged.
   Opposition leaders have made much of a $1.4 billion artillery
contract signed in 1986 with Bofors, the Swedish arms manufacturer.
They and Indian newspapers say senior government officials received
up to $50 million in kickbacks in the 1986 deal. Gandhi has
repeatedly denied the charges.
   Singh served as finance and defense minister under Gandhi but
left the government in 1987 after ordering an investigation into a
defense deal. He was later expelled from the Congress Party.
   Opinion polls suggest Gandhi's party might need the support of
Hindu fundamentalists or Communists to form the next government.
   The Congress Party, which spearheaded the struggle that
culminated in independence 42 years ago, has won the majority of
Parliament seats in seven elections.
   In 1977, however, the traditionally fractious opposition united
to oust Congress. But that government fell apart 29 months later,
and Congress came back to power in the 1980 elections.
   This year, major opposition parties again united but many voters
still have doubts about the durability.
   This year, voting will not be held in the 14 seats in the
northeastern state of Assam, where voters' lists are not ready.
Polls for four other seats have been postponed because of the
deaths of candidates. In one constituency, a candidate was returned
unopposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
