<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Helm     11-21 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Helm,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interstate Survivor had Undetected Heart Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: funeral doesn't begin until 5 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buck Helm, the longshoreman who became a
symbol of hope after the Northern California earthquake, had an
undiagnosed heart ailment that made his long fight for life all the
more incredible, his doctor said.
   Helm, who suffered injuries to virtually every organ in his body
when his car was crushed under the collapsing upper deck of
Interstate 880, had an enlarged ventricle discovered in an autopsy,
Dr. Tom McDonald said Monday.
   Helm, 58, died Saturday after a 28-day fight for his life,
including four days trapped in his compact car.
   ``The fact that he lived the four days he did (on the freeway)
was a miracle,'' McDonald said. ``The fact that he had to handle it
with a bad heart is even more of a miracle.''
   For many who survived the Oct. 17 quake _ which measured 7.1 on
the Richter scale, killed 67 and did $7 billion in damage _ the
Interstate 880 survivor embodied hopes for recovery.
   The defect in Helm's ventricle, a chamber in the heart that
pumps blood to the arteries, was undetectable while Helm was alive,
said McDonald, chief of surgery at Kaiser Permanente Medical
Center, one of the hospitals where Helm was treated.
   The heart problem combined with a fast-spreading blood infection
to kill Helm, McDonald said.
   A bacterial infection entered his blood with the rupture of an
abscess in an abdominal wound that may have been caused by the
seat-belt buckle of his car, McDonald said. The heart, already
weakend by the defect, got infected.
   McDonald said he had been optimistic about Helm's recovery but
admitted that much of his attitude was founded on hope. He called
Helm's injuries ``overwhelming.''
   Helm, who commuted 250 miles to rural from the Oakland to rural
Weaverville to visit his family on weekends, was trapped in his
crushed car for 89 hours.
   Funeral services were scheduled for this afternoon in
Weaverville.
   Helm is survived by his former wife, Lorrie, and four children:
Jeff, 16; Marc, 22; Desiree, 12; and Greg, 35.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
