<HEAD>Duquesne University Gets Endowed Chair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas J. Murrin, deputy U.S. secretary of
commerce, and his wife, Marie, have donated $1.5 million to
Duquesne University to establish an endowed chair in global
competitiveness.
   The chair will be filled following an international search for
an authority on the subject. It will be part of the School of
Business and Administration.
   Murrin, retired president of the Energy and Advanced Technology
Group at Westinghouse Electric Corp., headed Duquesne's board of
trustees until June, when he was appointed to the Commerce
Department.
   While at Westinghouse, he became an expert in global
competitiveness and served on governmental advisory committees,
including the President's Commission on Industrial Competitiveness.
   Murrin, of suburban McCandless Township, is a graduate of
Fordham University. His son, Thomas, and daughter, Heidi, are
Duquesne graduates.
