<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AnchorageTimesSold     11-21 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anchorage Times Sold,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Owner Promises Pro-Development Voice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil and mining services company that
is purchasing The Anchorage Times promised not to interfere with
news coverage but said the editorial pages would be pro-development.
   ``Through being a pro-development paper, maybe we can create
more jobs,'' said William Allen, chairman of the board of VECO
International. ``People can't stay up here (Alaska) unless they
have jobs.''
   Longtime owner Bob Atwood said he sold the evening newspaper
he's owned since 1935 to the VECO because he wanted to keep
Alaska's No. 2 paper in local hands.
   Documents to complete the deal were signed Monday by the
82-year-old Atwood and Allen, who said negotiations for the
purchase began about 1{ years ago.
   The price was not disclosed. The sale is to become final Dec. 14.
   Allen said he did not see any conflict with his political
activities, or with VECO's role as chief contractor for the Prince
William Sound oil spill cleanup.
   ``Owning the paper is not going to change my political views.
Any candidate I think is pro-development I'm probably going to
support. But the paper will not be supporting my political
beliefs,'' Allen said.
   The newspaper, which celebrates its 75th anniversary next year
and is as old as Anchorage, will remain the only locally owned and
operated daily paper in Alaska's largest city.
   ``It would have been a tragedy to have outside interests control
both newspapers in Anchorage,'' he said, referring to the Anchorage
Daily News, a Pulitzer Prize-winning morning newspaper owned by
California-based McClatchy Newspapers group.
   ``You'll see a change in the looks of the Times, the content of
the Times, beginning in January,'' Allen said. ``We'll keep the
same editorial philosophy. We're going to put the facts on the
front page and editorialize on the editorial page.
   ``There's not going to be any interference in the newsroom,''
Allen said. ``They can report on VECO as they have in the past. All
I ask is a more accurate story.''
   VECO chafed at the coverage of its lengthy battle with the
Alaska Public Offices Commission for the company's payroll plan for
campaign contributions.
   Atwood said he sold the Times to make it strong enough to
compete with the McClatchy group.
   The Times, first was published in a tent during the construction
of the Alaska Railroad, was long the dominant paper but now is No.
2 in circulation. The newspaper's circulation is 34,080 daily and
44,062 on Sundays, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations'
Sept. 30 figures. The News' circulation is 57,671 daily and 73,337
on Sundays.
   VECO is buying the Times' assets but not The Anchorage Times
Publishing Co., which will continue to be owned by Atwood.
   Allen said his company will commit substantial resources to the
newspaper to expand state and local coverage.
   Editor-in-Chief Bill Tobin has expressed a desire to
``semi-retire'' but will help during the transition, Allen said.
Atwood will become publisher emeritus, and Times General Manager
William J. Hofer will become president and chief operating officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
