<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     11-21 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official: Donors Unhappy With Afghan Government's Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Western governments are withholding
aid the Afghan people urgently need because they oppose the
communist Kabul government and want to help precipitate its
downfall, a U.N. official says.
   Western donors had been counting on the swift defeat of the
government following the Soviet military pullout, completed in
February, Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan told reporters Monday.
   ``They were taken by surprise that after the 15th of February,
after the last of the foreign troops withdrew, that somehow a
change in Kabul did not occur very quickly,'' said the prince, who
coordinates Operation Salam, the U.N. relief program for
Afghanistan.
   He said a reluctance to donate has prolonged the suffering of
Afghans and discouraged the return of 5 million refugees from
Pakistan and Iran.
   ``Why should they go back if their conditions outside are still
better than those that they would find inside?'' he asked.
   The prince said many Western donors disapprove of President
Najib's communist government and believe sending aid into
Afghanistan will help prop up his administration.
   ``In point of fact, a very large part of the country, which is
rural, is controlled by the opposition, by the resistance,'' he
said. ``Two-thirds of the country is gradually returning to normal.
   ``The needs are comparatively greater in those areas, so by
transferring aid to needy Afghan groups in areas controlled by the
resistance, you would not be shoring up the government in Kabul,''
said the prince.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar appealed last
year for $1.2 billion for Afghan aid and reconstruction.
   The prince said the Western governments ``have not been
extremely generous in responding to the secretary-general's appeal
so far.''
   His latest report, issued Monday, shows Moscow has pledged about
$600 million in aid, and Japan has pledged or given $20.1 million.
   The United States, by contrast, has donated only $16.7 million
in food and $2 million for instruction in clearing mines.
</TEXT>
