<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Jumps Above 400 Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell early today against all major
currencies in thin European trading. Gold bullion jumped above $400
an ounce in London for the first time in 10 months.
   Foreign exchange dealers said falling U.S. interest rates
brought renewed pressure on the dollar, while the West German mark
benefited from expectations that West German interest rates will
rise.
   ``The dollar looks on the way down,'' said Derek Saville,
foreign exchange manager at Standard Chartered Bank in London.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.24 Japanese yen to a closing 144.43 yen.
Later, in London, it fell further to 144.16 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.8270 West German marks, down from 1.8360
   _1.6260 Swiss francs, down from 1.6315
   _6.2205 French francs, down from 6.2465
   _2.0635 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0760
   _1,345.75 Italian lire, down from 1,351.00
   _1.1696 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1712
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5632 from $1.5595 late
Monday.
   Gold bullion opened in London at a bid price of $397.60 a troy
ounce, up from $396.50 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $400.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $399.55, up from $396.65 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.21 to close at a bid $398.61.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.70 a troy
ounce, down from $5.74 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
