<TEXT>
   Today's major developments in Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An official newspaper publishes an opposition call for the
ouster of top Communists, and opposition leaders decide to send a
delegation to meet Premier Ladislav Adamec. The actions come one
day after 200,000 people march in Prague in the largest
Czechoslovak anti-government rally ever. Protests also spread to
Brno, Bratislava and Liberec.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ROMANIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to a Communist Party congress extol hard-line leader
Nicolae Ceausescu and praise his rejection of democratic reform.
Ceausescu, the East bloc's fiercest hard-line leader, opened the
congress Monday with a six-hour speech that condemned changes in
neighboring countries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A state-run newspaper sharply criticizes Communist Party chief
Egon Krenz, the latest indication that he could lose his power
during a party congress next month. The European Community says an
envoy would visit East Berlin Dec. 4-5 to discuss East Germany's
request for a broad trade and economic cooperation accord. More
than 400,000 took to the streets of Leipzig, Dresden, Halle, and
Karl-Marx-Stadt on Monday night.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister responsible for environmental protection and
water management resigns, state media reports. Laszlo Marothy
supported the completion of the hydropower station at Nagymaros on
the Danube river, which Parliament rejected last month. The dam is
opposed by the growing independent environmentalist movement as
costly and ecologically dangerous.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ELSEWHERE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Norway's parliament approves a $31.8 million aid package for
Poland and proposes a $21 million fund to guarantee exports to
Poland of capital goods and investments.
