<FIRST>r a PM-Medflies     11-21 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medflies,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medfly Spreads in Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters sprayed the San Fernando Valley
against Medflies overnight as agriculture officials lamented a new
infestation threatening fruit crops elsewhere in Southern
California.
   ``The situation is grave,'' said Roy Cunningham, the leading
entomologist on the state's Mediterranean fruit fly advisory panel.
``Nobody wants more spraying, but we have to face the fact that
this is our fallback.''
   Early today, helicopters completed spraying the pesticide
malathion over the San Fernando Valley communities of North
Hollywood, Studio City, Burbank and Toluca Lake, crisscrossing a
12-square-mile section in an effort to eradicate the Medfly, which
ruins fruit and vegetables.
   Before the aerial attack began late Monday, about 15
environmentalists lined up along Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood
encouraging drivers to honk if they were against the spraying.
   ``he purpose of the protest is to increase pressure on public
officials to ban malathion,'' said demonstrator Randall Toller.
   The discovery Monday of a pregnant Medfly in Brea, about 25
miles from downtown Los Angeles, prompted state officials to order
spraying next week in Orange County to protect its $225 million
citrus and nursery industry.
   ``It is a tremendous threat to our industry, said Barbara Buck,
spokeswoman for the Western Growers Association. ``We're sensitive
to public concern, but the Medfly does need to be eradicated.
   In the San Fernando Valley, residents were warned to stay
inside, keep pets indoors and cover their cars against the
pesticide's sticky fly bait, which can harm automobile paint.
   Despite the warnings, officials maintain malathion poses no harm
to people.
   Pesticides have been sprayed over more than 100 square miles in
the four-month Medfly war in Los Angeles County. The fight this
year has cost taxpayers more than $10 million.
   Medflies threaten California's $16 billion farm economy because
they lay eggs in more than 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables,
making them inedible.
</TEXT>
