<DOCNO> AP891121-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Economy     11-21 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Economy,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Lawmakers Vote Down Government Plan for Limited Autonomy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet legislators rejected a Kremlin plan to
allow limited local autonomy, with lawmakers complaining it would
instead entrench central economic planning and worsen ethnic
strife, official news reports said today.
   The Soviet legislature, which was reshaped over the past year,
rejected the plan in a vote Monday. It has been taking an
increasingly independent role from Communist Party directives.
   The government plan was presented to legislators by Deputy
Premier Leonid I. Abalkin, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's top
economic adviser. It would govern relations between Moscow and
local authorities, primarily those in the 15 Soviet republics.
   The official Tass news agency said Abalkin called for a cautious
approach to economic decentralization because of the country's
difficult economic problems.
   ``We are now making only the first steps on the path of the
republics' economic independence,'' Tass quoted him as saying. ``It
is very important not to go to extremes, not to roll into a
dangerous and unjustified separation, and at the same time make a
decisive step from extreme centralization on the Union level.''
   But Deputy V.I. Alksnis said the plan was aimed at shaping a
single, federated government rather than a union of sovereign
governments sought by the Baltic and other republics, Tass said.
   ``Any other variant will lead to an aggravation of inter-ethnic
relations,'' Tass quoted Alksnis as saying.
   ``Rejecting the administrative-command style of managing the
economy, we must recognize that a Moscow bureaucrat is no better
than, for example, one from Riga,'' he added. ``Work collectives
must at last gain the right of full independence from the central
as well as the local apparatus.''
   The Supreme Soviet on Monday also imposed price controls on
several basic consumer goods, including some foods and clothes, and
export controls on scare items like furs, electrical appliances,
and fish products.
   Tass said the deputies imposed the price controls to help
retirees and other low-income groups hard hit by price increases
and shortages of consumer goods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
