<FIRST>r a PM-NavyBombs     11-21 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Bombs,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Cited by Nevada for Leaving Bombs on Public Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada has cited the Navy for leaving
unexploded bombs on public land outside target ranges.
   Environmental Protection chief Lew Dodgion, who issued the order
Monday against the Fallon Naval Air Station, said he has not
decided whether to seek fines, which could run as high as $10,000
per day per violation.
   Some of the bombs may have been dropped as long as 30 years ago.
No injuries have been reported.
   Capt. Rex Rackowitz, Fallon commander, said some of the bombs
and rockets may have landed outside the fenced ranges because of
inexperienced pilots.
   Other bombs may have skipped across the desert floor for miles
before coming to rest on federal Bureau of Land Management land
outside the ranges, he said.
   The alleged violations of state law include a failure to notify
the state and failure to get a state-approved plan to deal with the
situation.
   ``The order requires them to cease and desist if they aren't
complying with state laws, and to give us some background on when
they discovered this problem,'' Dodgion said.
   Gov. Bob Miller expressed outrage last week that the the bombs
were on public grazing lands for year but there was no effort made
to remove them until recently.
   Fallon has started a cleanup of bombs and bomb fragments near
one practice range, but not two other ranges used by Navy pilots.
The Bureau of Land Management has closed lands it holds around the
ranges pending inspections.
   Dodgion said his order won't stop the cleanup already under way.
   Some of the ordnance, being cleaned up in an exercise nicknamed
Operation Ugly Baby, was found more than a mile outside one bombing
range near Fallon, about 60 miles east of Reno.
</TEXT>
