<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     11-21 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expert Says Drugs in Motorcyclist's Blood Would Not Make Him Agressive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drugs found in the bloodstream of a black
motorcyclist shot to death by a policeman would not have caused him
to attack the officer, an expert for the prosecution testified.
   Dr. Herbert Moskowitz, an expert on drug-induced behavior, said
Monday that the high amounts of THC _ the active ingredient in
marijuana _ in the bloodstream of Clement Lloyd would have tended
to make him ``more mellow.''
   Moskowitz, of the University of California at Los Angeles, also
said that the small amounts of alcohol and cocaine that he had
ingested would not have significantly affected his driving or his
behavior.
   The defense for Colombian-born Officer William Lozano claims
Lloyd, 23, aimed his motorcycle at the officer while fleeing from a
squad car and that Lozano shot him in self-defense.
   The Jan. 16 shooting set off three days of riots.
   Lloyd's passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24, died in the subsequent
crash and Lozano, 31, was charged with two counts of manslaughter.
   In earlier testimony Monday, associate medical examiner Arthur
Copeland said the levels of THC in Lloyd's bloodstream were among
the highest on record at the medical examiner's office.
   He also said Lloyd had a moderate amount of alcohol in his blood
and small traces of cocaine in his nose.
   Using the head of a mannequin, Copeland traced the path of
Lozano's bullet from the left front temple to the rear of the head,
saying it appeared the officer was to the side of the motorcycle
when the shot was fired.
   The prosecution contends that the motorcycle was not headed
directly at Lozano and that he fired unnecessarily.
   Copeland also testified that Lloyd was carrying 5.5 grams of
marijuana and $1,500 in cash at the time.
   The rioting that followed the shooting left one person dead from
gunfire, 11 people injured and 13 buildings burned down in black
neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
