<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Palme     11-21 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief Prosecutor Won't Appeal Palme Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief public prosecutor today said
he will not appeal the acquittal of a man in the slaying of Prime
Minister Olof Palme.
   The prosecutor, Torsten Jonsson, said it was unrealistic to
believe the Supreme Court would overturn the Nov. 2 decision of the
Svea Court of Appeals, the national news agency TT reported.
   Palme, a three-time socialist prime minister who dominated
Swedish politics for more than a decade, was shot Feb. 28, 1986
while walking home from a movie with his wife, Lisbeth.
   A district court in July convicted Christer Pettersson and
sentenced him to life imprisonment, largely based on Mrs. Palme's
identification.
   The appellate court later ruled that Mrs. Palme's testimony left
too much room for uncertainty.
   The appellate court, however, said that Pettersson had no alibi
and that he was most likely the man seen waiting for Palme outside
the movie theatre.
   Pettersson, 42, was previously convicted of several lesser
crimes, including manslaughter. He was confined for 10 months
during the interrogation and trial for the Palme slaying, and could
be arrested again in the case if new evidence is uncovered.
</TEXT>
