<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Namibia 2ndLd-Writethru a0517 11-21 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0517,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibia Begins Work on Independence Constitution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with SWAPO head proposing democratic
guidelines, quotes. Pick up 7th pvs, `I'm here...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibia's newly elected assembly broke
into applause today at its opening session when the dominant party
proposed democratic principles as guidelines for the territory's
government.
   The assembly is working on a constitution that will cement the
territory's independence after 74 years of South African rule.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, or SWAPO, which
waged a 23-year war against South African rule, won 41 of the 72
seats in elections earlier this month. However, the constitution
must be approved by at least 48, or two-thirds, of the members.
   The 72 assembly members gathered at the Tintenpalast, Namibia's
seat of government since it was built by German colonial rulers in
1910.
   Theo-Ben Gurirab, foreign affairs secretary for SWAPO, proposed
that: the constitution be the supreme law of the land;, the
government consist of an elected executive responsible to the
legislative branch and an independent judicial branch; a
declaration of fundamental rights be written including freedom of
movement, speech and a free press.
   SWAPO has been known as Marxist throughout most of its history,
and its stand has been vague and contradictory regarding the
democratic principles outlined in a 1982 U.N. document calling for
Namibia's independence.
   Gurirab's proposal was unanimously applauded but could not be
adopted because the constitutional assembly does not yet have rules
of order. The assembly was adjourned until next week.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a multi-racial coalition that
favors a capitalist economy for predominantly black Namibia, has 21
seats in the assembly. The remaining 10 are divided among five
other parties.
   ``I'm here with great humility and pride,'' SWAPO President Sam
Nujoma told the assembly. ``Pride, because an occasion like this
only happens once in a lifetime. Humility, because I, Sam Nujoma,
son of an ordinary citizen, have been honored to be part of the
struggle that brought us here and to lead us to nationhood.''
   Hage Geingob, who headed SWAPO's election campaign, was elected
chairman of the assembly.
   The initial sessions are expected to focus on setting ground
rules for writing the constitution. The parties have said they hope
the document will be completed by early next year and independence
from South Africa can be declared shortly afterward.
   Marrti Ahtisarri, head of the U.N. team monitoring the
transition to independence, was present at the opening of the
assembly. He has said he expects Namibia, also known as South-West
Africa, to become independent before the United Nations is
scheduled to depart at the end of March.
   South Africa captured Namibia from Germany in 1915 and gained a
League of Nations mandate to administer the territory. The League's
successor, the United Nations, revoked the mandate in 1966, and
SWAPO launched its bush war.
   South Africa agreed last year to allow independence under a
U.S.-mediated peace accord that also calls for a phased withdrawal
of Cuba's 50,000 troops from Marxist-ruled Angola, Namibia's
northern neighbor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
