<SECOND>PM-Church of Love,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church of Love Leaders Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Pamala in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK ISLAND, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man and woman were sent to prison for
bilking thousands of lonely men out of $4.5 million with phony
tales of a paradise inhabited by nude ``love angels.''
   The two leaders of the Church of Love carried out a
``cold-blooded'' scheme that ``made fools'' of their 31,000
victims, U.S. District Judge Michael Mihm said at sentencing Monday.
   Donald Lowry, 60, founder of the sex-fantasy scam, apologized
before receiving 27 years in prison. Pamala St. Charles, 26,
declared herself the scam's ``biggest victim'' before she was
sentenced to six years in prison.
   In addition, Lowry and Ms. St. Charles, both of Bettendorf,
Iowa, were each ordered to pay $94,500 in restitution and placed on
five years' probation.
   Prosecutors said Lowry and Ms. St. Charles used a mail-order
operation to sell phony stories and nude pictures of ``love
angels,'' whom the victims hoped to someday join at a paradise
called Chonda-Za. Victims were solicited for donations for the
clothes and upkeep of the ``angels,'' who were actually models.
   ``These men wanted to believe the promise of Chonda-Za,'' the
judge siad. ``Loneliness plays tricks on us all.''
   He labeled as ``pathetic'' the 50 Church of Love members who
attended the hearing in support of Lowry and St. Charles, who were
convicted in 1988 of conspiracy, mail fraud and money laundering.
   Lowry, a former teacher, started the Church of Love mail-order
operation in 1965. He used donations to the ``angels'' to pay
himself a huge salary, buy a fleet of expensive cars and obtain
sexual favors from some of the models.
