<FIRST>u i PM-PalestinianActivist 1stLd-Writethru a0490 11-21 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palestinian Activist, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist: Palestinians Have Lost Initiative in Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD that interview was with AP.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-PLO activist says Palestinians have
``lost the initiative'' in the nearly two-year-old uprising and is
proposing a new strategy based on creating a provisional government.
   Sari Nusseibah said in an interview with The Associated Press on
Monday that if ``positive energy'' were focused on building the
institutions of Palestinian statehood, there would be less
violence, both among Palestinians and with Israelis.
   ``I believe over the last few months we have lost the initiative
and there has been a vacuum of strategy,'' he said. ``We haven't
had any renewed strategic plan to put into the intefadeh (uprising).
   ``In my opinion, these two things have helped in creating some
of the disorders ... the friction and fighting and some tendencies
towards violence.''
   By focusing on building infrastructure for the state, he said,
``you get rid of the diversions of energy that have taken place
over the past few months.''
   The remarks, unusually candid for a senior Palestinian
activists, in part appeared to grow out of rising frustration over
the killing or intimidation of Palestinians by other Palestinians.
   According to army figures released this week, Palestinian
activists have carried out 670 attacks this year against other
Palestinians, most accused of collaborating with Israel. By
Associated Press count, at least 147 Arabs have died in such
attacks.
   Some 615 Palestinians have died in confrontations with soldiers.
   Nusseibah said the problem stemmed largely from a lack of
overall coordination among local groups that had sprung up during
the intefadeh which he said led to confusion and unauthorized
initiatives.
   ``Our idea is to unite them in a single policy and seek to
implement it,'' he said.
   As a result, he said little headway in achieving statehood had
been made since the PLO met in Algeria in November 1988 and
declared an independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   A philosphy professor at Bir Zeit University in the West Bank,
Nusseibah has been described in Israeli court documents as closely
associated with the pro-PLO underground directing the uprising
against Israeli rule.
   His Holy Land Press Service was closed over the summer after
authorities said it was an intefadeh planning center, and he was
accused of acting as a conduit for PLO funds.
   He said that in the wake of last year's PLO declaration of an
independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied lands, ``we
should have moved, in my opinion, one step further in the direction
of state creation. We didn't do that.''
   Nusseibah said the PLO's 15-member executive committee, for
example, should be transformed into a Cabinet, parceling out
responsibilities such as health services, education and information.
   Palestinian officials in exile and those in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip would report to the same ``minister,'' thus
alleviating some of the confusion about lines of authority.
   He suggested Palestinians now serving in the Israeli-run
military government of the West Bank and Gaza could be named as
officials of a Palestinian government. Such officials have been
urged to resign by underground leaflets that have labeled them
collaborations.
   In the past, the concept of a provisional Palestinian government
has been proposed as a vehicle for negotiations, one that could get
around Israel's objections to talking to the PLO.
   Nusseibah said the PLO might ``wither away'' in its present form
if the infrastructure of a Palestinian state is created, allowing
the PLO to become part of the government.
   ``I think that people have come to realize here that a
Palestinian state is not going to arrive in a wrapped package ...
sent by the United Nations,'' he said. ``They have to create it.''
</TEXT>
