<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     11-21 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks on Family Visits Deadlocked Over Revolutionary Opera</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between South and North Korea on
an exchange of visits by separated family members hit a snag today
after the North insisted on showing a revolutionary opera by its
leader on South Korean television.
   Red Cross delegates from the two Koreas agreed to continue
discussions Monday on the proposed Dec. 8 family exchange, but the
chances of an agreement appeared slim.
   ``The prospect of the family exchange is dark as long as the
North Korean side sticks to its plan to show a revolutionary opera
encouraging class struggle,'' said South Korean senior delegate
Song Young-dae after eight hours of talks.
   North Korea's chief delegate, Pak Yong Su, urged Seoul to accept
the revolutionary opera, saying ``all the South Korean people want
to see it.''
   The opera is by North Korean President Kim Il Sung. It glorifies
him and his late mother, Kim Jung Suk.
   ``I don't think it would be impossible to reach an agreement,''
Pak told reporters when asked about prospects for the talks, which
reopened in September after a several-month stalemate.
   The delegates, meeting at this truce village inside the
demilitarized zone, overcame one problem today when they agreed on
the numbers: an exchange of 571-member delegations, for a period of
four days starting Dec. 8.
   They also agreed that each side would determine the composition
of its own delegation, which would be comprised of separated family
members, entertainers, support personnel and reporters.
   But the two sides could not agree on terms for their
entertainers to perform live on television.
   North Korea demanded four segments of air time, each lasting at
least three hours, during the four-day exchange. South Korea,
revising its original proposal, offered to allow three performances
of 2{ hours each.
   North Korean delegates insisted their entertainers needed at
least three hours to present the opera.
   South Korean officials denounced North Korea, saying it was
injecting political propaganda into the humanitarian project, and
strongly indicated that Seoul would not accept the showing of the
opera.
   There are about 10 million separated family members in the two
Koreas, which were divided by the partition of the Korean peninsula
in 1945 and the Korean War in 1950-53.
   The Red Cross talks are one of several channels of dialogue
under way to help ease tension on the peninsula. Talks on sports,
political and parliamentary contacts also have made little progress.
</TEXT>
