<HEAD>Real Phone Listing Has Maine Police Line Buzzing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Readers from all over the country have been
ringing a State Police station because the number is listed in one
of horror writer Stephen King's books.
   King has offered his apologies, but police say no harm done.
   The author says he didn't realize the consequences when he
decided to use the real number in ``Dark Half.''
   ``When I came to that part in the book, I thought, `Well, I'm
using the Maine State Police in Orono, I'll use the right number.'
I got out the phone book and there it was in bold type,'' said
King, who lives in Bangor.
   Communications supervisor Jim Ryan said the calls made to Orono
are no problem because they have been coming in on a non-emergency
line.
   ``All are very nice people who are just curious to see if the
number is for real,'' said dispatcher Dan Lawrence. ``A lady from
Montana said she is coming to Maine next year for vacation and
wants to stop by the barracks to get my autograph.''
