<FIRST>u i PM-CommonsTV 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commons TV, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0504,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Enters the British Commons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with broadcast beginning; picks
up 9th pvs, `Any other...' ^By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television cameras focused on the House of Commons
today to give Britons their first live screen view of the
venerable, if sometimes raucous mother of parliaments.
   The first image they saw in the live broadcast was the gowned,
bewigged speaker, Bernard Weatherill, bellowing ``Order! Order!''
to bring chattering, excited lawmakers into line for the TV debut
of the Mother of Parliaments.
   The unelected House of Lords has permitted television broadcasts
of its proceedings since 1985, and Queen Elizabeth II's ceremonial
opening of Parliament was seen nationwide earlier this morning.
   But the House of Commons, the often rowdy elected chamber down
the hallway, resisted the cameras until now, sticking only with
live radio broadcasts that began in 1978.
   Former Conservative Cabinet minister Ian Gow delivered the
traditional message of thanks to the queen for outlining the
government's legislative program earlier today in the House of
Lords.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, leader of the governing
Conservative Party, and Neil Kinnock, leader of the opposition
Laborites, then prepared to joust with each other about the
contents of the queen's speech.
   Any other lawmaker could join in, providing he or she can catch
the Speaker's eye by standing up and waving an order paper _ a
printed copy of the day's agenda _ and be called.
   The chamber can be a noisy place with much booing and braying
and it's Weatherill who can be heard repeatedly shouting ``Order,
order'' in a bid to restore calm at times of tension.
   But TV viewers are not going to see it all.
   To prevent anything unseemly being shown, such as campaign
buttons, outrageous dress or bored legislators asleep on their
green leather benches, the televisors have been ordered to show
only the head and shoulders of whoever is speaking.
   ``I think it's terrible that head shots will only be used. I
could be wearing a tutu, and nobody would notice,'' said Laborite
Austin Mitchell.
   Debates in the 650-member chamber go on for hours and hours,
sometimes all night. Eight remote control cameras have been
installed in the ornate chamber. Britain's four national channels
and the Sky satellite network will be able to broadcast as much as
they like of the daily proceedings, live or recorded.
   C-SPAN, the American cable-satellite public affairs network,
planned to offer portions of the debates to its subscribers.
   It has taken 30 years of debate to get cameras into the Commons.
   A 318-264 vote in February 1988 agreed to them for an
experimental six months, although the House of Lords _ where the
peers, most of them hereditary, sit on scarlet benches _ have been
on live TV since 1985.
   The U.S. House of Representatives has allowed television since
1979.
   The 21-month delay in getting the cameras into the Commons
included the dispatch of a delegation to Canada to see how
Parliament is televised there.
   ``Planning the invasion of Normandy in World War II took only 12
months,'' grumbled lawmaker Frank Dobson.
   It has taken 30 years of debate to get cameras into the Commons.
   A 318-264 vote in February 1988 allowed them for a six-month
experiment. Later, a delegation went to Canada to see how
Parliament is televised there.
   ``Planning the invasion of Normandy in World War II took only 12
months,'' grumbled lawmaker Frank Dobson.
   The partisan shouts and jeers of the Commons have made it a
byword for unruly behavior. This week's comments in the media
centered on whether the cameras will make the chamber better
behaved _ or possibly worse.
   London's Evening Standard newspaper predicted Monday that the
Commons was unlikely to beat the soap operas as a favorite with the
public.
   ``But, at least, we may get an insight into why they make those
peculiar noises we have heard for so long on the Commons sound
broadcasts,'' it said.
</TEXT>
