<HEAD>Gorbachev Backs Reform in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev today expressed
support for the rapid changes encompassing Eastern Europe,
including current demands for reform in Czechoslovakia.
   Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union must undergo radical change
because they lag behind the West technologically, Gorbachev told
reporters after meeting with Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   On Monday, about 200,000 people filled Prague's streets
demanding free elections and other freedoms, and tens of thousands
demonstrated again today. Also, an official newspaper published an
opposition call for the ouster of top Communist leaders.
   ``I think the changes underway now are consistent with the
overall context of the changing world, a world that is changing
both in the East and the West,'' Gorbachev told reporters.
   ``I think the change is very important, and the importance of
the change will be that it will create a better society, a more
open society, a more democratic society,'' he said.
   Mulroney, the first Canadian prime minister to make an official
visit to Moscow since 1971, invited Gorbachev to visit Canada and
address the Canadian parliament, a Canadian press pool report said.
No date for the proposed visit was given.
