<FIRST>u w PM-Contra-Sandinistas 2ndLd-Writethru a0564-a0459 11-21
0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra-Sandinistas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564-a0459,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Drops Demand for Total Withdrawal of Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan government, seeking a
cease-fire agreement, today dropped its demand for a total
withdrawal of Contra rebels from Nicaraguan territory and called
instead for a pull-back of 2,300 insurgents.
   Outlining the new proposal at a news conference, Nicaraguan Vice
Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said the figure represents the
total number of Contras who have infiltrated into Nicaragua from
base camps in Honduras in recent weeks.
   ``If the Contras do not accept the proposal, they have no
interest in a cease-fire,'' Tinoco said.
   He spoke to reporters at the Nicaraguan Embassy shortly before
the resumption of cease-fire talks with the Contras at the
Organization of American States.
   The Contras have insisted on a cease-fire in place and have said
that there has been no significant increase in the number of rebels
operating inside Nicaraguan territory in recent weeks.
   But Tinoco said even the State Department has acknowledged that
about 2,000 Contras have crossed back across the border from the
Honduran base camps since the first week of October.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega suspended the cease-fire on
Nov. 1 after alleging the Contra forces had engaged in terrorist
activities.
   The chief Contra negotiator, Col. Enrique Bermudez, has accused
the Sandinistas of hardening their position by insisting on both
the withdrawal of the Contras and their demobilization. But Tinoco
has said Bermudez misunderstood the Sandinista position.
   A commission made of United Nations and Organization of American
States mediators spent the weekend drawing up revisions of a plan
they had set forth during the early going of the negotiations,
which began Nov. 9.
   Part of Monday's negotiating session was spent going over the
revisions.
   Before the talks resumed Monday, rebel spokesman Bosco Matamoros
accused the Sandinistas of not negotiating in good faith.
   ``They want a total surrender,'' he said. ``They want an
unconditional surrender.''
   Matamoros called for an immediate cease-fire with appropriate
verification procedures.
   Tinoco reaffirmed his government's view that the cease-fire must
be linked to a ``separation of forces'' _ meaning the withdrawal of
Contra forces to base camps in Honduras.
   ``That's fundamental,'' Tinoco said.
   Tinoco also disclosed he had a brief meeting with a State
Department official Saturday to discuss issues relating to the
staffing of the respective embassies of the two countries.
   He didn't identify the official with whom he spoke.
   The administration generally has avoided high-level contact with
the Sandinistas, urging them instead to focus attention on
resolving their differences with both the Contras and the internal
opposition.
</TEXT>
