<FIRST>u a PM-Wood-ChipperTrial     11-21 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wood-Chipper Trial,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Convicted of Murdering Wife, Running Body Through a Wood Chipper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former airline pilot was convicted today
of murdering his wife and running the body through a wood chipper
to get rid of the evidence.
   A Superior Court jury deliberated more than three days before
finding Richard Crafts guilty in the 1986 slaying. The 51-year-old
Newtown man could receive up to 60 years in prison at sentencing
Jan. 8.
   Crafts was accused of killing his Danish-born wife, Helle, in
their bedroom, cutting up the body with a chainsaw and feeding
parts through a rented wood chipping machine.
   Prosecutors were unable to establish the cause of death but said
blood was spattered on the bedroom walls.
   Because Mrs. Crafts' body was never found, the prosecution faced
a burden of proof unprecedented in Connecticut _ proving that a
woman had been murdered when the defense argued that she may still
be alive, perhaps living in Europe.
   The evidence included less than an ounce of human remains, such
as a fingernail and hair that the prosecution claimed were Mrs.
Crafts.'
   Witnesses included three Newtown-area residents who said they
saw a man using a wood chipper on a bridge above the Housatonic
River.
   Damaging testimony also came from Crafts' brother-in-law, David
Rodgers, who said Crafts told him police divers would not find his
wife's remains in the river.
   According to Rodgers, Crafts said, ``Let them dive. There's no
body _ it's gone.''
   The prosecution suggested Crafts acted out of anger that his
wife, a 39-year-old flight attendant and mother of three, had asked
for a divorce because her husband was seeing another woman.
   Crafts' first trial in 1988 ended in a mistrial when a juror
walked out of deliberations after refusing to join in a guilty
verdict.
</TEXT>
