<HEAD>Former Judge Released From Halfway House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon
Jr. was released from a halfway house today, 18 days after the U.S.
Senate removed him from the bench for perjury.
   Nixon, 61, went to the halfway house July 17 from a federal
prison in Florida, where he served nearly 16 months of a five-year
term.
   The former Mississippi judge was convicted in 1986 of lying to a
grand jury in denying discussing a marijuana case with a
prosecutor. He was later impeached by the U.S. House and removed.
   Nixon's attorney, Boyce Holleman, said Nixon will try to get
back his law license, which was indefinitely suspended by the
Mississippi Supreme Court.
