<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     11-21 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leader Criticizes Zhao, Praises Deng</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Communist Party chief criticized his
predecessor, Zhao Ziyang, for siding with rioters during the
pro-democracy protests and said ``international hostile forces''
will continue to try to thwart socialism.
   In remarks released Tuesday, Jiang Zemin also praised senior
leader Deng Xiaoping, who recently retired from his last party
post, and indicated Deng still plays a pivotal role in government.
   He also called for cooperation to strengthen the national
economy and criticized corruption and a lack of discipline in the
party.
   Jiang made his comments in a wide-ranging speech to the
Communist Party's Central Committee Nov. 9. The speech was carried
by the official Xinhua News Agency and read on television. Neither
gave a reason for the delay in reporting the speech.
   ``The struggle between international hostile forces and
socialist countries will exist for a long time on the levels of
infiltration and counterinfiltration, subversion and
countersubversion,'' Jiang said.
   He was referring to the Chinese army's bloody suppression in
June of the pro-democracy movement, which the government calls
``counterrevolutionary turmoil'' and says was supported from
overseas.
   ``Because of a rampant ideological trend favoring bourgeois
liberalization (western ideals) for a period in the recent past,
there was confusion about many theoretical issues,'' Jiang said.
   ``Some cadres, including some leading officials, were affected
by this to different degrees, and some even sided with the
rioters,'' he said.
   He was clearly alluding to ousted party chief Zhao, who was
dropped from all his party posts in June for supporting the
student-led demonstrators and is believed to be under house arrest.
   Zhao's removal led to Jiang's meteoric rise from Shanghai party
boss to head the party at the last Central Committee plenum in June.
   Earlier this month, he was named to head the powerful Central
Military Commission as Deng's handpicked successor. Deng, 85,
retired as head of the commission, his last party post.
   Jiang, 62, urged patience in awaiting results from the ambitious
market-oriented reforms started by Deng a decade ago.
   While Deng's reforms have raised the standard of living for
millions of Chinese, increased production, and made more goods,
many of them imported, available to consumers, a common complaint
is that the reforms have not been benefited more people.
   But Jiang gave high praise to Deng, who despite his retirement
remains the most powerful man in China.
   While the Central Committee initially opposed Deng's desire to
step down,``a consensus of views is reached that Comrade Xiaoping
is far-sighted, so we should respect his wishes and grant his
request,'' Jiang said.
   ``The health and longevity of Comrade Xiaoping are of great
significance to the smooth development of the work of the party and
the state.''
   Jiang mentioned democracy, but not in the context of political
reforms. Party members and leaders, he said,``must adhere to the
principle of democracy, develop a democratic style of work, give
heed to opinions from all walks of life, including different and
even dissenting opinions.''
   He also displayed an almost disarming modesty, saying he was not
prepared to take the helm of the 47 million-member party in June.
   He lashed out at the bribery, embezzlement and other corruption
that has become widespread, saying,``We must rely on the masses to
strengthen our efforts to construct clean politics, and fight
against corruption and unhealthy tendencies in society and our
party.''
   He also said party discipline had become lax,
encouraging``selfish departmentalism and overstress on local
interest.''
   Party organizations in rural areas, he said,``are in a state of
weakness and slackness ... paralyzed or semi-paralyzed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
