<HEAD>Zaikov Removed as Moscow Party Boss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lev. N. Zaikov, the hard-line Communist who
succeeded firebrand Boris N. Yeltsin as Moscow party boss, was
removed today from that powerful position, a party official said.
Zaikov had been promoted.
   Zaikov, 66, ``was relieved of his responsibilities as Communist
Party first secretary for Moscow'' by a plenary meeting of the
Moscow party committee, said a duty officer at Moscow party
headquarters.
   Zaikov's removal is connected ``to his transfer to a higher
position,'' said the duty officer, who gave his name only as Ivanov.
   Zaikov, who is also a member of the ruling Politburo, was named
party boss in the Soviet capital after Yeltsin was fired in
disgrace in November 1987 for criticizing the slow pace of Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's reform program.
