<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Textbooks-Coyotes     11-21 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Textbooks-Coyotes,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Agrees to Change Reference to Coyotes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A publisher says it has agreed to correct
a textbook that depicts the coyote as no threat to sheep.
   Holt, Rinehart and Winston Inc., at the behest of the state
Textbook Commission, will provide an amended page for Utah users of
the book.
   The high school English text, in an exercise on identifying
nouns, says the ``most widespread misperception about coyotes is
that they prey on cattle and sheep'' and that no scientist has
documented a case of coyotes killing cattle or sheep.
   Clair R. Acord, executive secretary of the Utah Woolgrowers,
said 1988 figures from state and federal officials show that 24,300
sheep valued at $2.1 million were reported killed by coyotes in
Utah, which has roughly 500,000 sheep.
   Rural pupils likely wouldn't be taken in by the textbook, but
``an urban child could get the idea that the coyote is a prince,
which he isn't,'' Acord said.
   Pat McCambridge, a senior editor for Holt, Rinehart in Austin,
Texas, said, ``We had no reason to believe our source was wrong and
had no idea that this was controversial.''
   She said the amended page will say coyotes are known to kill
domestic animals and can have a devastating effect on sheep herds.
</TEXT>
