<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Coverage,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes Again to Repeal Catastrophic Medical Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today voted for the third time to
repeal catastrophic medical coverage for retirees, setting the
scene for the Senate to offer one last proposal to salvage some of
the benefits.
   The House vote was 352-63. Senators were preparing to send the
House a compromise offer to kill the unpopular surtax that finances
catastrophic benefits under the Medicare system and preserve some
parts of the program.
   ``At this late date and hour, the only prudent action this House
can take is force the Senate into voting for repeal,'' Rep. Clay
Shaw, R-Fla., said as Congress looked for a solution to one of the
two major obstacles to adjournment for the year.
   ``We are throwing out the baby with the bath water,'' said Rep.
Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y.
   The program was enacted a year ago to prevent a major illness
from plunging retirees into bankruptcy. Many of those retirees are
objecting to having to pay for the program because they have
private insurance coverage; some higher-income retirees don't like
having to pay an income surtax of up to $800 a year to finance the
benefits.
   Congressional leaders say the House and Senate will not adjourn
for the year without repealing the surtax.
</TEXT>
