<HEAD>Probation For Parachuting From Downtown Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who parachuted off a downtown building
has been placed on probation for two years and ordered to do 200
hours of community service after he said he had learned his lesson
and would not do it again.
   Mark Kruse, 27, was sentenced Monday by Milwaukee County Circuit
Judge Charles Schudson for the Christmas night jump from an office
building which was under construction at the time.
   Kruse pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of disorderly
conduct and entering a locked construction site.
   ``He seemed very responsible and contrite,'' Schudson said.
   Officials said Kruse smashed into a window of a building across
the street, landed in the Milwaukee River and became tangled in the
chute's lines. He was helped from the water by a friend and a
firefighter, but broke his arm.
   Assistant District Attorney Thomas McAdams said Kruse had been
found liable in a civil trial and was making payments for $7,700 in
damages.
