<FIRST>u w PM-ForeignAid 1stLd-Writethru a0448 11-21 0976</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Rejects Efforts to Curb Aid to El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs with advisers recommending Bush sign bill; picks
up at pvs 2nd graf, `After 10'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's senior advisers will
recommend he sign a $14.6 billion foreign aid bill following an
apparent truce on a provision that the White House believed would
reduce its flexibility in carrying out foreign policy, an
administration official said today.
   The provision bars the use of U.S. aid money to entice foreign
governments to carry out policies banned by American law. It grew
out of the Iran-Contra affair, in which aid to Honduras was
expedited in return for Honduras' agreement to shelter the
Nicaraguan Contras at a time when Congress had banned U.S. military
assistance to the rebels.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., in a statement on the House floor, said
today that the provision refers only to clear written or oral
agreements with other governments and ``is not an attempt to
hamstring government officials in the course of their normal
duties.''
   The administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Bush now was being advised to approve the measure.
   In another area of controversy within the bill, Congress
rejected attempts to restrict U.S. military aid to El Salvador, but
there were signs that a week of heightened violence has left
lawmakers wary of continuing what one called a ``blank-check''
policy.
   ``After 10 years of bankrolling failure, it is time we changed
our policy,'' said Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore. ``Have we no right to
ask why after almost $4 billion spent, after 70,000 lives lost, why
our policy has not produced different results?''
   Both the House and the Senate on Monday voted down efforts to
curb the $85 million in U.S. military aid due to flow to the
government of President Alfredo Cristiani in the coming year,
heeding a call by President Bush not to further weaken that
country's new administration.
   After a debate that rekindled old animosities over El Salvador,
the House voted 215 to 194 to effectively keep the restrictions
from being added to the foreign aid bill, which contains money for
U.S. allies around the globe and the first cash in a new aid
program for Poland and Hungary.
   It sent the bill to the Senate, which rejected a similar
amendment by a 58-39 margin and forwarded the measure to Bush for
his signature.
   Bush earlier in the day had termed any attempt to cut off aid to
the Cristiani government ``absolutely unacceptable,'' and added:
``This is not the time to undermine a fragile democracy that is
under attack ... It's totally unacceptable, and the day of these
Marxist attacks should end right now.''
   But the past week's violence in El Salvador appeared to have
created a shift of roughly 20 votes in the Senate since the body
voted 82-18 Sept. 20 for military aid with no conditions.
   And the House followed its rejection of strings on the military
aid with nearly unanimous approval of a resolution warning that
future aid would hinge on whether Cristiani tracks down and puts on
trial those responsible for the murder last week of six Jesuit
priests and two apparent witnesses to the killings. The vote was
409-3.
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said lawmakers were coming under
heavy pressure from Christian groups to take action against El
Salvador, including heavy lobbying and demonstrations at some
members' district offices.
   In Washington, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
expressed support for proposals ``to withhold substantial portions
of military aid while the performance of the Salvadoran government
and military is tested.''
   And opponents of U.S. aid heckled Bush during an appearance in
Chicago, while others in Washington repeatedly interrupted Senate
floor proceedings and were forcibly ejected from the chamber by
Capitol police.
   In El Salvador, a pitched weeklong battle that has cost more
than 1,000 lives was winding down as the leftist rebels of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front withdrew from the capital
of San Salvador into the countryside.
   In the House, Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., had proposed to add
language that would have held back 30 percent of this fiscal year's
military money until after April 1 of next year to keep pressure on
the Salvadoran government to solve the Jesuit murders.
   A similar proposal in the Senate, pushed by Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., would have withheld 30 percent of the military aid until the
killers of the priests were apprehended and brought to trial.
   But Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., called it ``a terrible amendment,''
and added: ``If we pass it, we reward the communist terrorists ...
and punish the democratically elected government.''
   ``To rush into this breech with this kind of amendment is
suicide, gentlemen, for that country,'' argued Rep. Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y. ``This amendment is a selective response to a great
tragedy.''
   ``This is not a debate over who are the good guys and who are
the bad guys,'' countered Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., ``This is a
debate over whether the United States has an obligation to assure
that taxpayer dollars are going to a government that protects human
rights.''
   Bush said he had personally told Cristiani ``how strongly we
feel about the killings.''
   ``And I told him that they must get to the bottom of it. I am
convinced they will. The people who did this, whether they come
from the extreme left or the extreme right, pay the penalty,'' Bush
said.
   Major aid items included in the bill were $3 billion for Israel,
$2.1 billion for Egypt, $500 million for Turkey, $300 million for
Greece, $440 million for the four Central American democracies,
$533 million for Poland and Hungary, $125 million for the drug war
in Bolivia, Peru and Colombia and $160 million for a new
international development initiative for the Philippines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
