<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DisabledChildren     11-21 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabled Children,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Designed To Ensure Eligible Children Get Disability Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday announced plans to
more carefully review cases in which severely disabled children
have been denied Supplemental Security Income benefits.
   The new procedures were announced by Health and Human Services
Secretary Louis Sullivan after a study by the Social Security
Adminstration found that some eligible children had been improperly
denied SSI benefits.
   The SSI program provides a minimum income floor to 4.5 mil   ``I want
to be personally assured that all needy children
entitled to disability benefits receive them and the critical
medical coverage that often accompanies receipt of SSI through
eligibility to the Medicaid program,'' Sullivan said.
   Social Security Commissioner Gwendolyn King said the new steps
were taken after a review of 927 cases in which children were
denied disability benefits found that 59 youngsters had been
improperly turned down.
   Mrs. King said the overall error rate was not statistically
significant, but that certain categories of youngsters were
particularly prone to error, such as those under age 3 and those
suffering from congenital, cardiovascular, digestive or mental
disabilities.
   Sullivan directed Social Security officials to do the following:
   _Review all cases of disabled children from birth through age 3
twice before a claim is denied, and conduct double reviews for
older children in certain categories prone to error.
   _Hire more pediatricians to help judge and review childhood
claims since they are expert in the growth and development of
children.
   _Review and revise the medical criteria used to determine which
chidren are eligible for SSI benefits.
   _Intensify training and education of all disability examiners
and medical personnel to improve their understanding of childhood
disabilities.
</TEXT>
