<HEAD>Wind Knocks Out Power, Bashes Planes, Fans Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf pvs, `We expected ...' with
windows falling out.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers cleared streets of trees and power lines today after
wind storms left more than 200,000 East Coast homes and businesses
without power, battered four parked jets in metropolitan New York
and fanned a three-block fire in New Jersey.
   Winds of 63 mph were blamed for the death of a Baltimore woman
killed when a warehouse fell on her home. Snow from the same cold
front was blamed for the deaths of two young men whose pickup
slammed into a tractor-trailer in western Pennsylvania.
   The fire early today in Newark, N.J., left at least 35 families
in a poor area homeless, Mayor Sharpe James said. Gusts to 50 mph
spread the blaze to more than a dozen houses and apartment
buildings, but no injuries were reported.
   ``We expected it to be windy but we didn't expect it to be this
strong,'' said Clyde Dossett of the National Weather Service in
Wilmington, Del., where the wind was clocked at 59 mph.
   In New York City, 18 panes of glass popped loose from a building
under construction, raining glass on the street and tying up
traffic in midtown Manhattan.
   Gusts to 64 mph lifted a parked Continental Airlines jetliner
and dropped it on a baggage cart and fuel truck at Newark
International Airport.
   No passengers were on the Boeing 727, but a worker inside the
craft's baggage area suffered minor injuries, authorities said.
   Three Pan Am planes parked outside a hangar at New York's
Kennedy International were damaged by 44 mph gusts, police said.
   The wind blew a 747 into the hangar and pushed another 747 into
a fence. Metal scaffolding around a third plane, an A-300 airbus,
was blown into the aircraft's skin.
   ``The storm came in fast and furious and ended almost as
quickly,'' police Lt. Kevin Hassett said. The airport was shut for
45 minutes Monday night.
   Planes at LaGuardia Airport in New York City also were delayed
for about an hour by the wind.
   Farther north winds up to 50 mph combined with ice and up to 13
inches of snow in Vermont to make driving nearly impossible this
morning.
   ``It's bad; it's bad; it's bad,'' said Ray Burke of the state
Highway Department. ``We've got some areas where it's white-out.
You can't see past your windshield.''
   Utility officials said more than 200,000 customers lost power at
the peak of storms Monday night that swirled out of a strong cold
front moving across the Eastern Seaboard.
   Utility crews worked through the night to get the number of
customers blacked out in the District of Columbia, and Prince
George's and Montgomery counties, Md., down from 20,000 to 14,000
by 7 a.m., said the Potomac Electric Power Co.
   Virginia Power reported all but 1,300 of 11,000 customers who
lost power had electricity again. Baltimore Gas and Electric put
all but 16,000 of 65,000 affected customers back in service by 5
a.m., and utilities worked to get power back to nearly 110,000
customers in metropolitan New York.
