<FIRST>r a PM-US-SalvadorProtests 2ndLd-Writethru a061 11-21 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Salvador Protests, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0618,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests of U.S. Aid to El Salvador in Seattle, San Francisco, Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with 131 arrests sted 80, scuffles
breaking out; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `The latest ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators demanding an end to U.S. aid to El Salvador linked
arms and surrounded San Francisco's Federal Building today for a
second day, and police said 131 people were arrested.
   More than 2,000 people around the United States joined
demonstrations Monday, tying up traffic in Seattle and heckling
President Bush. At least 230 were arrested Monday.
   ``We know what this place is for; murder in El Salvador,''
chanted about 400 protesters outside the Federal Building in San
Francisco today. Newsracks were overturned and scuffles broke out
between protesters and people trying to enter the building to go to
work.
   The latest round of outrage focused on last week's slaying of
six Jesuit priests, their houskeeper and her daughter in El
Salvador.
   The demonstrators blamed the killings on right-wing elements in
the central American country's military. The slayings occurred amid
heavy fighting as the government drove leftist rebels from the
capital, San Salvador.
   ``It has become very clear over this decade that United States
aid ... is that which is destroying the people of El Salvador,''
the Rev. William Wood, executive director of the California
Catholic Conference, said during the San Francisco demonstration.
   ``There is no democracy in El Salvador as long as the army is in
control. No one elects the army,'' Wood said.
   Protests also were held Monday in New York City, Spokane, Wash.,
and Newark and Camden, N.J.
   The demonstrations came as the U.S. House rejected 215-194 an
attempt to restrict up to $85 million in military aid to the
country.
   The House approved 409-3 a non-binding resolution saying that
bringing the priests' killers to justice would ``be instrumental in
determining continued U.S. support'' for El Salvador.
   Bush defended his support of what he called a freely elected
government, and defended the government of Salvadoran President
Alfredo Christiani against accusations of complicity in the
killings.
   At a political fund-raiser in Chicago, Bush rebuked hecklers who
accused his administration of responsibility for the deaths.
   ``We are not. You be quiet,'' Bush shot back.
   Four people were led out by security guards as the crowd
applauded. The four, including three women who said they were Roman
Catholic nuns, were charged with disorderly conduct.
   Six people who demonstrated outside the hotel where the
fund-raiser was held were arrested for obstructing traffic and
other minor charges. All 10 were released on their own recognizance.
   In Washington, D.C., about 200 people demonstrated and nine
people who staged a protest in the Senate galleries were arrested,
Capitol police said.
   In Seattle, about 300 people demonstrated, some carrying wooden
crosses.
   A mass of protesters up to three deep blocked southbound lanes
of Interstate 5 and an exit ramp near the downtown Federal
Courthouse, creating a 3-mile back up during morning rush hour.
   They were dragged away by police as fellow protesters chanted,
``No more bombs, no more war, U.S. out of El Salvador.''
   Seventy-two people were arrested, police said. Sixty were given
tickets for obstructing traffic and 12 were cited for refusing to
give their names or resisting arrest. All were released.
   In San Francisco on Monday, more than 600 people, including 150
Jesuits, staged a sit-in at the Federal Building and prayed for the
thousands slain in El Salvador's civil war.
   Authorities arrested 136 people, including priests, for blocking
doors to the building or blocking the sidewalk. Virtually all were
cited and released.
   About 250 people took part in similar marches and vigils at
Stanford University and about 150 at San Francisco State University.
   In Spokane, about 50 people marched nearly a mile from a Roman
Catholic church to the downtown office of House Speaker Tom Foley,
D-Wash, toting banners that read ``Salvadorans Forgive Us.''
   Eleven were arrested for refusing to leave Foley's office. Foley
was in Washington, D.C.
   About 500 protesters gathered outside a military recruiting
office in Times Square in New York City, said police Sgt. Maurice
Howard.
   Between 50 and 60 people held a protest at the Newark, N.J.,
office of Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and 25 to 30 demonstrated
in Camden, N.J.
</TEXT>
