<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter-Reagan     11-21 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter-Reagan,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Lawyers Say Subpoena Raises Constitutional Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan's attorneys indicated
Wednesday they were considering a challenge to a subpoena for
Reagan to produce documents and testify at the Iran-Contra trial of
his former National Security Adviser John M. Poindexter.
   In court papers asking for a two-week delay, Reagan's private
attorneys said the subpoena ``raises novel and complex
constitutional issues'' about the power of courts over a former
chief executive.
   The subpoena ``raises weighty and yet unsettled constitutional
issues regarding the doctrine of separation of powers and the
executive privilege,'' Reagan's lawyers said.
   The former president was directed by the subpoena to turn over
documents needed for Poindexter's trial by Wednesday.
   The Justice Department also sought a delay until Dec. 6 for
responding to a subpoena for Reagan papers that are held by the
National Archives and Records Administration.
   The subpoenas were served last week after they were approved by
the judge in the Poindexter case.
   Reagan's former national security adviser is scheduled to go on
trial Jan. 22 in federal court here on charges of making false
statements to Congress and obstructing congressional inquiries into
the Iran-Contra affair.
   Defense lawyers have suggested that Reagan knew about letters
that Poindexter sent to Congress in response to queries about
whether the administration was secretly aiding the Nicaraguan
rebels at a time when such assistance was banned by law. Poindexter
is accused of falsely assuring Congress there was no such
assistance.
   Reagan's pleading, filed by a team of lawyers headed by Theodore
B. Olson, suggested that the former president may invoke the
doctrine of executive privilege to resist turning over certain
documents or answering certain questions.
   Executive privilege was invoked by then-President Nixon during
the Watergate scandal when he tried to withhold tapes of
conversations he had with aides in the Oval Office.
   In a 1974 decision that ultimately led to Nixon's resignation,
the Supreme Court ordered him to turn over the tapes.
   The high-court's 8-0 ruling, however, appeared to leave room for
possible assertions of executive privilege to protect diplomatic,
military or state secrets.
   Reagan's lawyers note that Poindexter's request for documents
covers 67 separate subjects and the list itself is highly
classified.
   The attorneys also raised the possibility that President Bush
may seek to invoke executive privilege to block release of some of
the documents.
   In its pleading, the Justice Department said that it had an
``obvious and strong interest'' in the subpoena served on Reagan
``because of the sensitive nature and subject of the subpoena
directed to him and the potential relationship of the materials
sought to the national interest and to the presidency.''
   The Justice Department said that some of the documents sought
from the government and from Reagan may be covered by the
Classified Information Procedures Act, which regulates the
disclosure of government secrets in court.
</TEXT>
