<FIRST>r i AM-Nureyev     11-21 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nureyev,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nureyev Steps Down, Ending Soap Opera at Paris Opera</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-month battle between Rudolf Nureyev and the
president of the Paris Opera Ballet ended Tuesday when the
Soviet-born dancer resigned as dance director of the company he
helped bring to prominence.
   A statement issued after a meeting between Nureyev and President
Pierre Berge said the two ``decided mutually that Nureyev should
step down as dance director.''
   The break, however, sounded more like a separation than divorce.
The statement said Nureyev would stay on as ``premier
choreographer,'' a post created for him ``to insure the presence of
his productions at the Paris Opera.''
   Nureyev, 51, had been artistic director since 1983.
   The Paris Opera became almost a soap opera in recent weeks, with
tensions mounting as Nureyev and Berge exchanged charges in the
press.
   Nureyev's contract as dance director expired Aug. 31.
Interviewed last month by the newspaper Le Figaro, he complained he
had not heard from Berge, whom he later described as harder to
reach than God.
   Berge retorted that it was difficult to communicate with someone
who is so rarely in Paris.
   Nureyev has been frequently absent. He is touring the United
States with ``The King and I,'' and is scheduled to play the lead
role immortalized by Yul Brenner for another two years.
   Berge called for the dancer's contract to include a six-month
residence clause with the ballet company _ which Nureyev was
certain to refuse. Insiders said Berge hoped to boost the morale of
the ballet company, which has not appreciated Nureyev's part-time,
long-distance directing.
   Nureyev has been replaced temporarily by ballet masters Patrice
Bart and Eugene Polyakov, whom Nureyev trained and brought into the
company.
   Controversy is nothing new to Berge, who has never been one to
back down from a public showdown.
   Last year, he fired Daniel Barenboim as director of the new
Opera-Bastille opera house over his high fees and alleged elitist
views on opera.
   Nureyev is not expected to disappear like Barenboim. His
``Sleeping Beauty'' is on the program Dec. 16-31 and his ``Swan
Lake'' can be seen from April 21-May 13, 1990. And as ``premier
choreographer'' he is expected to revive ``La Bayadere'' in time
for next summer.
   Dance afficcionados say that's only fitting for the man who
defected to the West from a Paris airport with the apparent
approval of then-Culture Minister Andre Malraux.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0114 </DOCNO>
