<DOCNO> AP891121-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 9thLd-Writethru a0603 11-21 0993</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 9th Ld - Writethru, a0603,1019</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rebels Storm Luxury Hotel, 4 U.S. Advisers Reported Held</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with OAS chief rescued, details,
White House comment; Picks up 13th graf, `Brown said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed rebels today stormed a
luxury hotel in northern San Salvador and held dozens of foreigners
inside. Four U.S. military advisers were reported captured.
   Soldiers in an armored personnel carrier rescued the secretary
general of the Organization of American States, who had been inside
a different part of the building when the leftist guerrillas
attacked.
   Six government helicopters flew over the homes and tennis club
around the Sheraton Hotel in the wealthy neighborhood of Escalon.
Hundreds of soldiers moved into the area, frequently pinned down by
guerrilla fire.
   The army moved several tanks into the neighborhood to combat the
attackers, who were renewing an urban offensive that had appeared
to be dying out.
   Four U.S. military advisers, and two other advisers, one from
Colombia and one from Guatemala, were captured near the hotel, said
Antonio Hernandez, a spokesman for the rebels' Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front in Mexico City.
   ``They are considered prisoners, but we will respect their lives
and they will not be harmed,'' Hernandez said.
   Cable News Network, quoting an army spokesman, Col. Carlos
Amando Aviles, said four Americans were being held at the hotel.
Aviles did not say whether the Americans were in the military.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeff Brown said he was unable to confirm
the report.
   ``I haven't heard that,'' he said by telephone. ``I don't think
it's true but I can't be sure.''
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
Bush administration was ``making plans as necessary'' to protect
the lives of Americans in the hotel.
   Twenty-nine people, mostly foreigners, were held by the
guerrillas.
   The FMLN asked the government to agree to allow a Red Cross team
to come to the hotel and evacuate guests, aside from the military
advisers, Hernandez said.
   The rebels held a part of the hotel known as the VIP Tower.
Hotel executives and others, including OAS chief Joao Baena Soares,
holed up in an administrative office in the main building.
   Baena Soares, on a peace mission to El Salvador, told the hotel
manager that he wanted to be evacuated with the other guests.
Later, soldiers in an armored personnel carrier drove up to the
front of the main building and evacuated him. It was not
immediately clear whether others were taken with him.
   Brown said the embassy maintained an open line to some of the
Americans in the hotel but said he did not know how many were
there. Fifty-five U.S. military advisers are in El Salvador.
   ``The objective is to take Escalon,'' said a guerrilla who gave
his name as ``Marlon.'' He was in charge of an insurgent position
80 yards from the four-star hotel.
   ``We're taking Escalon because here the armed forces are not
going to bombard people's homes. This is where the oligarchy
lives,'' Marlon said.
   He said his rebel unit had been in Mejicanos, one of several
poor suburbs and neighborhoods where the guerrillas dug in during
their massive offensive last week.
   The fighting ended several days of relative calm in San
Salvador, one target of a rebel offensive launched Nov. 11.
   The new attack comes one day after President Bush reaffirmed his
administration's strong support for the right-wing government of
President Alfredo Cristiani. The United States has provided about
$3.5 billion in the past 10 years to help the government fight the
insurgency.
   A guerrilla official in Mexico City said Monday the offensive
would continue because the fighting had not yet convinced the
government that it cannot win the war. Salvador Samayoa said the
offensive would keep on ``with other surprises bigger than that of
Nov. 11'' until the government is convinced it must make
concessions and begin to negotiate.
   At least 1,000 people have been killed and hundreds if not
thousands rendered homeless in the latest offensive.
   A British journalist, Paul Iredale, was wounded today in the
lower back and taken to the Hospital Rosales. Iredale, a Reuters
reporter based in Mexico City, was later reported in fair condition.
   The fighting followed several explosions and exchanges of rifle
fire in the western sector of the capital at 4:30 a.m.
   The blasts appeared to come from the direction of Merliot, a
suburb where combat flared Monday, or from the slopes of the San
Salvador volcano that looms over the capital's northwestern sector.
   A little less than an hour later, other explosions were heard
echoing from the direction of the volcano and an airplane equipped
with rockets and machine-guns was heard making passes over the
city's outskirts.
   The later blasts appeared to be from heavy munitions, perhaps
120mm government mortars.
   Officials said the rebels had blown up seven of the country's 16
main power lines along with about 40 towers and other equipment.
   The fighting then moved to the area surrounding the Sheraton.
The hotel's coffee shop was the site of the Jan. 3, 1981 slayings
of the president of the Salvadoran Institute of Agrarian Reform and
U.S. AFL-CIO advisers, Michael P. Hammer, 39, of Potomac, Md. and
Mark David Pearlman, 36, of Seattle. Two National Guardsmen were
convicted of murder in the killings, but released in 1988 under an
amnesty given for political crimes.
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker was asked Monday if the raids,
the massacre of six Jesuit priests on Thursday and other incidents
indicated Cristiani was having trouble maintaining control over the
more extreme elements in his rightist government.
   ``Management control problems exist in situations like this,''
said Walker. In Washington, Congress also rejected attempts to
restrict U.S. military aid to Cristiani, heeding an admonition from
Bush not to further weaken a ``freely, democratically elected
government.''
   The decade-long war has claimed more than 71,000 lives, mostly
civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
