<FIRST>r w AM-US-Arafat     11-21 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arafat,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Sends Bush Message About Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has received a message from
Palestine Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat about Middle
East peace talks, the White House said Tuesday.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called it ``a private message'' and
refused to divulge its contents.
   ``The president has received an oral message from Arafat
delivered through the established diplomatic channels in Tunisia,''
Fitzwater said.
   The message went through Ambassador Robert Pelletreau, the U.S.
point man for contacts with the PLO.
   ``We won't reflect on the content of the message. There are no
plans at this time for the president to respond,'' Fitzwater said.
``The situation is not measurably altered. We still have not heard
from the Egyptians on our peace proposal ideas.''
   Israel has accepted _ with some reservations _ Secretary of
State James A. Baker III's five-point plan to promote talks between
the Israelis and Palestinians before an election on the West Bank
and in Gaza.
   The message from Arafat was received ``in the last couple of
days.''
   ``It was a private message and was sent orally in order to keep
it private, and we will maintain that confidence,'' Fitzwater said.
   The United States opened the diplomatic channel to the PLO late
last year after Arafat foreswore terrorism and recognized Israel's
right to exist.

</TEXT>
