<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--FraternitySheep     11-21 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Fraternity Sheep,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge to Pledges: Don't Be Baaaaad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSSINING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen of the 20 college fraternity
pledges who infuriated police by saying nothing but ``Sheep run
north, sir,'' have been told charges will be dropped if they stay
out of trouble for three months.
   The other two did not show up in court on Monday and their cases
were rescheduled.
   The 20 Pace University students were charged with disorderly
conduct Oct. 13 when they refused to tell police what they were
doing at 2 a.m. walking on Route 9A. They would only respond with
the phrase, ``Sheep run north, sir.''
   Members of Delta Kappa Epsilon had driven the pledges,
blindfolded, up near the Croton Dam and dropped them off with no
identification and no money.
   The pledges were ordered to use only the ``sheep'' phrase if
anyone asked them anything. They were walking back to school when
police stopped them.
   All 20 were arrested and given disorderly conduct tickets.
</TEXT>
