<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity     11-21 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Security Chief Vows to `Heal Wounds' At Agency</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 3 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security Commissioner Gwendolyn King on
Tuesday announced a plan to ``calm the turbulence'' in her
discontented workforce to ensure that agency employees provide
quality service to the public.
   In a speech to 14,000 Social Security Administration workers in
the Baltimore area, transmitted by satellite to employees
elsewhere, Mrs. King said morale has suffered in recent years as a
result of massive staff cuts at a time when the Social Security
workload was increasing.
   ``I don't believe we can guarantee the kind of public service we
need to ... unless we first take steps to ensure that our workforce
is energized and focused on our mission,'' she told reporters in a
preview of the speech.
   To her employees, she acknowledged: ``I realize that many of you
feel overworked, that you don't believe your efforts are properly
recognized and that many of you wouldn't recommend SSA employment
to a friend.''
   ``In the weeks and months ahead, I will have no higher priority
than to heal these wounds,'' she said. ``I want to calm the
turbulence and replace uncertainty with stability.''
   The agency's workforce has been slashed by 20 percent to 65,000
over the last six years as part of a campaign to modernize and
streamline operations. Surveys showed increasing numbers of
supervisors felt the agency was doing a poor job of providing top
quality service to the public.
   ``When you combine cutbacks in the size of the agency with
increased public demand for service, turmoil is likely to be the
result,'' Mrs. King told reporters. ``I believe we have to get
beyond that.''
   Mrs. King, who assumed the top Social Security job in August,
proposed a new ``compact'' with her employees. For her part, she
promised to resist further staff cuts, adjust uneven staffing
levels that create shortages in some offices, communicate with
employees in advance of major program changes, provide more
equipment such as computer terminals, and relax unreasonably
demanding job performance standards.
   Employees, meanwhile, were asked to avoid internal strife,
become proficient in new technologies such as computers, take a
greater role in agency decisions and resolve to treat each member
of the public ``as a unique individual and not a case number or a
file.''
   Mrs. King also said additional emphasis would be placed on
outreach programs to needy people who may not be getting the
benefits to which they are entitled, and on efforts to ensure that
only trustworthy people are appointed to handle the Social Security
checks of those who cannot manage their own finances.
</TEXT>
