<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     11-21 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Launch Planned for After Dark Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews worked under a tight schedule
to ready the shuttle Discovery for an after-dark launch Wednesday
with a NASA spokesman predicting the crew would have Thanksgiving
turkey in space.
   Workers made up for time lost on a parts replacement earlier and
Kennedy Space Center spokesman Dick Young said ``from a technical
standpoint we look good and from a weather standpoint we look
good.''
   The launch time is a secret and so is the nature of the military
payload the crew of five is to put into orbit. NASA has said only
that liftoff is set between 6:30 p.m. and 10:30 p.m. EST.
   There is only a 20 percent chance weather will interfere,
forecasters said. If the launch has to be Thursday, the weather
outlook worsens to 60 percent unfavorable.
   The menu released for the mission includes ``thermostabilized''
turkey and gravy, which means the food has enough preservatives to
be carried without refrigeration.
   ``We are hopeful the crew will have Thanksgiving dinner in
space,'' Young said.
   Checking systems and putting the two solid fuel booster rockets
back together had put the schedule in jeopardy. The rockets were
opened last week to inspect computer boxes for faulty wiring and
one box was replaced.
   The flight, commanded by Air Force Col. Frederick C. Gregory, is
the fifth shuttle flight dedicated solely to the Defense
Department. Officials said keeping advance knowledge of the
expected liftoff time secret makes tracking the shuttle more
difficult for Soviet reconnaissance satellites and a spy ship
sitting off Cape Canaveral.
   Announcement of an imminent launch will be made nine minutes
before the event, but there will be no public air-to-ground link
during the mission.
   The cargo is believed to be a satellite capable of monitoring
diplomatic and military communications in the Soviet Union and
other countries.
   The launch will be only the third after nightfall in 32 shuttle
missions and is, like the others, expected to provide a spectacular
sight in this central Florida area. The last night launch, in
November 1985, was visible along the 700 miles from Key West, Fla.,
to Charleston, S.C.
   Gregory, and the pilot Air Force Col. John Blaha, practiced
night landings on the shuttle runway here in a jet equipped to
handle like a shuttle.
   Disovery is scheduled to land at night at Edwards Air Force
Base, Calif., after a flight expected to last four days. Gregory
and Blaha also would have to land the shuttle in the dark here or
at emergency runways in Spain or North Africa in case of an abort
after liftoff.
   Gregory, who flew on a 1985 shuttle mission, is the first black
shuttle commander. The other crew members are Navy Capt. Manley L.
Carter Jr., F. Story Musgrave and Kathryn C. Thornton.
  
</TEXT>
