<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Grant'sSword     11-21 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Grant's Sword,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil War General's Jeweled Sword Auctions For Record $330,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jeweled silver sword belonging to U.S.
President Ulysses S. Grant sold for $330,000, a price auctioneers
called a world record.
   The ceremonial sword given to Grant by friends when he took
command of Union forces in 1864 during the Civil War brought the
highest price ever for such a weapon, said Laura Smissaert,
spokeswoman for auctioneers Butterfield &amp; Butterfield.
   ``It sets the world auction record for an American sword,'' she
said. ``It was a private buyer, you're not going to be seeing it in
a museum next week.''
   The buyer did not want to be identified, she said.
   The chased, or embossed and engraved, silver sword features
inset jewels and a gold plaque bearing Grant's initials set in
diamonds.
   The sword was auctioned Monday at a sale of other Civil War-era
military artifacts that included belongings of another Union Army
general, George Armstrong Custer.
</TEXT>
