<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Commons-TV Bjt   11-21 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commons-TV, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britannia Rules The Airwaves: House of Commons Makes TV Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON5,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a bellow of ``Order! Order!'' the gowned and
bewigged Speaker brought House of Commons lawmakers into line
Tuesday as TV cameras gave Britons their first pictures of their
elected legislators in action.
   Thirty years after first rejecting the notion, the elected
chamber of the Mother of Parliaments finally bowed to the
electronic age as eight remote-control cameras recorded the cut and
thrust of the government and the opposition, seated two sword
lengths and a foot apart.
   At precisely 2:30 p.m., Speaker Bernard Weatherill popped onto
TV screens, resplendent in shoulder-length horsehair wig and black
gown, and called the excited, fidgeting lawmakers to order.
   The first images were broadcast live by two of Britain's four
national networks and the satellite station, Sky Television.
   The honor of giving the first televised speech from the green
leather benches was given to Conservative Ian Gow, a former Cabinet
minister who opposes the cameras and says he doesn't know how to
operate his own VCR.
   But Labor lawmaker Bob Cryer beat him to it with a procedural
interjection during Weatherill's annual recitation of the Sessional
Orders, which remind lawmakers of parliamentary rules and instruct
Scotland Yard to ensure their free access to the Palce of
Westminster.
   Gow said Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher invited him to her
Downing Street residence for a drink on the eve of the first
televised session. ``It seems we were both feeling rather nervous
about our speeches,'' he confessed in a radio interview.
   In her first televised speech, Mrs. Thatcher promised more of
her free-market medicine in 1990. Opposition Labor leader Neil
Kinnock attacked her policies as failures. The debate broke no new
ground, but seeing it on TV gave it an unusual sense of drama.
   Mrs. Thatcher was combative, at times shrill when the opposition
got raucous. Kinnock looked more relaxed.
   The unelected House of Lords has permitted TV broadcasts of its
proceedings since 1985, including the pageantry enveloping Queen
Elizabeth II's ceremonial State Opening of Parliament on Tuesday
morning.
   But the House of Commons, the often-rowdy elected chamber down
the hallway of the Palace of Westminster, steadfastly resisted
until February 1988. It then agreed to a nine-month experiment.
Radio broadcasting was approved in 1978.
   A parliamentary committee drafted strict rules for the cameras,
although the opening broadcasts appeared to be interpreting them
liberally.
   To deter lawmakers from mounting camera-grabbing spectacles, the
broadcasters are supposed to show only the head and shoulders of
whoever is speaking. They are also barred from showing empty
benches, lest viewers get the notion their representatives are
goofing off.
   But several speakers, including Kinnock, were shown from the
waist up as they spoke. The shots were wide enough to show the
facial reactions of several colleagues.
   Screening rowdiness is also taboo. At the first hint of a
disturbance, the cameras are to focus on Weatherill, who is elected
by fellow lawmakers to preside over debates and quell the booing
and braying that often interrupts debate.
   Weatherill, who turns 69 Saturday, is the son of a Savile Row
tailor who still carries a thimble in his pocket because his mother
said it would keep him humble.
   Weatherill approves of the televising, and said Tuesday he hoped
it ``will show the House of Commons at work as it really is.''
   The cameras occasionally switched to wide-angle shots, showing
the 650-member Commons packed to the aisles. The BBC called it a
``historic day,'' while Independent Television News spoke of ``the
newest drama in London's West End.''
   For the uninterested, two other channels offered ``Angel in
Exile,'' a low-budget Western, the drama serial ``Take the High
Road,'' the game show ``Tell the Truth,'' and ``Coronation
Street,'' the popular British soap opera.
   The separation of benches by swords' lengths dates from older
times, when it was feared heated debate might degenerate into
fighting.
   Many lawmakers chose special attire for their TV debut.
Conservative Bill Walker sported his Scots kilt and a Royal Air
Force tie.
   ``Narrow striped shirts have disappeared in favor of blue and
yellow. And the ties have got distinctly brighter this morning,''
said Conservative lawmaker Kenneth Hind.
   ``Hair has been shortened and some of the men ... are carrying
powder puffs in their pockets to beautify their sallow complexions
for the cameras,'' he said.
   Mrs. Thatcher wore her customary blue suit.
</TEXT>
