<FIRST>r i AM-Zaikov     11-21 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zaikov,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zaikov Removed as Moscow Party Boss, Named Deputy Defense Council
Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lev. N. Zaikov, the hard-liner who has served as
the Communist Party boss of Moscow for two years, was replaced
Tuesday to become President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's top deputy on
the Soviet Defense Council.
   Party officials called the move a promotion for Zaikov, who is
also a member of the ruling Soviet Politburo.
   He was succeeded as Moscow party boss by Yuri Prokofiev, 50, who
as second party secretary in the Soviet capital had been Zaikov's
deputy.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said Zaikov, 66, received
the gratitude of the Moscow party committee that voted in plenary
session to replace him, indicating he was leaving in official good
graces.
   According to Tass, Zaikov's departure ``is connected to his
appointment to the post of the first deputy chairman of the Defense
Council of the U.S.S.R.''
   Gorbachev, in his role as president, chairs the Defense Council,
which is responsible for elaborating national defense policy and
whose membership was once top-secret.
   Zaikov will bring to the Defense Council experience in
military-related matters, since he formerly served under Gorbachev
as the party's top official overseeing the defense industry and in
1983-85 as party chief in the Leningrad region, one of the centers
of the Soviet armaments industry.
   He took the helm of the Moscow party organization in November
1987 after his predecessor, maverick politician Boris N. Yeltsin,
was fired in disgrace for criticizing the slow pace of Gorbachev's
reforms.
   One of the most powerful officials in the Communist Party
apparatus, Zaikov has supported the policy of promoting scientific
and technological progress, but has called for limits in the
party's drive for ``glasnost,'' or greater openness.
   This spring, Yeltsin and Zaikov's party apparatus clashed
head-on in the country's first multicandidate elections in seven
decades, with Yeltsin claiming the party was trying to sabotage his
bid to win the Moscow-wide seat in the new Coongress of People's
Deputies.
   Muscovites massively showed their support for Yeltsin, giving
him 89 percent of the vote against the party machine candidate, the
director of a Moscow automobile and truck works.
   A secretary at the party committee in Moscow's Frunze district
rejected a Western reporter's suggestion that Zaikov had been
ousted because of sagging popularity.
   ``Oh no, you can't be more mistaken,'' she said. ``He wasn't
fired. Far from it _ he was promoted.'' A duty officer at city
party headquarters also said Zaikov had received a ``higher
position.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
