<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-RobinHUD 3rdLd-Writethru a0661-a0666 11-21 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robin HUD, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0661-a0666,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Robin HUD' Indicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, with top two grafs new to include attribution
in lead.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Maryland woman who said she stole $5.5
million from the Department of Housing and Urban Development to
give to the poor was indicted today by a federal grand jury in
Baltimore, a court clerk said.
   Marilyn Louise Harrell, who has been dubbed ``Robin HUD,'' was
charged with theft of government property, making false statements
to the federal government, making false statements in connection
with a loan application and aiding and abetting, said the U.S.
District Court clerk in Baltimore.
   The clerk spoke on condition of annoymity.
   The Justice Department planned to announce the indictment
formally later in the day.
   Attempts to reach Harrell's attorney, federal public defender
Anthony Gallagher, were not immediately successful. A receptionist
at his office said Gallagher was in court on an unrelated matter
and not available.
   Prosecutors began presenting evidence to the grand jury not long
after Harrell testified to Congress last June that she withheld the
$5.5 million from HUD while handling the sale of government-owned
property and used some of it to assist charities and the homeless.
   Word of the possible indictment first came Monday when U.S.
Attorney Breckinridge Willcox of Baltimore said he would announce
today a ``major development'' in a HUD case.
   HUD and Justice Department sources, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, had said the announcement would involve the Harrell case
and that prosecutors had asked the grand jury to indict her.
   ``I can't say anything more at this time,'' Willcox said in a
brief telephone conversation Monday evening.
   Meanwhile, a report released Monday by the House Government
Operations Committee said former HUD official June Koch appears to
have repeatedly violated ethics laws by using her government
contacts to help her private business.
   The report urged the Justice Department to investigate Koch, who
was accused of using her influence on HUD officials to benefit the
consulting firm she has headed since leaving HUD two years ago.
   Harrell's testimony to Congress was among the most dramatic
during six months of hearings into allegations of fraud,
mismanagement and political favoritism at HUD during the Reagan
administration.
   Two weeks after she testified, HUD seized her house in
Washington's Maryland suburbs as well as several other properties
she said she purchased with HUD money to help various charities and
homeless families.
   ``I in no way justify what I have done as being anything less
than sin,'' she told a House subcommittee in June. ``I do,
regardless of where my life takes me from here, intend to repay in
full all monies taken.''
   Harrell, who was a private escrow agent hired by HUD to handle
the sales of HUD-owned properties, said she was easily able to
withhold money from the department. Several top officials in HUD's
Washington field office, to which she reported, were fired because
of the Harrell case and other alleged mismanagement.
   Harrell is one of a dozen escrow agents suspected of keeping
some of the money they were supposed to transfer to HUD.
   When she lost her house in late June, Harrell said she was
moving in with her mother in Fort Washington, Md. Attempts to reach
her Monday were unsuccessful; the mother's telephone number is
unlisted.
</TEXT>
