<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     11-21 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assembly Applauds SWAPO Call for Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Namibia's new assembly
joined in applause Tuesday when the dominant party, which espoused
Marxism for two decades, proposed a democratic framework for the
independence constitution.
   SWAPO, the South-West Africa People's Organization, fought a
23-year war against South African rule and won 41 of the 72
constituent assembly seats earlier this month.
   At least 48 members, a two-thirds majority, must approve the
charter written by the assembly.
   Twenty-one seats are held by the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance,
a multiracial coalition that favors a capitalist economy in the
predominantly black territory, and the 10 remaining seats are
distributed among five other parties.
   The assembly met in the Tintenpalast, Namibia's seat of
government since German colonial rulers built it in 1910. South
Africa captured the territory, also known as South-West Africa, in
1915, during World War I.
   Hage Geingob, elected chairman of the assembly, told the opening
session: ``The electorate has given us a mandate to hammer out, and
adopt, in a spirit of compromise, a spirit of give-and-take, a
constitution that will lead our people into nationhood.'' Geingob
was in charge of the SWAPO election campaign.
   Members applauded when Theo-Ben Gurirab, who handles foreign
affairs for SWAPO, proposed that the constitution be based on
democratic principles outlined in a 1982 U.N. document setting up
the procedures for Namibia's transition to independence.
   He offered a motion saying the constitution should be the
supreme law of the land, with specific procedures for amendment,
and Namibia should have an independent judiciary and an elected
executive responsible to the legislative branch.
   Guirab said a declaration of rights should include freedom of
movement, speech and association; a free press; the right to life,
personal liberty and property, and freedom from racial, ethnic,
religious or sexual discrimination.
   His motion could not be adopted because the assembly will not
have rules of order until it meets again on Monday.
   SWAPO espoused Marxist principles during most of its history,
and its stand on democratic principles during the campaign was
vague and contradictory.
   Sam Nujoma, president of SWAPO, told the assembly: ``I'm here
with great humility and pride. Pride, because an occasion like this
only happens once in a lifetime. Humility because I, Sam Nujoma,
son of an ordinary citizen, have been honored to be part of the
struggle that brought us here and to lead us to nationhood.''
   As he and other former guerrilla leaders mounted the steps of
the yellow-and-white colonial government building, Erica Beukes,
one of four protesters, screamed that they were ``killers.''
   She and the others belonged to the Parents' Committee, which has
demanded that SWAPO reveal the fates of more than 400 people it
detained in its foreign camps as spies. A U.N. investigation
concluded more than 100 were dead and no information could be
obtained about 350 others.
   Hundreds of swaying, ululating SWAPO supporters surged around
Nujoma, chanting ``Viva!'' as his bodyguards pushed a path through
the crowd.
   The parties have said they hope the constitution will be
completed by early next year and independence can be declared
shortly afterward.
   Martti Ahtisaari, head of the U.N. team monitoring the
transition, attended the assembly's opening session. He has said he
expects Namibia to become independent before the his group's
scheduled departure at the end of March.
   South Africa governed South-West Africa under a League of
Nations mandate. The United Nations revoked it in 1966, but South
Africa refused to leave and the bush war with SWAPO began for
control of the vast, mineral-rich territory and its 1.5 million
people.
   Earlier this year, South Africa agreed to allow independence
under a U.S.-mediated peace accord that also called for withdrawal
of the 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's northern neighbor.
</TEXT>
