<FIRST>r a AM-BabySwap     11-21 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Swap,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couples' Perseverance Gets Mixed Reaction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBRING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this small community where Ernest and
Regina Twigg live, friends understand but strangers question why
the parents of seven persevered until they proved a 10-year-old
stranger was their daughter.
   ``The folks who know us, our friends, have been real supportive.
Some of the people who work with me for Amtrak have called to say,
`We're with you,''' Twigg said.
   ``But others wonder why we're pursuing this, why we couldn't
just let it drop. I guess you'd have to be a parent to know why,''
he said from the Amtrak station where he's a ticket agent.
   Twigg went back to work Monday, after lawyers went public with
the news that genetic tests showed two families had raised the
other's child. The Twiggs say their real daughter is Kimberly Mays
of Sarasota who was switched in a hospital nursery with the child
they took home a decade ago. That child, Arlena, died last year of
heart disease.
   The girls were born just days apart at Hardee Memorial Hospital
in the rural central Floriday city of Wauchula in the fall of 1978.
   Test results released Sunday found a 99.9 percent chance that
Kimberly Mays is actually a Twigg, and a 98.9 percent chance that
Arlena Twigg was the daughter of Robert Mays and his wife, Barbara,
who died of cancer in 1981.
   Mays has not commented since the test results were released. He
is expected to attend a news conference at his attorney's office in
Sarasota on Wednesday.
   Lee Salk, a Cornell University Medical College professor of
psychology, said the revelation triggers a common fear.
   ``This affects us all,'' he said. ``It brings out the `Were we
switched?' fear. I imagine it will kick up anxiety in other
children.''
   Salk was one of seven child psychologists or psychiatrists asked
by Mays' attorney to state what effect the Twiggs' effort to
ascertain biological parenthood would have on Kimberly. In 1988,
all seven said that pursuing the case would be harmful to the
10-year-old.
   Some or all of them may be called by the court to help recommend
a visitation plan between the Twiggs and Kimberly. The Twiggs
agreed not to seek custody of Kimberly in an agreement with Mays
that allowed the genetic testing.
   The likely effects psychologists cited range from shattering the
security of Kimberly's relationship with the man who reared her, to
causing depression, anxiety, anger or confusion and a sense of loss.
   Salk expressed dismay Monday that the search was pursued.
   The Twiggs sued Hardee Memorial in September in U.S. District
Court in Tampa. Mays' attorney, Arthur Ginsburg, said he would
recommend that Mays also consider suing.
   The Twiggs' lawsuit alleges a baby swap resulted from medical
malpractice, neglect or deliberate acts and asks a jury to decide.
   Hardee Memorial has asked that the lawsuit be dismissed on
technical grounds.
   The hospital's lawyer, Janet Adams, said Florida's statute of
limitations requires patients to file malpractice claims within
four years. Since the alleged swap occurred in 1978, she said, it's
too late.
   But another attorney for the Twiggs, Bill Post, said the ``clock
did not start ticking'' until the Twiggs knew that Arlena was not
their child.
</TEXT>
