<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Books     11-21 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Books,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Esquire Sends 34 Books to President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush doesn't have to worry about a
dearth of good books to curl up with in front of the fireplace this
winter.
   Esquire magazine has shipped off 34 books picked for the
president by the 1989 Esquire Register Honorees.
   There's something for every mood, from the Bible, picked by
Oprah Winfrey, to the Robert Mapplethorpe catalog from the art show
that touched off a political firestorm over government funding of
art.
   Actor Billy Crystal picked Erich Segal's ``Love Story,'' because
``Bush could get out of it how much they cared for each other. It's
so sad that they're not together. Plus, it's short, he can get
right back to business.''
   Bush is getting a variety of historical tomes, including
``Roots,'' by Alex Haley, picked by Chicago Bulls star Michael
Jordan, and ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X,'' courtesy of
filmmaker Spike Lee.
   Randy Shilts' chronicle of the AIDS crisis, ``And the Band
Played On,'' was picked by two of the honorees.
   W. Keith Hefner, founder and executive director of the
non-profit Youth Communication-New York Center, named the newsroom
classic, ``The Elements of Style,'' by Strunk and White.
   ``I'd like him to correct his broken syntax,'' Hefner said.
   If he's thinking about getting a cat to curl with him by the
fire, he can thank country music star Lyle Lovett for ``You and
Your Cat,'' by David Taylor.
   ``I got this book when I first got my cat,'' Lovett said. ``I'd
never had a cat, didn't know anything about it. In spite of my
total inexperience, the cat's fine because of this book.''
   Should nothing in the entire pile suit his taste, however, he
can look forward to receiving one more.
   Actress Michelle Pfeiffer's response to Esquire's question was:
``Let me think about that and I'll get back to you.''
</TEXT>
