<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-HHS 1stLd-Writethru a0663 11-21 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-HHS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill Shorn of Abortion-Financing Provision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs, `Pretty cute,...' to CORRECT name to McBride,
sted McNulty. Picks up 14th graf pvs `The dog ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday signed a $157
billion labor, health and education appropropriations bill shorn of
language that would have liberalized Medicaid financing for
abortions.
   Bush had vetoed an earlier version of the bill in a battle with
Congress over abortion financing.
   In a statement, the president praised Congress for bowing to his
insistence that Medicaid fund abortions only to save the life of
the mother.
   The bill originally would have allowed Medicaid to pay for
abortions for poor women who had been raped or were the victims of
incest. Bush said the provision ``would have deprived innocent,
unborn children of the most basic civil right, the right to life.''
   He said the massive spending bill for the departments of Labor,
Education and Health and Human Services, plus related agencies,
will finance ``some of the nation's most important programs _
programs that help the needy, the unemployed, the sick and the
infirm, and programs that provide for the education of American
children.''
   He noted that the legislation includes nearly $1.6 billion to
combat the deadly AIDS virus and $5.4 billion for remedial
education for disadvantaged students.
   Bush, surrounded by 13 children, also signed a proclamation
declaring this National Adoption Week.
   Bush, who has sought to spur adoption as an alternative to
abortion, said each of the 50,000 children adopted in the United
States a year repay their new families a hundredfold.
   But he said thousands more children still wait to be adopted,
many of them with special needs.
   Bush recently asked Congress to pass legislation giving parents
a $3,000 tax deduction to help cover the costs of adopting children
with disabilities or other special needs.
   He shook hands and asked the names of each child, recognizing at
least one boy from an earlier adoption ceremony, then expressed
regret that first dog Millie was not allowed into the ceremonial
rooms.
   Mrs. Bush, putting her husband's thought into action, took care
of that.
   ``Pretty cute kids, I'll tell you,'' said the first lady. She
instructed Tim McBride, the president's personal aide, to let the
dog in, and in a flash Millie ran into the Roosevelt Room.
   The dog raced in, ran around the kids and raced out. Mrs. Bush
called her back and hoisted her up for a girl in a wheelchair to
pet.
   ``That's all for Millie. Goodbye!'' said Mrs. Bush, as the pet
trotted off.
</TEXT>
