<DOCNO> AP891121-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Storm-School     11-21 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Storm-School,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Back at Tornado-Damaged School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children, many clutching their parents'
hands, returned Tuesday to their storm-damaged school where seven
classmates died last week, as tornado-stricken Coldenham continued
to heal with unexpected help.
   The morning mail was filled with donations again Tuesday at the
Coldenham Fire Department. Donors, some anonymous, have given
$61,000 to help families after the tornado, which also injured 18
at the school, said Bud Black, assistant fire chief.
   Children have walked into the firehouse with coffee cans filled
with change and one man anonymously donated about $5,000 in
quarters, Black said. All firefighters know was that the man's
vehicle had New Jersey license plates, he said.
   ``It's great,'' he said. ``It's something a little bit to the
positive side.''
   Classes were held at East Coldenham Elementary School for the
first time since the tornado hit Thursday at lunchtime and blew in
the glass and concrete cafeteria wall. Parents brought children in
for counseling Monday to make the first day back less jarring.
   With a cold northwest wind shaking a flagpole and violently
flapping the flag, few parents and children paused in front of the
boarded-up cafeteria wall. Flowers remained piled against the wood
that has replaced shattered glass and bricks.
   The school is trying to get back to something like normal
operations before Thanksgiving, said Robert Schoonmaker, assistant
superintendent for the Valley Central school district.
   Rooms were set aside at the school for children and adults to
grieve and counselors remained on hand, officials said. Students
went back to school Monday at the district's other six schools.
   Coldenham firefighters have taken toy fire engines and other
playthings to children still hospitalized, Black said. Eleven are
still in the hospital, with two in criltical condition and one
fair. The rest were in good or satisfactory conditon Tuesday.
   ``We've visited every child and brought them gifts and it is as
much for our therapy as theirs,'' he said.
   Firefighters began getting donations even before they thought to
set up a memorial fund, Black said. A committee was hurriedly set
up to allocate the money, which will be used partly for hospital
and funeral fees for the stricken families, he said. The last five
funerals were Monday.
   The fund also will be used to pay expenses for Rosalie Sbordone,
the eighth East Coldenham student to die in the last week. Sbordone
died Monday from injuries suffered in an auto accident Sunday a few
hundred yards from the school's entrance.
   Her parents, Neil and Virginia Sbordone, have donated the
5-year-old girl's organs for transplant.
   ``She's going to live on in someone else,'' Virginia Sbordone
said. ``Other children are going to live because of her. Some other
grieving family is going to have joy because of her.''
</TEXT>
