<FIRST>r a AM-ChildrenSlain     11-21 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Slain,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Charged in Shotgun Slayings of Two Young Sons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIDDEFORD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas man being sought in the
abduction of his two young sons was arraigned on murder charges
Tuesday after he walked into a county jail and told a receptionist
he had killed the boys.
   Roy Irwin Abbott Sr., 52, of Denton, Texas, was ordered held
pending a bail hearing Nov. 29. No plea was entered.
   According to affidavit by state police Detective William Gomane,
Abbott said at the York County Jail: ``I need to see a police
officer. I've killed my kids.''
   Abbott told police he used a 12-gauge shotgun to kill the boys
Monday and left the weapon in the back of his car, Gomane said.
Authorities said the shotgun was recovered.
   Authorities found the boys' bodies, both with gunshot wounds, on
a dirt road in a wooded area near Silver Lake in Shapleigh, Maine,
state police said.
   Abbott, a Maine native, and the boys apparently had been staying
without permission at a Silver Lake cottage owned by Abbott's
brother, Benjamin Abbott, of Portsmouth, N.H., said state police
Sgt. Michael Harriman.
   Abbott made no comments to reporters as he entered the
courthouse.
   His court-appointed lawyer, Stephen J. Schwartz of Portland, had
little to say. ``I haven't even had the opportunity to discuss the
full set of facts with my client,'' he said.
   On Sept. 1, Abbott's divorce from Maria Louisa Abbott, 40, of
Denton, became final and he took custody of his sons for the Labor
Day weekend, Denton Police Capt. Bill Cummings said. Abbott was
supposed to return the boys on Sept. 4 but did not.
   Their mother contacted police the next day; a kidnapping warrant
was issued on Oct. 16.
   Abbott told police he had planned to turn himself in on the
Texas charge Monday but then shot his sons when they began crying
and did not want to go home, officers said.
   ``He started into town to turn himself in. They started crying,
and he shot them,'' Cummings said.
   Spokesman Stephen McCausland of the Maine Department of Public
Safety identified the older boy as Roy Irwin Abbott Jr., 6. Maine
officials identified the younger boy as Ronney Abbott, 4, but Texas
authorities identified the younger boy as Rooney Abbott. Neither
agency was able to explain the discrepancy Tuesday.
   Autopsies Tuesday revealed that the boys died of gunshot wounds
to the head and chest, Harriman said, adding that each boy was shot
twice at close range.
   Authorities said they believe Abbott came to the Portsmouth area
around Sept. 4 and that he worked briefly at a department store
there before taking the boys to Canaan, Maine.
   Abbott enrolled the older boy in Canaan Christian School in late
October for about two weeks, then moved to Yarmouth where he worked
at a dry cleaning business from Nov. 6 to Nov. 8, Harriman said.
   The sergeant said authorities searched for Abbott in Augusta,
Eliot, Kittery and Portsmouth. ``Each time we checked these
locations, there was another move on his part, indicating he was
aware he was being hunted.''
   Cummings said Texas authorities would likely wait for Maine
officials to finish legal proceedings before seeking an extradition
on kidnapping charges.
</TEXT>
