<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush-Xmas,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Continues Christmas Tradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush will help place the
main ornament atop the National Christmas Tree again this year,
continuing a ceremonial string she began in 1981 as the vice
president's wife.
   Mrs. Bush and 3-year-old granddaughter Marshall Bush will ride a
hydraulic lift Monday to place the ornament atop the 38-foot living
tree on the Ellipse across from the White House.
   Joseph Riley, president of the Christmas Pageant of Peace Inc.,
will join in the tree topping.
   ``This year marks the first time in the pageant's 35-year
history that a first lady has helped with this tradition,'' Mrs.
Bush's press office noted in a release.
   ``They asked her last year if she wanted to continue to do it
and she said, `You bet!''' said press aide Sondra Haley.
   President and Mrs. Bush will light the tree Dec. 14, continuing
a tradition begun by President Calvin Coolidge in 1923.
