<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     11-21 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Parties Agree on Interim Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Greece's three main parties
reached agreement Tuesday for an all-party, interim government to
end the stalemate that followed inconclusive elections on Nov. 5.
   ``The three parties agreed to support a government whose life
term will last until mid-April,'' conservative leader Constantine
Mitsotakis told a news conference.
   The decision to hold general elections in April follows four
rounds of talks between conservative, socialist and communist
leaders with President Christos Sartzetakis.
   Mitsotakis said the interim administration will be headed by
Xenophon Zolotas, an economist and former governor of the Bank of
Greece. Zolotas is not a member of Parliament.
   The government will include members of all parties and also
non-political personalities, Mitsotakis said, but composition of
the Cabinet has not been decided.
   He said the administration's first tasks will be to deal with
economic problems and negotiations with the United States on
whether to renew an agreement for U.S. bases in Greece.
   In Washington, the State Department said the United States looks
forward to working with the new government and will raise the
question of the status of the U.S. bases once a Cabinet is formed.
   It issued a statement saying, ``We believe it is in the interest
of both countries to continue a strong bilateral security
relationship. We will look for a mutually satisfactory way to do
so.''
   Talks between the party leaders had been deadlocked over a
demand by former socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou that the
electoral system be changed.
   His proposed change involving the proportional representation
system would have made it even more difficult for any party to win
a majority in the 300-member unicameral Parliament. Under the
present system if one party receives at least 47 percent of the
vote it can govern alone.
   Mitsotakis, whose New Democracy Party won 46 percent of the vote
and 148 parliamentary seats in November, rejected the proposal. He
said the April elections will be conducted under the present
electoral system.''
   Papandreou governed for eight years until the formation of a
conservative-communist alliance in June after elections that also
failed to give any party a majority.
   His party won 128 seats in November and the communist-led
Coalition of the Left and Progress led by Harilaos Florakis won 21.
Two seats went to independents and one to an environmentalist.
   Zolotas, 85, headed the nation's central bank for almost 20
years while conservatives were in power.
   The premier-designate is not a member of any political party and
has never run for Parliament.
   Zolotas served as Bank of Greece governor from 1955-67 and from
1974-81. He acquired a reputation as a pragmatist for maintaining
tight economic policies to offset Greece's trade deficit.
   A socialist party official who was close to the negotiations
that produced the compromise agreement said Zolotas was proposed by
Mitsotakis and ``accepted without any objections.''
</TEXT>
