<FIRST>r w AM-Darman-Budget     11-21 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Darman-Budget,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Director Hopes Deficit Agreement Means Good Relations With
Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Budget Director Richard Darman
said he hopes Tuesday's deficit reduction agreement means more
cooperation than confrontation with Congress next year on budget
issues.
   Darman said the deficit cutting package was made possible by
President Bush's insistence that he was willing to accept
across-the-board spending cuts rather than tolerate a 1990 budget
which met the Gramm-Rudman deficit targets through accounting
gimmicks.
   The $14.7 billion deficit cutting package was agreed to in
post-midnight negotiations as members of Congress rushed to
complete their work before the Thanksgiving holidays.
   Darman said the measure was ``far better than anyone thought
likely'' on Nov. 2 when Bush issued his ultimatum that he wanted to
see at least $14 billion in real deficit reductions or he was
prepared to live with across-the-board spending cuts.
   The director of the Office of Management and Budget, however,
warned members of Congress not to try to make changes in the
agreement in passing the necessary implementing legislation. He
said any such changes could still prompt a presidential veto.
   ``If they do not follow the agreement, then there will not be a
deal,'' Darman said in a meeting with reporters.
   The deficit-reduction package, Darman said, should get Congress
and the administration back to where they were last spring when
both sides reached a much-heralded budget pact. That agreement
dissolved into bitter partisan fighting over Bush's efforts to
slash capital gains tax rates.
   ``This can get us back on a path of bipartisanship and put this
recent period of partisan debate behind us,'' Darman said, adding
that the challenge of meeting the deficit-reduction target of $64
billion in 1991 was sizable.
   The administration is preparing its 1991 budget to be submitted
in January, but Darman turned aside questions about what will be in
that package.
   He did say the administration would be proposing cuts in
entitlement programs to meet the deficit targets.
   He also said that he would consider increases in alcohol and
tobacco taxes among the revenue increases that would be prohibited
under the president's no-new taxes campaign pledge. But he added
that he doesn't drink or smoke and said, ``I don't believe either
of those should be encouraged.''
   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that a Bush
administration task force is considering proposals to raise the
federal tax on tobacco and liquor and impose new taxes on polluters
and use the revenues raised to underwrite the cost to the
government of offering individuals new tax breaks to encourage
savings.
   Darman said he believed that the budget deficit, which totaled
$152.1 billion in the fiscal year which ended on Sept. 30, had now
been stabilized at a sustainable level withthe new deficit cutting
agreement for the current fiscal year.
   ``There isn't the sense of erosion or lack of control that I had
in the 1980s,'' Darman said, referring to his years of service in
the Reagan administration. The budget deficit hit a record of
$221.1 billion in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
