<FIRST>r w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0611 11-21 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Next Panama Coup Attempt Will be Bloody</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs new material.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior member of the House Armed Services
Committee said Tuesday that Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
has executed ``probably more than 100'' officers and troops since a
failed Oct. 3 coup.
   ``As a result, there cannot be a chivalrous coup d'etat in the
future. The next batch of coup plotters won't be interested in
handing Noriega over to us or dispatching him into exile,'' said
Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo.
   ``Noriega has changed the ground rules. So the next coup will be
bloody.''
   The purge, Skelton said, amounts to 3 percent of the men in the
Panamanian Defense Force.
   Skelton's comments came a day after his Defense Policy Panel
received a closed-door, top-secret briefing from Gen. Maxwell
Thurman, chief of the U.S. Southern Command, based in Panama.
   Skelton said Noriega had killed ``more than 70 and probably more
than 100 officers and men of the Panama Defense Force.''
   ``Before October, coups in Panama were essentially bloodless. If
you lost a coup, you lost your job _ but not your life. Noriega has
changed all that,'' Skelton said in a statement.
   The result is that any new coup attempt, ``if successful, will
do little that we want except eliminate Noriega, which will
probably happen in a manner we do not wish to be associated with,''
Skelton said.
   ``Whoever wins lives, and whoever loses will die. That's the
game we're in now,'' he said.
   Intelligence sources have said that, in the wake of the failed
coup, the Central Intelligence Agency has received congressional
clearance for a new covert plan that would spend up to $3 million
to depose Noriega. The plan would permit aiding coup plotters, even
if violence were likely, as long as the plot did not include plans
for assassination.
   A longstanding executive order bars U.S. operatives from
participating in any plot to assassinate a foreign leader.
   Skelton said he was satisfied that the likelihood Noriega could
die in a later coup does not necessarily represent an impediment to
U.S. involvement.
   ``A death involved in a coup is different from an out-and-out
assassination attempt,'' he said.
   Noriega's purge has left a ``concentration of thugs'' in the
PDF, which lessens the chances that any new coup would lead to a
restoration of democracy and elimination of drug trafficking and
money laundering, Skelton said.
   The coup attempt occurred during Thurman's first week as the new
chief of Southcom, and Skelton was among the harshest congressional
critics of U.S. failure to give full support to the rebels led by
Maj. Moises Giroldi.
   But after Thurman's briefing, Skelton said it was clear that the
coup attempt was flawed because it was based on the ``irrational
premise'' that Noriega would agree to retire to his farm in Panama,
and because the rebels wouldn't turn Noriega over to U.S.
authorities, would not have restored democracy and probably would
have continued Noriega's drug operations.
   At the Pentagon, a spokeswoman, Maj. Kathy Wood, said security
has been tightened at U.S. defense sites in Panama because of bomb
threats.
   Wood said that the first such threat was made about a week ago
and that the new security steps have been in effect for nearly a
week's time.
   ``It means that they are inspecting cars more carefully, and
that some parking lots have been closed if they are within 75
meters of buildings,'' Wood said.
   U.S. personnel are acting under personnel movement limitations
that require them to keep others advised of their movements, to
exercise caution and to avoid any known trouble areas, Wood said.
</TEXT>
