<SECOND>AM-Bush-FCC,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Johnson Aide Gets Nod for FCC Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate Ervin S. Duggan,
a one-time aide to President Johnson and speechwriter for Joseph
Califano, as a member of the Federal Communications Commission, the
White House announced Tuesday.
   Duggan, 50, is a published novelist who has run his own
communications consulting business in Washington since 1981. He was
national editor of Washingtonian magazine from 1981-86.
   Duggan would succeed Patricia Diaz Dennis if confirmed by the
Senate.
   Duggan was a staff assistant to Johnson from 1965-69, and was
special assistant to Califano during his tenure as secretary of the
old Department of Health, Education and Welfare.
   He also worked in the State Department in the final two years of
the Carter administration, and served as a special assistant to
former Sen. Adlai Stevenson III, D-Ill., from 1971-77.
   Duggan, of Bethesda, Md., is national chairman of Presbyterians
for Democracy and Religious Freedom.
   Bush also announced Tuesday he will retain Bill D. Colvin as
inspector general of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
