<FIRST>r i AM-India-Elections-Glance     11-21 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Elections-Glance,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Elections at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts and figures on India's
parliamentary elections:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE VOTING _ Voting begins Wednesday, when 221 constituencies go
to the polls; 266 go to the polls on Friday and 37 on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE VOTERS _ There are 498 million registered voters. The
government last year lowered the voting age from 21 to 18, adding
about 35 million people to the electorate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE SEATS _ The winners of the elections will enter the Lok
Sabha or House of the People, the decision-making lower house of
Parliament. The house has 545 members, of whom two are nominated.
Elections are not being held for 14 seats in the northeastern state
of Assam because voters' lists have not been completed. But there
will be voting in only 524 constituencies. Elections in four
constituencies have been postponed because of the deaths of
candidates; in another constituency, one candidate ran unopposed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE CANDIDATES _ There are 6,090 candidates, including at least
4,000 independents. Candidates are also from eight national
parties, 33 state parties and 251 other parties. The Congress Party
of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi is fielding 509 candidates. The
National Front, an opposition coalition, is up for 314 seats. In
most constituencies, the front has agreed not to oppose candidates
of the the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party, which is fielding 226
candidates, the Communist Party of India (53 candidates) and the
Communist Party-Marxist (64 candidates.) However, the left parties
and the right-wing group will oppose each other.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   KEY ISSUES _ The Congress Party, which won an unprecedented 415
seats in the last election in 1984, is beset by opposition charges
of corruption. Opinion polls say it may lose its majority. The
governing party has campaigned this year on a platform of past
performances and continuing stability in government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   COUNTING _ Counting of votes begins Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PREVIOUS ELECTION _ In 1984, the Congress Party won 415 seats,
the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party 2, the centerist Janata
(People's) Party 10, the centerist Lok Kranti Dal (People's
Revolutionary Party) 3, the Communist Party of India 6, the
Communist Party-Marxist 22, the Congress Party-Socialist five,
major state parties 59, smaller parties 16 and independents five.
In the current election, the Janata Party, the Lok Kranti Dal, the
Congress-Socialist and three of the larger state parties have
formed the National Front coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
