<FIRST>r w AM-Radar-Planes     11-21 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radar-Planes,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Concludes Powerful Radar Threatens All Aircraft At Georgia
Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has concluded that a powerful
radar system built to detect submarine-launched missiles off the
southeastern United States poses a potential risk to virtually all
military aircraft landing at Robins Air Force Base in central
Georgia.
   The conclusion was disclosed Tuesday in a letter made public by
Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the Senate Armed Services Committee chairman
who last year asked the Air Force to assess the danger posed to
aircraft by the PAVE PAWS radar installation two miles south of the
Robins airfield.
   PAVE PAWS stands for Precision Acquisition Vehicle Entry Phased
Array Warning System. The 10-story, pyramid shaped installation at
Robins, one of four such facilities nationwide, consists of
thousands of computer-directed antennas that can scan 240 degrees
for 3,000 miles. The radar reportedly can identify an object the
size of a basketball 1,500 miles away.
   The Air Force acknowledged in January that since 1987, it has
been turning off the north face of the radar every time a plane
carrying an externally mounted electroexplosive device (EED) lands
at Robins.
   The shut-downs are designed to keep the radar's electromagnetic
radiation from accidentally detonating the EEDs, the tiny explosive
charges that are used, among other things, to trigger weapons
systems and ejection seats, or jettison bombs and fuel tanks.
   The explosive devices normally are detonated by an electrical
circuit, but they also can be set off high levels of
electromagnetic energy from such sources as radio waves, radar
emissions, static electricity and lightning.
   In the letter to Nunn, Brig. Gen. Burton R. Moore said an Air
Force review of the problem has concluded that the radar poses a
potential risk to aircraft with internal EEDs, such as those used
to power ejection seats, as well as to aircraft with the devices
mounted externally.
   ``It would look like most aircraft would probably have internal
EEDs of one sort or another,'' Lt. Col. Joseph W. Purka Jr., an Air
Force spokesman, said Tuesday.
   Purka said the north face of the radar now is turned off when
any plane enters the one-nautical mile restricted zone around the
facility.
   Purka said there was ``no incident that triggered'' the decision
to begin shutting down the radar for some planes.
   Moore told Nunn the shut-down procedures ``will have a minimal
impact'' on missile warning operations.
   The Air Force convened a panel of senior generals in January to
develop a permanent solution to the problem. The panel was supposed
to have finished its work by June, but Purka said Tuesday the group
recommended this month that the temporary shutdown procedures
remain in effect for another year while further study is done.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
