<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Culture     11-21 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Culture,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foe of Censorship Named Culture Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film and theater director who opposes censorship
was named culture minister Tuesday by the Soviet legislature, which
had rejected Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov's nominee.
   ``The ministry should not allow or ban; it should expand the
possibilities of workers in art,'' the new minister, Nikolai
Gubenko, was quoted as saying by the official news agency Tass.
   Only eight votes were cast against Gubenko in the 542-seat
Supreme Soviet legislature, according to Tass.
   Last summer, the lawmakers refused to reconfirm Vasily Zakharov
as culture minister, as Ryzhkov had wanted, and the post was vacant
until Gubenko was elected.
   Tass reported that in his statement to the legislature, Gubenko
said he will seek to create a climate fostering creativity, provide
legal protection against officialdom and dismantle restrictions on
creative work.
   For the past two years, the 48-year-old Gubenko has served as
chief director of Moscow's Taganka Theater.
   In the 1960s, Gubenko made his debut in that theater, which
under then-director Yuri Lyubimov became one of Moscow's most
politically progressive and provocative stages.
   Gubenko also has directed many feature films.
</TEXT>
