<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-DeathSquads     11-21 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Death Squads,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Requests Death Squad Report; Papers Demand Independent Inquiry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President F.W. de Klerk asked
for an official report on alleged killings by police death squads,
but newspapers demanded Tuesday that an independent inquiry be
conducted.
   Casper Venter, spokesman for De Klerk, said the president told
Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok last week to provide a
``detailed, in-depth'' report on the allegations that opponents of
the government have been assassinated.
   ``This may satisfy the president, but it will not satisfy anyone
else,'' said The Star, the nation's largest daily. Its editorial
was one of many demanding an inquiry by someone outside the
official establishment.
   ``Only a full-scale, open judicial inquiry can clear the air,''
said the paper, which often opposes the government. ``Without it,
the stain on South Africa will be indelible.''
   Three former policemen, including a white captain, have said
they took part in the killings on orders from superiors.
   A former police commissioner, a ranking officer investigating
the bombing of an anti-apartheid church organization and other high
officers still in service were named by former Capt. Dirk Johannes
Coetzee during an interview in Mauritius last week, after he left
South Africa.
   ``It is neither right, nor fair to the police, to appoint the
head of the (internal affairs division) to investigate such
horrendous and politically explosive allegations against his own
colleagues,'' the Cape Times newspaper said.
   That official and a provincial attorney general were appointed
to investigate when the charges first arose in an affidavit by a
black former security policeman.
   Butane Nofomela, scheduled to hang Oct. 20 for the murder of a
white farmer in a case with no apparent political overtones,
summoned lawyers the night before and signed a statement that
Coetzee was his superior in a death squad that killed political
activists, prisoners and African National Congress guerrillas.
   He has been granted a stay of execution while his allegations
are checked. Investigators did not get in touch with Coetzee, who
was given a medical discharge from the police in 1986, and he left
the country more than two weeks later.
   Last weekend, newspapers quoted black former policeman David
Tshikalange as saying he also was part of a police death squad and
had left the country.
   ``It is essential that the truth comes to light. There should
not be a scrap of suspicion about the police being neutral in its
duty of keeping law and order,'' said Die Burger, an Afrikaans
language paper that supports the government.
   Business Day, the leading financial daily, commented: ``The
credibility of the police has simply collapsed. The general public
reaction to the ... allegations has been that, given the secrecy in
which the police operate and the accumulation of unsolved murder
cases in which the victims have been opponents of the government,
an assassination squad might well have existed.'' Nofomela's
statement focused mainly on the killing in 1982 of Griffiths
Mxenge, a black lawyer and civil rights activist. He and Coetzee
said Mxenge was stabbed to death in an attack made to look like a
robbery, his dogs were poisoned and his car was taken away and
burned.
   In parts of the statement obtained Tuesday by the independent
South African Press Association, Nofomela said a radio-tape deck
was removed from Mxenge's car before it was destroyed and was
installed in a police vehicle used by Brig. Willem Schoon.
   Both Nofomela and Coetzee said Schoon ordered the killing, and
Nofomela said the brigadier supervised several squads that carried
out assassinations and other crimes in South Africa and neighboring
countries.
   Schoon has refused to talk to the press. Police headquarters in
Pretoria issued a statement Tuesday saying his retirement Oct. 31
had been planned since July and was not related to the allegations.
   Dozens of killings of anti-apartheid activists in the 1980s
remain unsolved and human rights groups have said for years they
believed security forces were responsible.
</TEXT>
