<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Canada     11-21 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Canada,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missionary Denounces U.S., Canadian Aid to Rightist Gov't</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lutheran minister on Tuesday
criticized U.S. and Canadian aid to El Salvador, where he directed
an orphanage until his arrest by Salvadoran security forces.
   The Rev. Brian Rude said he planned a speaking tour to address
the suffering of many Salvadorans, who resent the foreign
assistance to the rightist government of President Alfredo
Cristiani.
   ``Certainly the preference there would be that it (aid) be
discontinued and that the Salvadorans be allowed to resolve their
problems without what they see as that kind of interference,'' Rude
told a news conference hours after his return to Calgary.
   The United States has provided $3.5 billion in aid to battle the
decade-old insurgency, and Canada has a $12 million program that
aids farmers.
   Rude, 33, worked in an orphanage outside San Salvador for a year
and was also caring for people wounded or displaced by fighting
between government troops and leftist rebels.
   He was among a dozen Lutheran missionaries arrested Thursday by
Salvadoran security forces in a government crackdown on people
suspected of leftist sympathies.
   The arrests came hours after six Jesuit priests, their
housekeeper and her 15-year-old daughter were mutilated and slain.
Roman Catholic officials blamed right-wing death squads, and the
United States said it would pressure Cristiani to fully investigate
the slayings.
   The slight Lutheran minister spent a night blindfolded and
handcuffed in a jail before his release. He returned to Calgary
late Monday to the cheers of friends and family.
   Rude, who was originally scheduled to return to Calgary in
December, said he will go on a speaking tour to tell the stories
that are not getting out.
   ``I feel disconnected. Even while I was there listening to news
reports from other parts of the world over shortwave I realized
that a lot of the information going out wasn't necessarily the way
we were experiencing it.''
   The minister said he was concerned Canadian aid was not being
distributed properly.
   ``There is some potential for the aid to be used in positive
ways, but I think if it were channelled more directly through
churches it could be used in a better way than it is being used,''
he said.
   Since 1986, the Canadian International Development Agency has
sent more than $12 million to the country in fertilizer that is
sold by a local bank on the open market. The proceeds are used for
special projects.
   ``I feel the aid we offer as a Canadian government _ even though
it's not directed through the Salvadoran government _ does offer
some legitimacy to the government of El Salvador which can be
interpreted in the wrong way.''
   More than 1,000 people have died since the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front launched a nationwide offensive Nov. 11.
At least 71,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed in the
insurgency.
</TEXT>
