<FIRST>u w AM-Pentagon-Budget     11-21 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Budget,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Uncertain of Effect of Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional passage of a deficit reduction
package is expected to force a 1.5 percent budget cut on defense
spending for this fiscal year, but the Pentagon spokesman said
Tuesday the precise effect is unclear.
   ``What that translates into in terms of people, and systems ...
we are not prepared to say,'' said Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams.
   While saying that the impact could be ``$6 or $7 billion,''
Williams added that Pentagon officials are not yet able to estimate
the exact magnitude of the cuts under the complicated features of
the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit reduction law.
   The figure is widely expected to be at least several billion
dollars, at least.
   Although Congress approved a $286 billion defense budget for the
1990 fiscal year that began Oct. 1, President Bush has not yet
signed it into law.
   Williams said it is difficult to determine the exact nature of
the impact of the cuts, because different rules may apply to
various DOD accounts under the budget reduction law.
   ``It's very hard to know precisely what the impact would be. But
we think it would be about a 1.5 percent recutive for the Defense
Department over four months,'' Williams said.
   Had the terms of the Gramm-Rudman law been fully enforced over a
year's time defense programs would have to be pared by $8 billion,
or half the $16 billion spending reductions the law would have
automatically imposed on most federal programs.
   Bush stated repeatedly in recent weeks that he preferred
retaining the across-the-board cuts for a full year to accepting
congressional efforts to reduce the deficit, which he said
contained phony savings.
   Pentagon officials had warned of severe cutbacks in military
personnel and weapons acquisition if the Gramm-Rudman cuts had been
left in place the entire year.
   On Capitol Hill, lawmakers ran into last-minute delays in
beginning debate on the $14.7 billion budget-cutting bill for the
current fiscal year.
   The bill relies heavily on across-the-board cuts triggered last
month by the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law, a mechanism
designed to shrink federal spending.
   Williams said that Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and his top
aides are also in the final stages of ``putting together some final
numbers'' for the department's 1991 fiscal year budget.
   Department sources said the secretary is considering a cut
ranging from $10 billion to $20 billion for the next year, bringing
the level down to the range of around $297 billion.
   The spokesman refused to confirm those figures, saying with a
laugh, ``I've heard numbers lower and I've heard nubmers higher.''
   Williams said Cheney had also spent part of the day discussing
with the service chiefs their suggestions for the long-term cuts
for the years 1992-94, which have been reported to be in the range
of $180 billion.
   The spokesman said that no decisions have been made on those
cuts, but that the talks have been ``a good starting point.''
</TEXT>
