<FIRST>r w AM-Seabrook 300   11-21 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook, 300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Licensing Board Blasts Shannon, Stands By Seabrook Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal panel Tuesday accused Massachusetts
Attorney General James Shannon of unfairly delaying the Seabrook,
N.H., nuclear power plant and reaffirmed its view that evacuation
plans for nearby residents are adequate.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board, in a 41-page memo dated
Monday and made public Tuesday, said concerns raised by a
higher-level regulatory board should not prevent Seabrook from
getting a full-power operating license.
   Using unusually harsh language, the licensing board said Shannon
had raised ``the specter of the deplored `endless loop of
litigation,''' in opposing Seabrook even though Seabrook is
entitled to a license.
   ``The attorney general of Massachusetts is carrying out his
announced strategy of filing contentions at every opportunity,''
the board wrote, adding that Shannon's ``large staff of assistants
with their fecund word processors can produce motions for renewed
litigation faster than the board and parties can deal with them.''
   If the practice is allowed to continue, the board wrote, ``there
is no hope for the Seabrook Station despite applicants' fairly won
victory.''
   Stephen Jonas, Shannon's top deputy handling the Seabrook issue,
said the licensing board's decision was based on impatience, not
law.
   ``The thrust of the decision is `We're tired of this
litigation.' There's no legal substance to their arguments,'' Jonas
said. ``They're trying to railroad this thing through.''
   The memo comes a week after the board touched off a furor among
Seabrook opponents by ruling that Seabrook should be granted a
full-power license despite concerns raised by the Atomic Safety and
Licensing Appeal Board. Shannon called the ruling ``lawless.''
   Both the licensing and appeal boards are branches of the federal
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
