<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-21 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Storm Over New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful storm system raked parts of New England with high
wind, low temperatures and heavy snow Tuesday, a day after it
pushed a line of damaging thunderstorms across much of the
Northeast.
   But temperatures hit record highs on the southern and central
Plains.
   Wind blowing at 30 to 50 mph, with gusts to 58 mph, caused
considerable blowing and drifting of snow in Maine, along with
subzero wind chill readings. And a gale warning extended all the
way southward along the coast to Virginia.
   By midday, the storm had dumped 17 inches of snow at South
Lincoln, Vt., with 16 inches at the Middlebury Snow Bowl of Vermont
and 12 inches at Farmington, Maine, the National Weather Service
said. Rumford, Maine, got 3 inches of snow during the six-hour
period up to 1 p.m. EST.
   The high wind in Maine downed trees and power lines in some
areas. Outside Maine, wind gusted to 54 mph at Providence, R.I.,
during the morning and to 55 mph at Boston.
   The storm, centered off the coast of Maine by afternoon,
produced severe thunderstorms which raked Pennsylvania, southern
New York state, southern New England, New Jersey and the
Washington, D.C., area with high wind Monday.
   The storm continued to produce strong wind Tuesday as far south
as the Carolinas and as far west as Ohio and eastern Michigan.
   That wind produced snow squalls around the lower Great Lakes
region, with heavy snow reported in northeastern Ohio, where the
towns of Jefferson and Andover had received 5 inches of snow from
late Monday to midday Tuesday.
   Elsewhere, an upper level weather disturbance moving
southeastward out of eastern Montana produced light snow across
North Dakota and Minnesota, with up to 4 inches possible in
Minnesota by Wednesday morning.
   A few light showers were scattered from Louisiana to
north-central Oklahoma.
   Unseasonably high temperatures were over parts of the southern
and central high Plains, with readings in the 70s across much of
Texas and in the 50s and 60s to the north.
   Cheyenne, Wyo., tied its record of 64 degrees; Colorado Springs,
Colo., hit a record 70; Midland, Texas, tied its record of 81; and
San Angelo, Texas, warmed to a record 83.
</TEXT>
