<FIRST>u w AM-US-Salvador 3rdLd-Writethru a0756 11-21 0963</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0756,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Says U.S. Will Protect its Citizens</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs bgng Rep. Henry ... to update
with travel restrictions; INSERTS 3 grafs after 10th graf pvs bgng A military
... with additional military detail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House hinted broadly Tuesday that
U.S. military force might be used to assist Americans trapped in a
hotel seized by by leftist guerrillas in El Salvador. President
Bush said it was ``a tough situation.''
   ``The president believes very strongly in our responsibility to
protect American citizens,'' White House Press Secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   Four U.S. military advisers were among the Americans and other
foreigners that the rebels said they ``captured'' at a luxury hotel
in northern San Salvador. However, there was some doubt about the
guerrillas' claims.
   At least six armed military men, believed to be the U.S.
advisers, were seen by an Associated Press reporter barricaded on
the fourth floor of the hotel. They were brandishing M-16 rifles.
   Guerrillas and an unknown number of guests were on the fifth
floor and guerrillas on the third floor.
   One of the Americans told reporters in the hotel that he and his
companions were not hostages, but could not leave. ``We're here
because we feel we can't leave safely,'' he said. One of the
military men said they did not fire at the rebels because they were
not shot at.
   Fitzwater refused to say what steps were being considered but
added, ``We are making plans as necessary, and we feel we have a
very specific responsibility in this area.'' He said no options _
including military ones _ were being ruled out.
   ``It's a tough situation there,'' Bush told congressional
leaders summoned to the White House to discuss his summit next week
with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Afterward, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said, ``If diplomatic notes
and representations won't get them free, then we must do what we
must do. That would include in my book military action, but I'm
just speaking for myself.'' He said Bush did not discuss military
options.
   The State Department issued a warning to U.S. citizens not to
travel to El Salvador and urged Americans already there to register
with the U.S. Embassy.
   A military source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Pentagon was making preparations to send ``intelligence and
tactical assistance'' to El Salvador. He declined to elaborate on
the number of men, the equipment they would carry or from where
they would travel.
   He later said special operation forces were put on a heightened
alert.
   ``Although always on alert for this type of situation, their
status has been raised,'' he said.
   The source said any involvement of U.S. military personnel
depended on a request for assistance from Salvadoran President
Alfredo Cristiani, followed by the final go-ahead from Bush.
   Comparing the holding of the four military advisers to the
murder of Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins in Lebanon, he said:
``We're not going to get another bloody eye. Not this time, not
again.''
   The source said military strategists did not rule out direct
U.S. intervention but said they would rather see Salvadoran troops
acting on the advice of U.S. advisers.
   As recently as Monday, Bush reaffirmed his administration's
strong support for the right-wing government of President Alfredo
Cristiani against the guerrillas. The United States has provided
about $3.5 billion in the past 10 years to oppose the insurgency
with weapons and other American support.
   Bush was briefed several times during the day on San Salvador by
top military and foreign policy advisers.
   Fitzwater also said a group of officials from the Pentagon, CIA,
State Department and National Security Council met in the White
House situation room to monitor events. The panel, known as the
deputies' committee, was formed to improve coordination in the
aftermath of the abortive coup in Panama.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said no
negotiations were under consideration with the rebels, whom she
called ``terrorists, pure and simple.''
   She said about a dozen of the rebels, deliberately targeting
civilians, had entered the El Salvador Sheraton Hotel shortly
before dawn. They were later reinforced by up to 150 guerrillas,
some of them set up as snipers in the area, Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Although the hotel is called the Sheraton, the U.S.-based hotel
chain said it sold its interest several years ago.
   Mrs. Tutwiler said the Salvadoran army had surrounded the hotel.
She described the situation as ``very fluid and dangerous'' and in
an ambiguous warning to the rebels, declared: ``We will not
speculate on the steps the United States and the Salvadoran
government might take.''
   Fitzwater told reporters at the White House that the rebels had
``embarked on a despicable road of violence by threatening
citizens, Americans and innocent citizens of all nations who may be
in their path.''
   ``The United States stands committed to the people and the
government of El Salvador,'' the spokesman said.
   Similarly, Fitzwater said: ``The president believes very
strongly in our responsibility to protect American citizens. But we
cannot speculate on steps the U.S. or the Salvadoran government
might be undertaking or considering at this time.''
   ``These Marxist guerrillas have shown their true colors,''
Fitzwater said. ``They are attacking defenseless citizens in a
civilian hotel and using the surrounding neighborhood of
defenseless Salvadoran citizens as a shield against the government
forces.''
   The rebels launched an offensive a little more than a week ago,
occupying poor and working-class neighborhoods in the vicinity of
the capital. There were indications on Monday that their offensive
had subsided under pressure of strong air and ground attacks by
government forces. However, the seizure of the Sheraton indicated a
new show of strength by the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
