<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Missiles     11-21 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Missiles,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Department Attempts Missile Technology Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced on Tuesday it took two
steps to help control the spread of ballistic missile technology,
including tightening oversight of foreign and domestic
manufacturers of missile parts that deal with the Department of
Defense.
   The actions are designed to help curb the export of sensitive
missile technologies to nations such as Iraq, said one Pentagon
official, who spoke on condition he not be named.
   Under the new procedures, the Defense Department will now
require domestic and foreign contracting companies to comply with
the laws and regulations of their own government in regard to
missile-related export controls, as well as those of the United
States.
   In addition, the department will establish procedures to ensure
that its cooperative defense programs are in compliance with
Missile Technology Control Regime, a 10-nation agreement among
Western nations to curb the spread of dangerous missiles.
   ``This means we can put pressure on the contractors, foreign and
domestic. It gives us more leverage. We'll have the authority now
to look at what business they do with other nations, and if we
don't like it, we won't do business with them,'' the source said.
   ``At a minimum, these initiatives will encourage DOD
contractors, including their subsidiaries, to act responsibly in
missile related exports,'' the Pentagon said in a statement
announcing the steps.
</TEXT>
