<DOCNO> AP891121-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Romania     11-21 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceausescu Suggests Soviets Give Up Moldavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Nicolae Ceausescu suggests
the Soviet Union give up territory gained through a pact with Nazi
Germany that would include Moldavia, part of which Josef Stalin
took from Romania.
   In comments from a speech to the 14th Romanian Communist Party
Congress, published Tuesday, Ceausescu said the non-aggression pact
of 1939 in which Stalin and Adolf Hitler divided Eastern Europe
into spheres of influence should be canceled.
   Among countries and territories assigned to the Soviet Union
were the Baltic republics _ Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania _ and
Bessarabia, Romanian until 1940 and now part of Soviet Moldavia.
The Soviet Union also absorbed the Baltic states in 1940.
   Ceausecu, a Communist autocrat in his own country and a maverick
in the Soviet bloc, told the party congress:
   ``First of all, a clear, unequivocal stand of condemnation and
cancellation must be taken on all the accords concluded with
Hitler's Germany ... to eliminate all the consequences of those
accords and dictates.''
   He did not go into detail, but his allusion to Hitler-Stalin
pact was clear. Ceausescu's suggestion comes at a time of political
and ethnic turmoil in many parts of the Soviet Union, including
Moldavia and the Baltic republics.
   In the speech, delivered Monday to the opening session of the
congress, the Romanian leader also rejected political and economic
liberalization of the kind sweeping through the Soviet bloc.
   His contempt for reform was contained in a prepared text of the
speech, which lasted more than five hours. He departed from the
text to comment on the 1939 treaty.
   Romania's official media published their first reports of unrest
in the Moldavia, where 60 percent of the people are ethnic
Romanians.
   Scinteia, the Communist Party daily, carried a dispatch Tuesday
from the official Soviet news agency Tass that described a
crackdown on ethnic Romanian demonstrators in the city of Kishinve
several days earlier.
   A Western diplomat said privately Romania was showing increased
interest recently in its former territory, which officials still
call Bessarabia.
   Although regaining the territory ``may be part of his vision,''
the diplomat said, Ceausescu's primary purpose probably was to
demonstrate independence of Moscow.
   Romanian officials, speaking anonymously for fear of
retribution, agreed that Ceausescu appeared to be making more of a
political statement than a demand for the return of lost territory.
</TEXT>
