<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NewsInterest     11-21 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News Interest,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>SF Quake, Berlin Wall Capture Public Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of the American public closely
followed news of the San Francisco earthquake and the opening of
the Berlin Wall but paid little attention to other major news
events in the past month, according to a survey by the Times Mirror
publishing company.
   The destruction caused by the Oct. 17 earthquake aroused the
close attention of 73 percent of Americans, Times Mirror said.
   In the four-year history of the survey, it said, that level of
interest was exceeded only by the 80 percent who closely followed
the explosion of the Challenger space shuttle in 1986.
   Half the American public closely followed the news of the
breaching of the Berlin Wall, but comparatively little interest was
shown in the resumption of fighting in Nicaragua, the World Series
or state and local elections, according to the Times Mirror News
Interest Index for November.
   Only 13 percent of those surveyed said they followed the
Nicaraguan story or U.S. election coverage closely, while 23
percent said they paid close attention to the World Series.
   Times Mirror said 44 percent of those surveyed rated coverage of
the earthquake and Berlin Wall stories as excellent. Typically,
about 20 percent give the press an excellent rating for its
coverage of a national news story.
   The survey results were based on telephone interviews with 1,230
adults aged 18 or older during the Nov. 9-12 period. Times Mirror
said results based on the total sample had a margin of error of
three percentage points.
   Times Mirror said interest in the San Francisco quake was high
in all regions of the country and among all types of Americans.
Nearly two-thirds of people under 30, who usually are least
interested in all kinds of news, said they followed quake coverage
closely.
</TEXT>
