<FIRST>u w AM-Bye-ByeCongress 1stLd-Writethru a0707 11-21 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bye-Bye Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers in Jovial Mood on What They Hope is Last Day of Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs `With enough ...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
Congress having enough business to last until next week. SUBS grafs 12-13,
beginning `The House ...' with 8 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrators opposed
to US policy in El Salvador protesting. Picks up 14th graf pvs `That prompted
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House gave about 100 Soviet soldiers a
standing ovation Tuesday and a congressional tape of upcoming
events played show tunes as Congress plunged through what it hoped
was its last day of business for the year.
   With enough unresolved business to last until after midnight _
or even next week _ members of Congress were in jovial spirits as
they began the day after a late night session Monday.
   ``Maybe, it's because they're getting a raise,'' said a staff
member.
   The House went into session at 9 a.m., an hour earlier than
normal, causing some observers to ask why the lawmakers were
pushing themselves so hard.
   ``Are you kidding?'' responded Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass.,
chairman of the Rules Committee. ``Give these guys a good night's
sleep and a strong wind at their back and we'll be here until
Christmas.''
   The Senate slept in, with no floor business until noon.
   Not many House members showed up for opening formalities, but
those who did were studied carefully from the gallery by an
impressive contingent of Soviet soldiers, resplendent in their
olive and red uniforms.
   A scene that couldn't have been imagined two years ago unfolded
as the 12 or so House members recited the Pledge of Allegiance and
then turned and applauded the soldiers.
   The Soviets, members of a military choral group on tour in the
United States, clapped back.
   ``Forty-five years ago our countries were together against
Hitler,'' reminded one of the soldiers later as Reps. Steny Hoyer,
D-Md., and Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., gave the group a guided tour
of the Capitol.
   ``It's an exciting time in which we live,'' Hoyer said. ``A
hopeful time for our generation and generations to come in terms of
de-escalating the tension that has existed between the two greatest
military powers of the globe not only to our benefit, but to the
benefit of the world.''
   A few hours later, an encounter of quite a different nature
occurred between several people in the Senate gallery and the
lawmakers below.
   Demonstrators opposed to the U.S. policy in El Salvador shouted
slogans from the viewing seats and were dragged from the chamber by
Capitol police.
   The Senate responded by temporarily closing the gallery to
visitors.
   Three of the protesters were charged with disrupting Congress
and demonstrating within the Capitol. Each charge is punishable by
a maximum fine of $500 and or six months in jail.
   The long legislative day required action by both houses on much
of the same legislation, including the complicated deficit
reduction package.
   The Senate stayed in session, taking ``quorum calls'' when it
had no business to handle, but the House recessed periodically
through the day while waiting to vote on legislation.
   At lunch, the House dining room treated members and visitors to
a turkey buffet with all the Thanksgiving trimmings.
   During the morning, C-Span, which broadcasts Congress, used the
channel that usually carries the Senate to show the British
Parliament in action.
   That prompted House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., to quip to
reporters: ``I know you're going to think they're much more
interesting, and much more witty and much more stimulating in every
way.''
   Foley said he entertained the speaker of the House of Commons
about a month ago who asked him how many speakers had preceded him.
Foley replied he was the 49th Speaker of the House.
   ``He said he was the 634th. They generally date the speakership
from 1377,'' Foley said. ``And I said, `Well, that's what we call a
putdown in the United States, Mr. Speaker,' and he said, `Well,
eight of them were beheaded, two of them on the same day.'''
   Congressional staffers, eager to get their bosses out of town,
were much gentler in their approach.
   Show tunes such as ``The Impossible Dream,'' ``One Day More,''
and ``Tonight'' were programmed into the House Republican cloakroom
legislative tape of upcoming events.
   The Democrats' staff members said they were keeping their jokes
inside the cloakroom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
