<HEAD>Networks Plan Coverage of Bush, Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with ABC plans; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC, CBS and CNN are planning live coverage for
both President Bush's speech and the liftoff of the space shuttle
Discovery on Wednesday night.
   NASA has said only that the liftoff is scheduled between 6:30
p.m. and 10:30 p.m. EST. Wednesday and that it will make the count
public just nine minutes ahead. However, the launch is expected to
take place about 7:30 p.m.
   President Bush is to address the nation at 9 p.m.
   ABC will cover both events, said spokeswoman Elise Adde.
   CBS plans to cover the space shuttle launch, then return to
regular programming until 9, when President Bush's speech begins.
   CNN also will cover both. If the shuttle were delayed and both
events occurred simultaneously, ``I don't know what our choice will
be,'' said spokesman Steve Haworth.
   NBC will carry Bush's speech live and make launch coverage
available to its affiliates, said spokeswoman Katherine McQuay.
