<FIRST>u i AM-OttawaStrip     11-21 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ottawa Strip,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Federal Loan That Financed Strip Club Was a Mistake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two federal loans that helped finance a strip
club across the river from Ottawa, Canada's federal capital, were a
mistake that won't be repeated, officials said Tuesday.
   ``An error was made,'' Harvie Andre, minister of regional
industrial expansion, said in the House of Commons. ``Procedures
are being amended to insure this doesn't happen again.''
   The Federal Business Development Bank, a government agency, made
two loans totaling $899,000 ($1 million Canadian) to two
businessmen in Hull, Quebec, over 18 months to buy land and a
building for the bar, called Le Lido.
   ``It's against the bank's policy to finance clubs of that
kind,'' spokesman Ken Cavanagh said by telephone from bank
headquarters in Montreal. ``It was an error made at the local
level.''
   A report Monday by Radio-Canada Television, the French-language
service of the Canadian Broadcasting Corp., disclosed the loans to
Andre Frechette and Frank Bentivoglio. It said they totaled $1.1
million, but Cavanagh said that was too high and provided the lower
figure.
   Hull, on the Quebec side of the Ottawa River, is the site of
many office buildings in the national capital district. Le Lido is
near the Promenade du Portage, one of the largest office complexes.
   Andre said the federal agency's officers in Hull did not tell
superiors in Montreal what the loans were buying.
   During the Commons debate Tuesday in Ottawa, Donald Boudria of
the opposition Liberal Party asked: ``Haven't we had enough of this
nonsense? Why doesn't the government clean up its act once and for
all?''
   Frechette operates Le Lido and employs about 20 young women to
dance. He said in an interview with Radio-Canada that most
afternoon customers were government employees, many of high rank,
who took cigarette breaks at the club because smoking was
prohibited in government buildings.
   The Federal Business Development Bank's purpose is to make loans
and provide management counseling to small and medium-sized
businesses.
   Cavanagh said helping finance bars or discotheques would not be
against bank policy if they were not of an erotic nature.
   ``We intend to tighten up the policy and make it clearer,'' he
said. ``Senior officials of the bank are going to be looking into
the entire process.''
</TEXT>
