<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Murders     11-21 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Murders,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Not to Blame for Union Workers' Murders, Defense Argues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Seattle union activists were murdered in 1981
because a ``vicious thug'' didn't get his way in a union dispute,
not because the martial-law government of former Philippines
President Ferdinand Marcos had marked them for death, a defense
attorney said Tuesday.
   The murders of Silme Domingo and Gene Viernes at the Alaska
Cannery Workers Union offices resulted from a dispute over gambling
and work assignments in Alaskan fish canneries, Richard Hibey told
a federal court.
   Hibey is the Washington, D.C., attorney for the estate of Marcos
and for Marcos' widow, Imelda. They are among the defendants in a
$30 million civil lawsuit filed September 1982 that claims the
Marcos government ordered the Seattle killings because of Domingo
and Viernes' anti-Marcos agitation.
   The trial began Monday and is expected to last three to five
weeks.
   Friends and relatives of the dead men hope to prove before U.S.
District Judge Barbara Rothstein that Domingo and Viernes were
targeted by a Philippines intelligence network that kept track of
anti-Marcos dissidents in this country.
   Hibey called the murders an ``undeniable, terrible fact,'' but
added: ``Nothing was going on in Seattle that had anything to do
with Filipino politics that could ever rise to the level ... to
cause the deaths of Mr. Domingo and Mr. Viernes.''
   ``No matter how many witnesses, no matter how many self-styled
experts are called to testify about the politics of the
Philippines, there will be no evidence of any link, any relation,
any connection, between what these politics were and the deaths of
Mr. Domingo and Mr. Viernes,'' Hibey said.
   A jury of eight, including two alternates, is hearing the case
against the Marcoses; Rothstein will judge liability of the other
defendants.
   At the original criminal trial, at which three men were
convicted and given life prison sentences, prosecutors said the
murders occurred because Domingo and Viernes were union reformers
working to eliminate gambling in the canneries.
   That, Hibey said, is the accurate motive in the case.
   Six days before the 1981 murders, Hibey said, Viernes argued
with one of those convicted, Fortunato Dictado about dispatching
gang members to work in the canneries.
   Evidence will show that Dictado muttered, ``I'm going to get rid
of you,'' Hibey said.
   The motive, Hibey said, was simply ``the demands of a vicious
thug whose demands were not met when he wanted them to be met'' by
Viernes. Domingo died, Hibey said, ``because he happened to be
there.''
   ``This was a (union) local that had suffered from the ravages
... of bribes and kickbacks in order to get jobs, where violence
and thuggery were the order of the day,'' he said.
   On Monday, Jeff Robinson, an attorney for the plaintiffs, argued
that evidence will show that the union-dispute motive was only a
cover for the men being marked for death by Marcos' intelligence
network.
   Jailing and killing dissidents or causing them to disappear were
weapons in Marcos' anti-opponent arsenal before his government was
toppled in 1986, Robinson said.
</TEXT>
