<FIRST>u a AM-TexasJailSuit     11-21 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Jail Suit,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Judge Rules State Must Deal With Jail Overcrowding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state prison system must accept inmates
who have been sentenced to state prison but are being held in local
jails because of prison overcrowding, a judge ruled Tuesday.
   State District Judge Joe Hart also said the state must pay the
counties for housing and feeding the inmates.
   Numerous counties have complained that they are being forced to
house inmates who can't immediately enter state prisons because of
a federal court ordering limiting inmate population.
   Twelve counties sued the state in an effort to force the
transfer of an estimated 6,000 felons from their jails. Statewide,
an estimated 12,000 inmates have been sentenced to state prison but
are being held in local jails because the prison system has delayed
accepting them.
   Attorney General Jim Mattox said the state would appeal.
   ``There is just not enough room in the inn,'' Mattox said. ``We
can't violate the federal court order and take additional prisoners
into the Department of Corrections.''
   Hart did not specify how much the Texas Department of
Corrections should pay the counties for housing the state prisoners.
   Ann Clark Snell, representing 11 counties in the lawsuit, said
the counties want compensation because the state neglected its
duty. She said each inmate costs the state $40 a day to maintain.
   At that rate, the cost for 6,000 inmates in the 12 counties
could be more than $87 million a year.
   Mattox urged Gov. Bill Clements to allow the current special
legislative session to consider payments to counties. Clements had
no immediate comment on the ruling or Mattox's suggestion.
   Hart said there are many measures that the state could use to
take the prisoners off the counties' hands.
   ``Such other methods include contracting with private vendors,
the federal government, and local government, and greater use of
the Prison Management Act ... furloughs and `good time','' he wrote.
</TEXT>
