<FIRST>r a AM-Lincoln-Release     11-21 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln-Release,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Spokeswoman Says Keating Directed Misleading News Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lincoln S&amp;L Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former spokeswoman for American Continental
Corp. says company Chairman Charles Keating Jr. personally directed
preparation of a press release saying the sale of the company's
troubled Lincoln Savings and Loan was imminent when it really
wasn't.
   Patricia Johnson, a former American Continental public relations
executive, said Tuesday she wrote the release regarding the
proposed sale of the subsidiary at Keating's direction.
   ``He was concerned about the publicity, and the stock was
falling and he asked me for advice,'' Ms. Johnson told The
Associated Press.
   Lincoln Savings, in Irvine, Calif., was taken over by federal
regulators last April. Its failure, which could end up costing
taxpayers as much as $2 billion, and Keating have been the subject
of Congressional hearings and a Securities and Exchange Commission
investigation.
   The Feb. 9 press release Ms. Johnson discussed was distributed
the day after American Continental's stock fell 87 cents, to $5.50
a share. Market observers blamed the slide on rumors that Lincoln
Savings' proposed ale to a group of California investors had hit
snags and that American Continental was in financial trouble.
   Following American Continental's announcement that the sale of
Lincoln was ``imminent,'' the stock rose to $6.25 per share and
trading volume increased sharply.
   The sale didn't take place. American Continental filed for
protection under bankruptcy laws on April 14, the day before
Lincoln Savings was taken over by the government. American
Continental stock now trades for 5 cents a share.
   Ms. Johnson told The Arizona Republic she had recommended that a
press release about the sale be issued and that Keating specified
that the word `imminent' had to be used.
   ``He said that he wanted, no matter what else I put in the press
release, to make sure I used the word `imminent,'' Ms. Johnson told
the newspaper.
   Ms. Johnson said she has a draft of the release that has a
notation written in the margin by Keating.
   There was no immediate comment Tuesday from American
Continental; company officials didn't return phone calls. However,
in documents prepared for the Securities Exchange Commission,
American Continental officials have said Ms. Johnson was
responsible for the press release's contents and that the release
was issued in response to news media inquiries.
   ``I didn't create the news, I only disseminated the news,'' Ms.
Johnson said Tuesday. ``I had no reason to believe the information
he had given me was incorrect.''
   Several individuals familiar with American Continental's attempt
to sell Lincoln told the Republic the statement about a sale being
imminent was false.
   ``It was untrue in our judgment,'' said Ernest Leff, one of the
investors interested in buying the thrift. ``I smiled when I saw
Charlie making his flamboyant statements.''
   ``What bothered me was that they lied,'' said William Davis,
chief deputy commissioner of the California Department of Savings
and Loan. ``They knew absolutely dead certain that the sale was not
imminent.''
   Ms. Johnson said she has cooperated with government officials
who contacted her. But she said there was no indication if she'll
be called to testify in any proceedings.
   Ms. Johnson said Keating called her into his office in April and
told her American Continental was dismantling its public relations
unit, which consisted of herself and clerical staff. She said she
didn't receive severance, vacation pay or even compensation for the
day she was told she was dismissed.
   A single mother of three, Ms. Johnson said she does some
public-relations consulting work from her home but has had
difficulty finding work because of her past with American
Continental.
</TEXT>
