<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     11-21 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 17 Guerrillas, 2 Soldiers, Killed in Continued Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 17 guerrillas and two soldiers
were killed in scattered battles, marking November as the month of
heaviest fighting this year, the military said Tuesday.
   Battles between leftist rebels and security forces since Nov. 1
have claimed the lives of 112 insurgents and 22 soldiers, according
to military statistics.
   The armed forces said the latest casualties came in four clashes
Monday and gave this account:
   Ten guerrillas, including three women, and a soldier were killed
in a gun battle in the mountains near the town of Rosas, 190 miles
southwest of Bogota.
   At Vistahermosa 125 miles east of Bogota, one guerrilla and one
solder were killed.
   Four rebels were killed in fighting near San Pablo, a town 215
miles north of Bogota, and two were slain near Santander de
Quilichao, 220 miles south of the capital.
   The army said the rebels involved in Monday's clashes were from
three organizations _ the Revolutionary Armed Forces, the National
Liberation Army and the Quintin Llame group.
   National police said a city councilman from Paime, a town 45
miles north of Bogota, was killed Monday night in Bogota.
   They said Pablo Enrique Canon was shot as he was leaving a
restaurant. Police said the reason for the attack was not known.
</TEXT>
