<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-DCBill     11-21 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-DC Bill,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Appropriations Signed After Abortion Provisions Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday signed a $3.4
billion budget bill for the District of Columbia after Congress
stripped from the measure an abortion provision that had provoked
two vetoes.
   The measure, for the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1,
includes the federal government's annual $435 million contribution
to the district government. The rest of the funds are paid by local
taxpayers but must be appropriated by Congress before the D.C.
government can spend anything.
   Bush on Monday night vetoed the D.C. appropriations bill for the
second time because of abortion provisions that would not have
restricted the use of the taxpayer-paid money, while limiting
federal Medicaid funds to abortions to save the life of the mother.
   Until last year, the district had been funding
abortion-on-demand for poor women with locally raised money.
   Bush exercised similar vetoes on two other measures over
abortion issues.
   One was a bill providing funds for the Department of Health and
Human Services which would have expanded use of Medicaid funds to
cover abortions for poor women in cases of rape and incest.
   Congress sustained Bush's veto, then sent him a new bill without
the abortion liberalization provison which he signed.
   Bush also vetoed a foreign aid bill that contained a provision
giving money to a United Nations population control program. The
program, in turn, supported a Chinese program under which abortions
were sometimes utilized.
   Congress removed that provision from the measure and sent it
back to Bush for his expected signature.
</TEXT>
