<FIRST>r a AM-ProfessorsDispute     11-21 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Professors Dispute,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist's Comments On Central Park Rapists Leads To Professors'
Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yale lecturer's angry letter to a
prominent Harvard psychiatrist attacking him for his comments on
the gang rape of a jogger in New York City has led to charges and
countercharges of racism.
   The latest salvo was fired this month in the Yale Daily News,
the student newspaper. Alexander Theroux wrote a column defending
his letter to Dr. Alvin Poussaint and accusing the psychiatrist of
trying to have him fired by the Ivy League school.
   Theroux sent the letter to Poussaint after hearing him
interviewed on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley'' about six
young men accused of raping and badly beating the woman jogging in
Central Park on April 19. The woman was released from a
rehabilitation center in Wallingford only last Wednesday.
   Theroux said in an interview last week that he described the
attackers as ``monkeys'' in his letter because he felt the attack
was animal-like.
   Poussaint, who is also a consultant to television's ``The Cosby
Show,'' is black. Theroux, a novelist and lecturer in English who
said he is a friend of the victim, is white.
   Poussaint, viewing the term ``monkeys'' as a racist remark,
passed the letter on to a Boston Globe columnist after failing to
get what he felt was a proper response from Yale. He said he
believed the letter warranted an apology.
   Theroux said the subsequent column in the Globe transformed ``an
angry letter into a racial one,'' and prompted him to respond that
he was being treated in a racist manner.
   Theroux said his choice of the word ``monkey'' may have been
injudicious, but he did not use the term as a racial slur.
   ``It wasn't _ and isn't _ a racial term to me,'' he wrote in the
Yale Daily News. ``It could have been pigs, dogs, scumfish. They
had behaved literally worse than animals.''
   Theroux said he wrote Poussaint because he was outraged by the
psychiatrist's description of the young men as having been angry,
which he viewed as a partial defense of the woman's attackers.
   The Yale lecturer said he told Poussaint that he could create a
backlash in the white community by defending such people. ``My
point was to tell him he was an irresponsible idiot,'' he said.
   Poussaint said that in the television interview he said that
``any kids who attack and brutalize a woman this way must have some
terrible anger and rage inside them.''
   ``It was not an attempt on my part to excuse these kids'
behavior,'' he said in an interview last week. ``That would be
absurd.''
   Poussaint said he didn't think Theroux ``could be that
unsophisticated not to understand what the term `monkey' meant. He
picked a common term used in derision of blacks.''
   The Harvard psychiatrist wrote the chairman of Yale's English
department, Richard H. Brodhead, to call his attention to the
letter. Poussaint said he also sent copies of his letter to Yale
President Benno C. Schmidt Jr. and the university's affirmative
action officer.
   The letter was written on Yale stationery. Poussaint said he had
thought it might be a forgery because of its tone, and that if it
were not, the English department should question its author.
   The letter ``raised questions about professionalism and whether
a person holding such views was appropriate to be a teacher of
black students,'' Poussaint said.
   Theroux, who is in his second one-year appointment to the
English department, was chastised by the chairman for using Yale
stationery to write the personal letter but was not subjected to
any other action.
   For a university to get into the position of firing someone for
saying something others may find distasteful ``is to do the work of
censorship,'' said Brodhead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-McCain-Lincoln     11-21 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCain-Lincoln,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCain Asks Ethics Committee To Clear His Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lincoln S&amp;L, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John McCain wrote the Senate Ethics
Committee on Tuesday that he never acted improperly on behalf of a
collapsing savings bank whose top official gave him campaign money
and use of an airplane.
   ``I have every confidence that you and the committee will
determine that there has been no improper conduct on my part and
that you will clear my name,'' the Arizona Republican wrote Ethics
Committee Chairman Howell Heflin, D-Ala. and Vice Chairman Warren
Rudman, R-N.H.
   McCain is one of five senators who received campaign money from
Charles H. Keating Jr., who headed Lincoln Savings and Loan, of
Irvine, Calif., when it collapsed, becoming the nation's largest
thrift failure.
   The ethics panel had written to the five, asking whether their
intervention for Keating and his bank with federal regulators was
prompted by Keating's campaign contributions. All have denied any
wrongdoing. The Ethics Committee has hired an outside counsel to
gather information in the case.
   McCain said he always represents constituents _ Keating lives in
Arizona _ when they have ``a valid complaint'' and denied his help
is ever based on their campaign contributions.
   McCain admitted, however, that he inadvertently did not pay in a
timely fashion for flights on Keating's corporate plane _ although
he eventually discovered he paid twice for some flights.
   McCain received $112,000 from Keating, his family members and
business associates from 1982-86, although the senator has
contended that some of them might have contributed to his campaigns
independently of Keating.
   McCain and three other senators met with then-Chairman Edwin
Gray, of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, on April 2, 1987 to
discuss the board's investigation of Lincoln.
   One week later, McCain joined four senators in a meeting with
the regulators who were conducting the examination.
   The senator said he attended the meetings after complaints from
Keating, and after receiving favorable reports on the bank from the
large accounting firm of Arthur Young; and from Alan Greenspan, now
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board but a consultant for Keating
when he wrote a letter on the bank's behalf.
   Keating complained in March 1987 that the examination of Lincoln
was taking too long, and that bank board examiners were being
unreasonably critical of Lincoln's investments.
   Arthur Young, which was working for Keating, supported his
contention. The Greenspan letter, written in 1985 but given to
McCain two years later, endorsed Lincoln's investment policies and
its management.
   McCain, noting that the bank's parent company, American
Continental Corp. was based in Arizona, said, ``I felt reasonable
questions were being raised'' about whether the bank was receiving
``fair and equitable treatment by the bank board.''
   McCain told the ethics panel that after the San Francisco-based
bank examiners informed the senators they had uncovered potentially
serious legal and financial problems at Lincoln, he ``was totally
satisfied'' that the examination was fair and never intervened
again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
