<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil     11-21 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Release Final Results of Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced on Tuesday the
final results of the presidential election a week ago and confirmed
a conservative businessman and Marxist labor leader will be in the
Dec. 17 runoff.
   The announcement was just a formality. Earlier results had shown
conservative Fernando Collor de Mello and former union leader Luis
Inacio Lula da Silva received the most votes in the Nov. 15
balloting. Both fell far short of winning a majority, forcing the
runoff.
   Collor de Mello of the National Reconstruction Party led the
21-candidate field with 20,609,009 votes, or 28.52 percent, after
more than 82 million ballots were counted by the Superior Electoral
Court.
   Da Silva, of the Workers' Party, received 11,622,673 votes for
16.08 percent, according to Electoral Court spokesman Irineu
Tamanini.
   The main interest during the vote count was which of two leftist
candidates would be the No. 2 vote getter and face Collor de Mello
in the runoff.
   Leonel Brizola of the leftist Democratic Labor Party finished a
close third with 11,168,228 votes or 15.45 percent.
   Tamanini said more than 17 percent of the voters cast blank
ballots _ a high rate for Brazil. Voting is mandatory for
Brazilians aged 18 to 69.
   The winner of the second-round balloting will be sworn in March
15 for a five-year term. President Jose Sarney by law was not
eligible for election.
</TEXT>
