<SECOND>AM-Salmon Warning,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Warns Against Eating Chicago Company's Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration warned
consumers Tuesday not to eat smoked salmon products packed by Royal
Food Enterprises of Chicago because bacterial contamination could
make them ill.
   The agency said a voluntary recall had not been effective
because some of the company's brokers and wholesalers had failed to
notify retail outlets.
   The bacteria involved, Lysteria monocytogenes, cause
listeriosis. This disease, characterized by flu-like symptoms,
presents little risk to healthy people but can be life-threatening
to the seriously ill, people with impaired immune systems, fetuses
and the newborn.
   FDA spokesman Emil Corwin said he had no reports of illness from
eating the salmon.
   Here are the products involved.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Sliced or Smoked Nova Salmon:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Vita label, distributed by Vita Food Products Inc. of Chicago,
three-ounce boxes and eight-ounce boxes, both color added and no
color added, and one-pound trays, color added and no color added.
   _Royal Taste label, packed by Royal Enterprises, Chicago, one
pound plastic trays.
   _Smith Brothers Sliced Nova Lox, distributed by Smith Brothers,
Port Washington, Wis. three pounds, type of container not
specified, color added.
   _Star David label, packed by Royal Enterprises, Chicago,
three-pound plastic trays.
   _Meyers label, distributed by Vita Nova Scotia Food Products,
Brooklyn, N.Y., three-pound plastic trays, color added.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Sliced or Smoked Regular Lox or Salmon:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Vita label, distributed by Vita Food Products, Chicago,
three-ounce and eight-ounce boxes, one-pound and three-pound
plastic trays, color added.
   _Star David label, packed by Royal Enterprises, Chicago,
three-pound plastic trays.
   _Vita Nova Salmon Spread, distributed by Vita Food Products
Inc., Chicago, five-pound plastic tubs.
   _Vita Smoked Salmon Trims, distributed by Vita Food Products
Inc., Chicago, 10-pound bulk plastic bags.
