<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-ForeignPolicy     11-21 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Foreign Policy,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vetoes Another</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush vetoed the annual bill
authorizing operations of the State Department late Tuesday and
Congress scrambled to pass a version acceptable to the president
before adjourning for the year.
   Bush objected to a provision that officials said would tie the
government's hands in conducting foreign policy. The provision,
stemming from the Iran-Contra affair, would have imposed criminal
penalties on any official convicted of using U.S. aid to pressure
foreign governments into carrying out polices contrary to U.S. law.
   The House immediately passed by voice vote a new, ``clean''
version of the bill with the offending provision stripped out, and
sent it to the Senate in the hope of winning approval before
Congress adjourned for the year.
   The measure authorizes the spending of up to $9.7 billion over
the next two years, and includes a series of trade sanctions
against China as a protest against its brutal crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators last spring.
   The China sanctions include suspension of risk insurance for
companies doing business in China, suspension of trade assistance,
a freeze on exports of U.S. satellites, a halt to sales of
controlled munitions and an end to sale of certain nuclear
materials and components.
   The bill also provides authority for the administration to spend
up to $16 million to begin U.S. government-sponsored television
broadcasts to Cuba, modeled after Radio Marti, a government
broadcasting effort which has operated for the past several years.
   Also included are $910 million over two years for refugee and
migration assistance, $2 billion for the U.S. Information Agency
and $600 million for the Board for International Broadcasting.
   The provision to which Bush objected would ``severely hamper the
conduct of U.S. foreign policy and would impose an unfair and
unreasonable burden on our diplomats and on the conduct of our
diplomacy and intelligence activities,'' according to a White House
letter to Capitol Hill.
   While Congress backed down from the language, the confrontation
damaged relations with some White House allies on Capitol Hill and
left lingering anger at White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray.
   ``I frankly think it's left some scars that are very deep with
people up here,'' Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., said after talks
aimed at finding a compromise broke down.
   Congressional proponents of the provision took some solace in
the passage of a separate foreign aid bill which contained similar
language, without the criminal penalties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     11-21 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Says Hungary's Foreign Debt Larger Than Thought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Miklos Nemeth told Parliament
Tuesday that Hungary's true foreign debt is $20 billion, $3 billion
more than previously reported.
   Nemeth told stunned legislators that false figures on the debt
had been published for years because the communist leadership
feared an admission of the correct amount would endanger talks with
foreign creditors.
   Last month Parliament adopted laws and constitutional amendments
to prepare for a democratic transformation that includes the first
free elections in more than 40 years and the establishment of a
Hungarian Republic without communist domination.
   The Communist Party was disbanded, replaced by a
Western-oriented Socialist Party that promised to surrender power
if it loses elections scheduled for next June at latest.
   Nemeth said while Hungarians greeted those changes with
jubilation other reforms needed to revitalize the economy probably
will lead to lower living standards and more unemployment.
   ``The decisions that need to be made now will not be applauded
by tens of thousands of people,'' he told Parliament in a
nationally televised session.
   ``Wanting democracy, the majority supported the dismantling of
the party state, but the new changes will be more divisive.''
   There have been calls for elections to be held before June so
that opposition groups can elect represtentatives to the new
legisalature, still controlled by deputies who had been from the
ruling Communist Party.
   One legislator, Gyoergy Banffy, said Monday Parliament should
dissolve itself at its session next month.
   Elections would have to be called within three months after
Parliament was dissolved and Banffy proposed they be scheduled by
March 11. His motion is to be discussed by the legislatore later
this week.
   Nemeth said until the elections his government will work to
``put national interest ahead of everything else.''
   He said that would include a new relationship with the Warsaw
Pact military alliance and the Soviet-led Eastern trading bloc
Comecon.
   He did not elaborate but Hungary has increasingly been turning
toward the West for trade and often has criticized Comecon as
ineffective.
   Hungarian leaders have pledged to remain in the Warsaw Pact but
advocate greater sovereignty within the alliance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
