<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ForeignAid     11-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Aid,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appropriations Bill Signed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed into law a $14.6 billion
foreign aid bill Tuesday night that includes the first cash in a
promised three-year aid program for Poland and Hungary.
   The measure included $533 million in new aid for Poland and
Hungary, aid which has become politically popular because of the
wave of economic and political reform sweeping Eastern Europe.
   About $293 million would be in cash, including support for new
private enterprise and to stabilize Poland's currency; the rest
would come in trade and investment insurance.
   It also includes $85 million in unfettered military aid for El
Salvador, where a weeklong spate of intense warfare has prompted
congressional calls for a re-examination of U.S. policy.
   As usual, more than one-third of U.S. aid goes to the two
parties to the Camp David peace accord, Israel and Egypt. Israel is
due to receive $1.8 billion in military aid and $1.2 billion in
economic aid, while Egypt will get $1.3 billion in military aid and
$815 million in economic assistance.
   Other aid in the bill is earmarked for the Philippines, which
would get $160 million as the U.S. share of a new international
assistance program; Turkey, with $500 million in military aid;
Greece, with $350 million in military aid; $230 million in economic
aid for Pakistan; $440 million in economic aid to be shared among
the four Central American democracies as the administration sees
fit; and $20 million for an economic development fund for Northern
Ireland.
   The administration agreed to accept one item it had argued
vociferously against, a section written by Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.,
that would bar the administration from using aid money to buy
support from other countries for policies the United States could
not legally carry out itself.
   Agreement came after Obey rose on the House floor and announced
the section was not intended to tie the hands of administration
officials carrying out their normal diplomatic duties, but was only
to bar explicit ``quid pro quo'' deals with other countries to
carry out prohibited activities.
   A similar provision in the bill authorizing State Department
activities prompted a veto by Bush Tuesday night.
   The bill survived a major battle over whether the United States
should reverse a five-year policy and renew contributions to the
United Nations Population Fund, which carries out family planning
programs in third-world countries.
   Pressed by anti-abortion forces, Bush vetoed an earlier version
of the bill over a provision giving the U.N. agency $15 million,
and the section was later stripped from the bill. Opponents noted
the agency operates in China, which they contended forces women to
have abortions to enforce its one-child-per-family policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
