<HEAD>Protestors of U.S.Salvadoran Aid Demonstrate Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their third straight day of protest,
chanting, yelling demonstrators outraged over U.S. support of El
Salvador clashed Tuesday with police and about 130 were arrested.
   With helmeted San Francisco police standing behind them, the
protesters held hands and linked arms to form human barricades at
entrances to the Federal Building.
   Some of the building's 6,000 workers and people headed for
court, fought their way through the protestors to get into the
20-story building.
   At the ramp to the building's basement garage, federal and city
police stormed through demonstrator lines to escort workers into
the building. Occasionally, federal police grabbed demonstrators
and dragged them onto the ramp where they were arrested.
   Lt. Frank O'Bando of Federal Protective Services estimated about
100 people were arrested by his officers and scheduled to go before
a U.S. magistrate on disturbance and assault charges.
   San Francisco Deputy Police Chief Frank Reed estimated 30 others
were arrested by city police on similar charges.
   About 135 protesters were arrested Monday as they blocked
entrances at the Federal Building. Hundreds marched through San
Francisco's Mission District on Sunday to protest the violence in
El Salvador and U.S. aid there.
