<FIRST>u w AM-DrugAreas     11-21 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Areas,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Designations Planned for New York, LA, Miami, Houston and
Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National drug policy director William Bennett
plans to designate five areas as major drug trafficking areas
eligible for extra federal aid, an administration source said
Tuesday night.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said four of
the chosen areas are centered on Miami, Los Angeles, New York and
Houston. The fifth area consists of various parts of the
southwestern border with Mexico.
   Under last year's drug law, Bennett may single out such areas
for special emphasis.
   Administration officials have talked of making $40 million
available to those areas, but the source said it was not clear yet
how the extra money would be divided or what it would be used for.
   The areas will be identified in the second draft of the national
anti-drug strategy to be reviewed soon by the National Security
Council and the Domestic Policy Council.
   That strategy is to be submitted to Congress early next year
when President Bush submits his proposed budget for the 1991 fiscal
year beginning next Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
