<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     11-21 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Soldiers Withdraw Following Panamanian Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCON, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. soldiers withdrew from positions in
front of an American military hospital Tuesday after two days of
protests by Panamanian civilians and government officials.
   There was a brief scuffle between six soldiers and 30 Panamanian
demonstrators when the soldiers tried to remove protesters who had
walked between two armored personnel carriers.
   No injuries were reported and shortly after the shoving match
U.S. and Panamanian representatives negotiated a settlement.
   It provided for the U.S. troops to withdraw with Panamanian
military police taking responsibility for the street between the
Gorgas Hospital and a Panamanian Health Ministry building.
   U.S. armored personnel carriers and coils of barbed wire around
the hospital had blocked access to the Panamanian offices.
   Shouting ``Gringos go home!'' and ``Gringo animal, get out of
the canal!'' more than 100 members of the pro-government ``Dignity
Battalions'' had hoisted Panamanian flags outside the hospital.
   The battalions support Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the
commander of Panama's Defense Forces who controls the government.
   Mercedes Morris, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Southern Command,
said American soldiers were stationed in front of the hospital
after Panamanian Defense Forces refused to increase security
following bomb threats.
   A spokesman for the protesters said the U.S. servicemen were
posted at the hospital because the hospital was being used to treat
people wounded in the civil war in El Salvador. The Southern
Command denied Salvadorans were being flown in for treatment.
   The Panamanian Foreign Ministry said Tuesday the U.S. deployment
was ``a powerful affront to our territorial sovereignty, a flagrant
violation'' of the 1977 Panama Canal treaties that give Panama
control of the waterway at the end of 1999.
   Washington has been pressing for Noriega's removal since he was
indicted in February 1988 by federal grand juries in Florida on
drug trafficking charges.
   Noriega has denied the charges and accuses the United States of
trying to renege on the canal treaties.
</TEXT>
