<DOCNO> AP891121-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:MaRainey Adv27   11-21 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Ma Rainey, Adv 27,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Nov 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>August Wilson's Theatrical Blues Find a British Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At last they're singing August Wilson's theatrical
blues in London.
   After years of being virtually unknown in Britain, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning American playwright is responsible for one of the
hits of the London fall: ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' at the Royal
National Theater.
   ``Ma Rainey'' ran eight months on Broadway in the 1984-5 season,
was named best play by the New York Drama Critics' Circle and was a
Tony nominee.
   Wilson's next play, ``Fences,'' again won the Drama Critics'
award, as well as the Tony and the Pulitzer Prize. ``Joe Turner's
Come and Gone,'' netted Wilson's third Drama Critics' award in four
years.
   In the United States, Wilson is considered one of the great
finds of the decade in playwriting. A former poet born in
Pittsburgh to a black mother and a white father, Wilson is writing
a cycle of plays about the black experience this century, one play
for each decade.
   Now, confounding those who doubted Wilson's pungently
colloquial, blues-based language could travel overseas, ``Ma
Rainey'' has won plaudits in London, vindicating the playwright's
belief that his message and characters transcend borders.
   ``I think it's a true test of the universality of the play, if
you can move from the specifics of black American expression and
say, OK, the plays are about that, but they are also about the
human condition,'' Wilson said in an interview at the National,
where ``Ma Rainey'' opened Oct. 25 in the small Cottesloe
auditorium. Intended to run until Jan. 27, the production has been
extended through May.
   Set in a Chicago recording studio in 1927, the play tells a
rending story of racial exploitation and divisiveness involving Ma
Rainey, the ``mother of the blues''; the four black members of her
band; and the two white men who are her producer and manager.
   The cast mixes local talent such as Oxford-educated Hugh
Quarshie with such American expatriates as Clarke Peters, who
starred in ``Driving Miss Daisy'' on the West End.
   The director is Englishman Howard Davies, whose last American
play was Tennessee Williams' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' at the
National in 1988. He also directed ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' in
London and on Broadway.
   Carol Woods-Coleman, who plays Ma Rainey, initially doubted the
actors and director would mesh in their approach to the play.
   ``I was wondering about that prior to meeting Howard (but) our
first meeting put all those queries at ease,'' said Woods-Coleman.
   She praised Davies as ``sensitive and sensible and a very
thorough director.
   ``He let us move with our experience of being black and knowing
about black history without putting bridles on us,'' said the
actress, who won London acclaim in 1987 for the musical ``Blues in
the Night.'' She starred in an off-Broadway production of that show
last fall.
   In the United States, Wilson has worked almost exclusively
alongside black director Lloyd Richards, and feels ``Ma Rainey'' is
``best served by a black director.''
   But ``any human should be interested in, and able to recognize,
the humanity in it,'' he says.
   ``Because the play is about betrayal and honor and duty and love
and all these other universal things, it should be able to be
directed by anyone _ white, Asian, whoever.''
   ``Ma Rainey'' is the second recent American play, following
David Mamet's ``Speed-the-Plow,'' which the National has staged
commendably this year.
   Two other Wilson plays debut in Britain in March: ``Joe Turner's
Come and Gone'' at the ``fringe'' Tricycle Theater in northwest
London, and ``Fences'' at the Liverpool Playhouse, with Richards
repeating his Tony-winning direction.
   Wilson's next Broadway play, ``The Piano Lesson,'' opens April
16 at the Walter Kerr Theater.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Nov. 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
