<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Wyman Adv01   11-21 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Wyman, Adv 01,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Dec 1 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Numbers and Big Celebs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you're talking about the book, ``Blinds &amp;
Shutters,'' subtitled ``the Photographic Collection of Michael
Cooper,'' further subtitled ``Text and Actual Signatures of his
Friends, the World's Pop and Art Legends,'' you're talking big
numbers.
   The 384-page book, of which 5,000 have been printed, weighs 11
pounds, has a pricetag of $595 and cost Bill Wyman, the Rolling
Stones' bassist, $100,000.
   It's sold by mail, from Christopher, Cabot and Fuller, in
Atlanta.
   Cooper, a young British photographer, who hung out in the worlds
of art, fashion and pop music, died in 1973. The book includes a
suicide letter addressed to his 8-year-old son, Adam. Adam Cooper
now works as a clapper loader on movies.
   ``Michael was hanging around with a camera,'' Wyman recalls.
``Nobody paid much attention. He took pictures without you
realizing it. Those were the days you weren't afraid of the gutter
press in England. You never thought of a photographer interfering
in your privacy. Lucky Michael. He did our `Their Satanic Majesties
Request' cover and the Beatles' `Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club
Band.'''
   Wyman was involved in the larger-than-expected project of
compiling the book for six years.
   ``I was approached by Michael's son and his assistant,'' Wyman
recalled in an interview.
   ``They wanted to put together a really good book about Michael's
life. I put them in touch with various people. They came back a
month later; they weren't having much joy.''
   Wyman said they had print and identify for about 70,000
negatives. Very few had been seen before.
   ``We had continual meetings. I put them in touch with people to
do one and two-hour interviews with people who loved Michael.
They'd show Eric Clapton a picture and ask him to say something
about it and they did general interviews.''
   Wyman said he financed everything. ``I dread to think how much I
spent. It was $100,000 at a minimum. I might recoup some. I thought
it was a nice project to be involved in. It has been done very
nicely. If I don't recoup, I'll still be happy. It's something
special.'' Wyman says that some people buy expensive limited
edition books hoping to sell them later at a profit.
   Since Cooper was a special friend of Keith Richards and not
close to Wyman, why did Cooper's son approach Wyman for help?
   ``Keith isn't the kind of person that would do a thing like
that,'' Cooper said. I'm more organized than Keith, businesswise.
I've got an office in London. I've always been interested in other
projects. I'm almost finished with my history of the Rolling Stones
book.''
   Many of the reminiscences culled from the interviews, included
between pictures, talk about the drug scene.
   ``It is hard for me to talk about that because I wasn't
involved. I had family. I was one of the two married Stones at that
time. Charlie Watts was the other. We didn't hang out with the
fraternity very much at all,'' he said.
   ``The music business and people around that I was very into. I
didn't know fashion people, artists, writers and poets so much.
There were a few clubs that everybody used to go to. Peter Blake,
who did the wonderful painting of the Beatles with just the eyes, I
became great friends with him and am to this day.''
   Each book has 10 original signatures, some even contain Andy
Warhol's.
   Cooper took pictures from the early '60s to the early '70s.
Commenting on the '60s, Wyman says, ``It was rather wonderful. I
don't think anybody was really aware of the enormity of change. We
(the Rolling Stones) were responsible for certain changes in
fashion and hair, being the long-haired ones at the beginning. We
made it possible for places like restaurants, bars and clubs to let
you in without ties and jackets. The casual approach was unheard of
then. Through a lot of problems we had at the beginning, things
changed.
   ``We were all ostracized for minor things. We couldn't go into
pubs and buy cigarettes. They would tell us, `We don't serve the
likes of you.' We were refused food in restaurants. We were not
conventional and they'd rather not deal with us, I suppose. It
happened in every country.
   ``We were the only band that went on stage without uniforms. The
Rolling Stones walked on casually. Now everybody has done it, ever
since.''
   Asked whether the 1989 Rolling Stones tour is exhausting, Wyman
says, ``The shows aren't. Going on stage has always been a joy;
still is good fun. The energy is wonderful. Moving, traveling,
unpacking, trying to get food and laundry done _ all those silly
things are exhausting.
   ``We do have the odd day off. Everybody took a week off in Los
Angeles except me. I was doing work for this book.''
   Has he ever thought, since the tour started, ``I'm too old for
this''?
   A smile creases Wyman's face. ``I wondered. But since the tour
has been going, it's been OK.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Dec. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
