<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PMs-APonTV-BennyHill Adv22   11-21 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>PMs-AP on TV-Benny Hill, Adv 22,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PM Wed Nov. 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Benny Hill Takes Manhattan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Benny Hill was a lad, his grandad took him
to places of learning in London. These places had revues called
``Piccadilly Spangles'' or ``Toujours La Femme,'' and dance troupes
like ``The Saucy Girls.''
   A fine education. But what most interested him was the
``prin-com,'' the principal comedian. Little Benny saw that the
prin-com got lots of laughter and hugs and kisses from all the
dancing girls.
   ``I'd think, `That's not a bad life,''' he recalls. ``And I
think that's when I got hooked.''
   Thus it has been for most of Hill's working life _ dancing girls
in minimalist costumes, slighty naughty comedy, word-play, a bit of
music hall. Much of it still is on display on about 100 U.S. TV
stations as the syndicated ``The Benny Hill Show.''
   Sight gags abound in his shows. A recent one here showed him as
a ship's captain about to sing. As he opened his mouth, the ship's
foghorn made what sounded like a basso whoopee cushion being sat on.
   It bothers him not that some dare call this vulgar. ``You can do
a show for six of your friends or you can do a show for as many
people as possible. I'd rather make a hundred million people
laugh.''
   His half-hour shows, seen since 1979 in the United States,
actually are bits and pieces of the three to five one-hour specials
he usually makes each year in London. He reckons he's made about 70
in 20 years.
   He usually takes four days to rehearse each one, then five to
film them. The skits are rapid-fire. Not so the writing of them.
   The longest part is the writing, he says: ``I write the show on
trains, on buses, in hotel rooms on the beach at St. Tropez.'' His
voice trails off and he smiles.
   This is far better than the early days, when he was a struggling
young straight-man-turned-comic in music halls, pubs and the army
camps where, during and shortly after World War II, he honed his
entertainer's skills.
   The army pay was minimal, he notes, ``but it was a very good
audience. You didn't have to sweat blood for them.''
   The man the British tabloids call ``King Leer'' spoke of these
things while on a recent visit to Manhattan to case the joint for a
one-hour special. He'll tape it here _ at least sketches on the
streets _ in April or May.
   Some comics, when off-stage, are said to be quiet, anguished
souls who are on a first-name basis with the dreads. Not Hill, 64,
a lifelong bachelor.
   Sitting in an office here with Dennis Kirkland, for 20 years the
producer-director of his shows, he remains an epic in extrovert,
skittering from thought to thought, accent to accent.
   The tour of accents in understandable. Hill's cast of characters
is many and varied, ranging from a Japanese warrior to a French
waiter at the Hotel Sordide. But he has Shakespeare time logged,
too, as Bottom in a TV production of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
   He admires the fine British comic, Spike Milligan: ``An
original.'' Also W.C. Fields, one of his heroes. And Danny Thomas,
whose gentle tales of family life might seem an odd choice, given
Hill's quick-hit style of humor.
   He first saw Thomas in 1948, in London. ``He was the first comic
I'd seen who spoke the truth, or I thought it was the truth,'' Hill
says.
   Most British comics did quick jokes,
a-funny-thing-happened-to-me-on-the-way-to gags, he says. ``But
when Danny Thomas talks about his home, he seems to be telling the
truth, and that's why it's more funny.''
   During his visit here, Hill briefly visited with a civilian, a
fan named Donald Trump. Trump, as the world knows, is somewhat
wealthy.
   Hill also is in the chips, although to a lesser extent. Unlike
Trump, he lives quietly, without flash, and sometimes takes buses.
This makes the British tabloids consider him eccentric.
   He in turn considers them eccentric. At one point in the
interview, he mentions that a news photographer in London spent 12
weeks perched in a tree to get a shot _ not involving him _ of a
furtive affair-in-progress.
   But that is the way of the tabloids back home, he says, and why
he is wary of journalists there. Eyes twinkling, Benny Hill quotes
what he says is a British saying:
   ``The only reason that people believe truth is stranger than
fiction is because they're not so used to reading it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   AND NOW, FOR SOMETHING COMPLETELY DIFFERENT _ CBS'
post-Thanksgiving fare on Friday night will include yet another
awards show, ``Grammy Living Legends.'' The Grammy, lest we forget,
is the music industry's Oscar. Four persons determined to be living
legends (Willie Nelson, Smokey Robinson, Liza Minnelli, and Andrew
Lloyd Webber) will be honored on the two-hour broadcast, and the
guest performers range from the Pet Shop Boys to Gene Autry.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Nov. 22</NOTE>
