<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv22   11-21 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 22,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Nov. 22 ^Temporary Work Force Growing,
Changing With Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>Editor's Note: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIE AICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial need forced Karen Coats back into the
workplace four years ago, but temporary employment has since
allowed her to spend the time she needs with her two teen-age boys.
   ``There's spurts of time when home is the priority,'' Mrs. Coats
said. ``I totally lose touch with what's going on at home with my
husband and kids if I work 40 hours a week.''
   Mrs. Coats, 37, of Indianapolis, is just one of many Americans
flocking to temporary employment agencies. Some are parents seeking
flexibility. Others are students seeking summer jobs, housewives or
retirees looking to relieve boredom or people easing back into the
workplace. Some make temporary work their career.
   ``The image people have of temporaries is, `Oh, these are people
who can't get a full-time job,''' said Laurie Andersen, information
specialist at Manpower Temporary Services. ``But that is passe.''
   Manpower Inc., based in surburban Milwaukee, is the world's
largest temporary agency, employing about 1 million people a year,
Ms. Andersen said. Manpower has 1,450 offices and 300,000 customer
companies in 33 countries.
   Britain's Blue Arrow PLC bought Manpower in 1987, but in a
switch, Manpower President Mitchell Fromstein became the chief
executive of the smaller Blue Arrow.
   Flexibility and the chance to make extra money are primary
reasons single and married parents choose temporary employment, she
said. Temporaries can tell the agency if they prefer long-term or
short-term assignments and can refuse a call to work, she said.
   ``Many temporaries are secondary wage earners and responsible
for running the household and taking care of the children,'' she
said. ``They don't have the pressing need to work 40 hours a week.''
   Ms. Andersen said temporary workers' wages depend on the job,
company and location. A file clerk with minimal skills could make
$5 an hour, while people with specialized computer skills can earn
more than $20 an hour, she said.
   Some workers who have a need for full-time employment still rely
on temporary work either as a career or as a steppingstone to more
permanent jobs.
   ``Temporary work has given me an overview of what's available in
the employment arena,'' said Marianne DuBois, 41, a single parent
who moved to Grand Rapids, Mich., from California last summer. ``It
does meet my needs at this point.''
   For many people, the biggest drawbacks of temporary work are the
lack of employment security and health and pension benefits that
regular employees get. But many temporary agencies now offer
employee benefits such as insurance coverage and paid vacations
after a certain length of service.
   ``It's great for me,'' said Pam Skallinger of Maplewood, Mich.,
who has been a temporary for six years. ``I've got all the benefits
plus the flexibility.
   ``It gives me a chance to be a good mother and give my all to my
assignment when I have one,'' she said.
   College students make up a large part of the temporary work
force for several reasons, said Jim Dinsmore, public relations
manager for Kelly Services Inc. in Troy, Mich.
   ``It gives a lot of students the chance to work during the
summers but it's also a good way to get exposed to the job market
for recent graduates,'' he said.
   Temporary agencies also provide a chance for companies to see
workers in action before committing to hire them permanently.
   Manpower's workforce went from 330,000 in 1979 to 1 million this
year, and Kelly's rose from 330,000 to 550,000 during the same
period, the companies reported.
   While more men are entering the temporary workforce, they make
up only about 10 percent to 15 percent of their current employees.
Most temporaries are office workers.
   One area of major growth has been older workers. Workers aged 55
and up make up 15 percent of Manpower's workforce. Kelly has an
Encore program to recruit and retain senior employees.
   ``We get a lot of older, retired people who are bored,'' he
said. ``They want to stay busy but they can't work full time or
they might lose their social security.''
   Dinsmore said he believes temporary workers have found a
permanent spot with many companies.
   ``A lot of companies have temporary workers as a line item on
their budgets,'' he said. ``It's becoming more and more popular to
use temporaries for special projects instead of just to fill in for
sick people or vacation time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Nov. 22.</NOTE>
</DOC>
