<HEAD>Fors Won't Rid Schools of Drugs</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   WASHINGTON _ South Carolina school principal Ben Nesbit became
suspicious when two students who had been suspended for illicit
drug use passed a drug test with little trouble. ``We found out a
couple of weeks ago that there's a chemical that washes drugs out
of the system,'' said Nesbit, whose school has received national
acclaim for its drug-fighting efforts. Education officials say such
episodes show that simplistic demands for universal drug testing _
and other quick-fix proposals _ won't win the war on drugs in the
schools.
   AM-Drugs in Schools, by Tamara Henry, moving Nov. 21 as b0357,
for Monday AMs, Nov. 27.
   LaserPhoto WX12 of Nov. 21.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALSO FOR SUNDAY:    </HEAD>
<HEAD>VATICAN-SOVIET SUMMIT: Long Way From Bolshevik `War on God'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   VATICAN CITY _ ``How many divisions does the pope have?'' Josef
V. Stalin asked snidely in the 1930s when confronted with Vatican
protests of the Soviet suppression of religion. A half century
later, Pope John Paul II rendered a reply for his Vatican: ``Its
army is powerful: 800 million Catholics.'' This coming Friday in
the Vatican, John Paul II, spiritual leader of those Roman Catholic
legions, will meet Mikhail Gorbachev, leader of a nation that
harbors atheism as official policy. They meet with olive branches.
   BC-Vatican-Soviet, an AP Extra by Mary Beth Sheridan, moved Nov.
20 as b0695-b0696.
   LaserPhoto ROM1 of Nov. 20.
   
