<HEAD>IRAN AFTER KHOMEINI: Radicals Complain Legacy Is Ignored as Taboos
Ease</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Six months after the death of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, old taboos are breaking down in Iran. A heady whiff of
social and religious tolerance is in the air. But President Hashemi
Rafsanjani, leader of the so-called pragmatists, treads gingerly
between preserving Khomeini's legacy of Islamic values and opening
up the country after a decade of turmoil.
