<HEAD>CAROLINA AFTER HUGO: Thousands May Slip Into Poverty</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Hurricane Hugo, the greatest natural disaster
to befall South Carolina in a century, swept thousands of the poor
and near-poor into a maelstrom from which many will take years to
escape. ``You've got to do the best you can. It's hard until
something comes around,'' said Rosalie Johnson, whose modest home
in Mount Pleasant was destroyed by the storm surge.
   BC-Hugo-Poor, by Bruce Smith, will move in advance.
   With LaserPhoto.
   
   With:
   
   MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. _ The air is acrid with the smell of mud
and decaying marsh grass as flies swarm around cast-off pieces of
lives shattered by the 15-foot waves of Hurricane Hugo. Relief has
been slow in coming to this rural hamlet near the plush Wild Dunes
resort. BC-Hugo-Hamlin Beach.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RURAL HEALTH CARE: Improved Medical Insurance Urged by Cooperative</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   WASHINGTON _ Rural advocates have for years urged more attention
to the medical needs of sparsely settled areas, the small towns and
farms where a fourth of America's people live. A study done for the
National Rural Electric Cooperative Association says improved
health care insurance would help as much as anything, ranking with
jobs, water and sewer systems.
