<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-21 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0759</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-running battle for LIN Broadcasting
Corp. took another twist as McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
increased its cash tender offer for a controlling interest in LIN
by $625 million to $3.4 billion.
   McCaw also said Monday that if its offer succeeded, it would
have LIN borrow $425 million to buy McCaw stock which then would be
distributed to remaining LIN shareholders.
   New York-based LIN said it would review the offer. It has
already accepted an offer for its cellular interests from BellSouth
Corp., the regional telephone company based in Atlanta. LIN
shareholders are to vote on the BellSouth proposal Jan. 12.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farm chemical trade association said a total
ban on the use of crop fungicides would boost consumer food prices
by 13 percent and reduce the supply of fruits, vegetables and
peanuts by 24 percent.
   Jay Vroom, president of the National Agricultural Chemicals
Association, said Monday he wanted to call attention to the
``enormous benefit and the very small risk'' that result from the
use of fungicides and other high-tech farming methods on food
supplies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca said
sluggish car and truck sales may force the company to increase
budget cuts above a planned $1 billion by the end of 1990.
   Iacocca also said Monday that assembly plant closings were
possible for the nation's third-largest automaker.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. said it agreed to pay
$333 million in cash for Management Science America Inc., which
sells mainframe computer software.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said Monday the companies reached a definitive
merger agreement at a price of $18.50 a share after unanimous
approval by MSA's board of directors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. is cutting
stockbroker commissions for the first time in 15 years, reflecting
an industry-wide slowdown in brokerage activity by individual
investors.
   Shearson, the nation's second-largest retail brokerage, said
Monday the portion of the commission that a broker gets for selling
investment products would be trimmed by 1 to 2 percentage points in
1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of Reynolds Wrap aluminum foil
announced a joint venture to build a $200 million aluminum foil
production plant in the Soviet Union.
   Under the deal signed Monday in Rome, a subsidiary of
Richmond-based Reynolds Metals Co., six Soviet organizations and
two Italian companies will jointly own the aluminum plant.
   The plant in the south-central Siberian town of Sayanogorsk is
slated to produce 47,000 tons of foil and foil products each year
and employ 650 people. Production is expected to begin in 1992.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the United States ended three days of
talks on wood products trade without an agreement on increasing
U.S. lumber exports to Japan.
   Negotiators on both sides said Monday the talks were
constructive but that no agreement was reached on U.S. claims that
Japan is keeping U.S. wood products out of Japanese markets.
Negotiators agreed to continue talks in December or early next
year, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditional Thanksgiving meal of
turkey, cranberries, stuffing and pie will cost more this year, a
Purdue University economist says.
   Food prices rose about 5 percent in 1989, compared with a 4
percent increase from 1987 to 1988, said agricultural economist
Joseph N. Uhl.
   The good news for Thanksgiving is that turkey prices are lower
this year because of increased supplies and more grocery specials.
Ham costs about the same as it did last year, Uhl said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. International Trade Commission ruled
that small business telephone systems imported from Japan and
Taiwan cause harm to American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and smaller
domestic U.S. manufacturers.
   The split decision Monday opened the way for U.S. Customs
starting next month to start collecting ``dumping'' duties of more
than 100 percent from importers of one Taiwan maker and several
Japanese makers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly Monday as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials lost 20.62 points to close at 2,632.04.
   The dollar fell against most major foreign currencies.
   Bond prices rose in slow trading.
   Copper futures prices fell sharply; precious metals and energy
futures rose; and grain, soybean, livestock and pork futures
finished lower.
</TEXT>
