<FIRST>r f BC-LINChronology     11-21 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-LIN Chronology,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of Buyout Overtures Involving LIN Broadcasting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LIN-McCaw, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the buyout overtures
involving LIN Broadcasting Corp., a New York-based cellular
telephone, broadcasting and specialty publishing company.
   June 6 _ McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. proposes a buyout at
$120 a share in a deal that values LIN's 53.9 million shares at
nearly $6.5 billion.
   June 20 _ LIN says its board determined the McCaw offer is
inadequate, and directs its management to evaluate alternatives.
   July 10 _ McCaw lowers its offer for LIN to $110 a share in
light of an unfavorable court decision involving LIN's claims to
certain cellular interests in New York and Philadelphia.
   July 13 _ McCaw and LIN say they are in negotiations about McCaw
paying $127.50 a share in cash and stock for each share of LIN
common stock.
   July 21 _ McCaw and LIN say their talks have been suspended.
   July 27 _ LIN Chairman Donald Pels sets a July 31 deadline for
an agreement with McCaw on a buyout at $127.50 a share.
   July 31 _ LIN's deadline passes without agreement.
   Sept. 11 _ LIN and BellSouth Corp. say they have agreed to merge
their domestic cellular telephone interests. LIN shareholders also
would get a special dividend of $20 a share and stock in a new
company that would consist of its television station interests.
   Oct. 3 _ McCaw announces plans to buy Metromedia Corp.'s
interest in a New York City cellular franchise for $1.9 billion and
plans to sell its Southeastern franchises for $1.3 billion to
Contel Corp.
   Oct. 10 _ McCaw revises its bid for LIN, proposing to pay $125 a
share for 22 million LIN shares. With its holdings of 5.1 million
LIN shares, the proposal would give McCaw 50.3 percent of LIN's
stock.
   Oct. 27 _ LIN and BellSouth amend their merger agreement offer.
LIN shareholders will get a special dividend of $42 a share, in
addition to stock in the spinoff television company and the
cellular telephone company.
   Nov. 16 _ LIN schedules Jan. 12 shareholders meeting for a vote
on its deal with BellSouth.
   Nov. 20 _ McCaw revises offer for LIN, proposing to pay $150 a
share for 22.5 million shares of LIN, giving McCaw 51.2 percent of
LIN's stock. It also plans to have LIN borrow $425 million to Buy
McCaw stock for distribution as a dividend to LIN shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     11-21 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction with rates on six-month bills
dropping to their lowest level since July.
   The Treasury Department sold $8.0 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.61 percent, down from 7.68 percent
last week. Another $8.0 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.40 percent, down from 7.51 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.52
percent on Oct. 23 and six-month bills averaged 7.35 percent on
July 31.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.86 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,809.80 and 7.79 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,627.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.71
percent last week, down from 7.87 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
