<FIRST>r f PM-Lin-McCaw Bjt   11-21 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lin-McCaw, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN, BellSouth Review Latest McCaw Offer for LIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-LIN Chronology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The music is still playing in the marathon
contest for control of LIN Broadcasting Corp., and neither suitor
is ready to give up.
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., which started the dance with
an unsolicited buyout offer in early June, said Monday it was
increasing its cash tender offer for a controlling interest in LIN
by $625 million to $3.4 billion.
   McCaw also said that if its offer succeeded, it would have LIN
borrow $425 million to buy McCaw stock which then would be
distributed to remaining LIN shareholders.
   ``Our amended offer, which has a value more than $800 million
higher than our earlier offer, is clearly the superior alternative
for LIN's shareholders,'' said McCaw's chairman and chief
executive, Craig O. McCaw.
   The alternative is a competing offer from BellSouth Corp., the
Atlanta-based regional telephone company that has agreed to merge
its cellular telephone operations with LIN's cellular business.
   New York-based LIN said its board would review the revised
proposal ``on a timely basis,'' but urged its shareholders against
tendering to McCaw until its board announced its recommendation.
   BellSouth said it was studying the revised offer but that its
first reading indicated its own deal with LIN offered more
``strength and value'' to LIN shareholders.
   Analysts said they valued McCaw's new offer at $123 to $128 a
share, compared with $110 to $113 a share under McCaw's previous
offer and $117 to $124 a share under the BellSouth offer.
   ``I am sure that BellSouth will come back with a higher offer,''
said Geoffrey Johnson, telecommunications analyst for Argus
Research Corp.
   In over-the-counter trading, LIN climbed $4.37{ a share to close
at $120.12{, while McCaw fell $1.25 to $35.75. BellSouth rose 50
cents a share to $51.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   McCaw, based in Kirkland, Wash., asked LIN to put its new offer
to a vote at the previously scheduled Jan. 12 meeting, at which
LIN's shareholders are being asked to consider BellSouth's offer.
   McCaw said that if LIN refuses, it intends to ``take our case
directly to the LIN stockholders'' by mounting a proxy fight for
control of the LIN board.
   McCaw is the nation's largest cellular company, but LIN's plan
to merge its cellular operations with those of BellSouth would
create a cellular company larger than McCaw.
   Under its latest offer, McCaw said it would pay $150 a share for
22.5 million LIN shares, or $3.4 billion. Its previous offer was
$125 per share for 22 million shares, a total of $2.75 billion.
   McCaw already owns about 5.1 million LIN shares, and the revised
offer would give it 51.2 percent of LIN's 53.9 million shares.
   In addition, McCaw said that as soon as possible after the
tender offer is completed McCaw would have LIN buy $425 million of
McCaw stock and distribute it to LIN shareholders, at a value of
$16.17 in stock for each LIN share held.
   The new offer expires at midnight EST Dec. 15, although it would
be extended until the LIN shareholder meeting if LIN puts the bid
to a vote.
   Under the deal with BellSouth, LIN shareholders would get a cash
dividend of $42 a share, stock in the new cellular company that
would be created by the merger of LIN and BellSouth cellular
interests and stock in a new company that would consist of LIN's
seven television stations.
   The participants in both deals have offered guarantees that LIN
shareholders who hold on to their stock in the cellular company
will get private market value for it several years down the road.
   BellSouth and LIN said in announcing their merger plan in
October that they felt the deal could be closed in the first
quarter of 1990.
   McCaw said regulatory approvals could delay the BellSouth-LIN
deal for up to a year. McCaw said its deal could be closed much
sooner and said it would demonstrate its confidence in that by
paying interest of 12 percent annually on its cash tender offer if
the offer closes after March 31, 1990.
   McCaw said last week it has received firm commitments totaling
$3 billion from a 22-bank syndicate, which, with about $1.2 billion
of its own cash and marketable securities, is enough to complete
the tender offer.
</TEXT>
