<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WallStreetSlump Bjt   11-21 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Slump, Bjt,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Commission Reduction Could Herald More Wall Street Cutbacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dramatic reduction in stockbroker commissions
by Wall Street's second-largest firm heralds further retrenchment
during an industrywide slowdown in brokerage activity by individual
investors, analysts say.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. announced a rollback Monday of 1 to
2 percentage points for 1990 in the portion of the commission a
broker gets for selling investment products. It was Shearson's
first commission cut in 15 years.
   ``That amounts to a lot of money when it gets all done,'' said
an official at one large Wall Street firm who asked not to be
identified. ``I'm surprised at that.''
   Analysts said the reduction was the first direct commission
cutback in the last year by a brokerage house.
   Business has lagged on Wall Street partly because of an exodus
of individual investors since the October 1987 stock market crash,
and firms have laid off thousands of employees in an effort to save
money.
   Brokerages also have imposed a variety of customer fees that go
directly to the brokerage but do not affect the size of brokers'
commissions. But firms such as Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., the nation's
biggest brokerage, and Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. said Monday they
do not plan to reduce broker commissions.
   Such fees result in ``a slightly higher take for the company
than it does for the representative, but it's not as brutal as
this,'' said James P. Hanbury, a securities industry analyst with
Wertheim Schroeder Inc.
   ``You're trying to raise the revenue to the firm because the
overall business is not that robust,'' he said.
   Hanbury said he expected other Wall Street houses to cut
commissions. ``Either the business gets better or you're going to
see it, and I think you're going to see it,'' he said.
   Shearson, which is 61 percent owned by American Express Co., has
been contemplating trimming the commission a broker gets, known as
the payout rate, by 4 to 5 percentage points over the next four to
five years, Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill said.
   In 1989, Shearson retail brokers brought in commissions
averaging $228,000. Shearson returned 46.5 percent of the total to
brokers and their supervisors in the form of direct payments,
employee benefits and deferred payments.
   In 1986, when an average Shearson retail broker brought in
$265,000 in commissions, the payout rate was 43 percent. Wall
Street officials said most firms' payout rates were are about 37
percent.
   Shearson, stung by declining profits and a low stock price,
announced earlier this month it was laying off up to 800 employees
and restructuring its senior management.
   While not slashing commissions, virtually all Wall Street firms
have imposed ``handling'' fees on customer accounts to help enhance
revenue without boosting expenses.
   Earlier this month, for example, Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. imposed a
$2.50 handling charge on all individual investors' stock and bond
trades. Merrill Lynch boosted its service charge last year to $2.35
for each trade from $1.85.
   The Securities Industry Association expects third-quarter
industry pre-tax profits to be about half of the $1 billion in
pre-tax profits in the second quarter.
   The second-quarter profit marked a sharp jump from $200 million
in the previous quarter and was attributed to increased volume and
declining interest rates. The bulk of the recovery came from the 10
largest investment banks, which recovered from $63 million in
first-quarter losses.
   But retail commissions accounted for just 17 percent of revenue
in the first half of the year, unchanged from 1988 but down 25
percent from 1987 and 35 percent from 1980.
   The Shearson cut is expected to hurt the firm in hiring new
stockbrokers. Shearson was one of several Wall Street firms to
reduce its in-house broker training programs after the 1987 crash
in favor of recruiting from other firms. Officials said they
expected some brokers to leave the company in protest.
   ``It's difficult to go to the troops in a tough market where
they're breaking their backs and say we're cutting you,'' the Wall
Street official said. ``The last people you want to go to is the
producers.''
</TEXT>
