<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TakeoverCurbs     11-21 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Takeover Curbs,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Discuss Bills To Curb Corporate Takeovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation concerned with the problems caused
by corporate takeovers has been introduced by at least four
senators sponsoring separate bills.
   The Senate Banking Committee's securities subcommittee heard
testimony Monday about bills that seek to curb takeovers and
leveraged buyouts while protecting shareholders' rights.
   The senators appearing before the subcommittee were Howard M.
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, Terry Sanford, D-N.C., Arlen Specter, R-Pa.,
and Richard Shelby, D-Ala.
   Many in Congress are concerned that the wave of hostile
takeovers, mergers and acquisitions and corporate raids for profit
are hurting the economy and turning American management's attention
away from long-term planning.
   The subcommittee chairman, Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.,
said he and the ranking Republican, Sen. John Heinz of
Pennsylvania, called the hearing ``to provide a record for
consideration of these measures in the next session.''
   Congressional leaders were trying to wrap up business this week
so they could adjourn for the holidays until January.
   All four bills would limit or close the 10-day window stock
purchasers have to declare their intentions after they buy 5
percent or more of a company's stock.
   Under the Williams Act, anyone acquiring 5 percent of a
company's stock must disclose their holdings and whether they
intend a takeover within 10 days in a Securities and Exchange
Commission document known as a 13-D.
   Most of the bills would cut that 10-day period to curtail what
Specter called ``creeping takeovers.''
   ``Because the individual can continue purchasing shares during
the 10-day period,'' he said, ``his or her ownership can greatly
exceed 5 percent by the time the public actually is informed.''
   His bill would require disclosure within 48 hours. Sanford's
would cut it to five days. The five-day limit would kick in if the
purchaser acquires more than 5 percent in Shelby's bill. And
Metzenbaum's bill would cut the limit to 4 percent and require
diclosure within one day.
   The senators also want to curb the practice of paying
``greenmail.''
   ``Too often a raider making a play for a company becomes rich
when a corporation is forced to buy its own stock at a premium,''
said Metzenbaum. ``It's blackmail, but we've made it more dignified
and call it `greenmail,''' he added.
   His bill would prohibit the payment of greenmail unless approved
by a majority of those holding the outstanding voting securities of
the issuer.
   He and other senators said small shareholders often don't have
enough say in whether greenmail should be paid.
   Shelby's bill would allow a company to recover any profit made
by a person who sells the company its own stock if that person
holds more than 3 percent of the company's stock and has held it
for less than a year.
   Specter's bill combined elements of the two bills _ allowing a
company to recover its greenmanil payments, unless the payments
were approved by a vote of the majority of the aggregate
outstanding voting securities of the issuer.
   Sanford said, ``We need to shift the debate and focus our
legislation away from the old `raiders' versus `entrenched
management' fight to the more fundamental problems of encouraging
corporate management to manage for the long term and encouraging
investors to take a longer-term view.''
   His bill would treat 5 percent holders of a company's stock as
`insiders' and block their ability to make a profit on stock of the
company bought or sold within a six-month period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
