<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     11-21 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0295</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed in early trading
today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 2.77 points at
2,634.81 at 11 am EST.
   The broader market was lower, however. Declining issues edged
out advances by around 6-to-5 on the New York Stock Exchange, with
642 issues down, 532 up and 556 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 50.95 million shares.
   Analysts said an early advance ran out of steam when the market
took a closer look at a government report today on inflation that
was slightly worse than most analysts had been expecting.
   The Labor Department reported that consumer prices shot up 0.5
percent last month as higher gasoline and food costs gave the
country its biggest inflation surge since May.
   The government blamed the rise on a jump in gasoline costs,
higher prices for new cars and a sharp turnaround in fruit and
vegetable prices.
   ``There were some disturbing elements in there,'' said
Hildegarde Zagorski, an analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The market appeared to be shaky after Monday's 20.62-point drop
in the Dow average, caused by a selling wave that hit defense
contractors especially hard.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
edged down 0.01 to 188.02.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
0.46 at 371.02.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, General Electric was
down [ at 59, Texas Instruments had dropped 1\ to 28\, Philip
Morris had slipped ] to 40~ and IBM was unchanged at 98}.
