<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LincolnS&amp;L 2ndLd-Writethru f0037 11-21 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0037,0900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adamant Wall Denies Political Influence in Lincoln Decisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with opening statements from committee
members, pick up at 11th pvs, The chief... A version moving on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrift regulator M. Danny Wall, acknowledging
mistakes in his handling of the nation's largest savings and loan
failure, today vigorously defended his overall performance and
declared, ``No political figure influenced my decisions.''
   ``We have all learned some tough lessons from this case. We made
some mistakes, and in retrospect, we would do some things
differently,'' Wall said in testimony prepared for delivery under
oath to the House Banking Committee.
   The panel, chaired by Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, was
conducting the last of six scheduled hearings investigating the
collapse of Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif.
   Gonzalez, in an opening statement, chastized Wall for rejecting
a 1987 recommendation from field examiners in San Francisco who
wanted to seize Lincoln.
   San Francisco ``sounded an eight-alarm warning ... (but) for 23
months and two weeks (Washington) failed to take definitive and
effective action,'' he said.
   The committee also planned to hear from the thrift's owner,
Charles H. Keating Jr., but it was unclear whether Keating would
refuse to testify by asserting his constitutional protection
against self-incrimination.
   Keating, a Phoenix, Ariz., millionaire, is the target of a
federal grand jury probe and of a $1.1 billion fraud and
racketeering suit filed by regulators. Congressional sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said his attorneys were
advising him to remain silent today.
   Rep. Chalmers Wylie, R-Ohio, who has been critical of Wall at
times, drew a contrast between the regulator and Keating.
   ``Danny Wall has made a career of public service, while Mr.
Keating has made a career of self-service,'' he said.
   Democrats on the committee have been focusing on Wall's
performance, while Republicans also have used the sessions to bring
out the role of five senators, four of them senior Democrats, who
intervened on Lincoln's behalf after accepting $1.3 million in
political contributions from Keating.
   They met with regulators on Lincoln's behalf in April 1987,
three months before Wall took office as chairman of the Federal
Home Loan Bank Board, now called the Office of Thrift Supervision.
The five are: Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.;
Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.; John Glenn, D-Ohio, and John McCain,
R-Ariz.
   Wall said in his formal testimony that he had no direct
knowledge of that incident. But he declared, ``My decisions in the
Lincoln case were my own. They were devoid of any political
influence. I was not under the spell of Charles Keating.''
   Wall has acknowledged receiving calls concerning Lincoln from
three members of Congress _ DeConcini, Cranston and Rep. Carroll
Hubbard, D-Ky. But he said, ``Those calls were well within the
limits of propriety.''
   ``Their inquiries were for a status report or to urge action,
but in no way were they attempts to tell me what action to take,''
Wall said.
   Hubbard, in an emotional defense of himself, told the Banking
Committee he made the call at a request of former Rep. John
Rouselot, R-Calif., who was then seeking to arrange the sale of
Lincoln.
   ``I have no relationship with Mr. Charles Keating,'' he said,
adding, ``I'm proud to call Danny Wall my friend.''
   The chief thrift regulator's defense comes after weeks of
critical testimony and may be too late to secure his political
future. In response to a call from Gonzalez for Wall's resignation,
President Bush said a week ago he was ``not closing the door'' on
the Wall's departure. Bush added he would make changes if it is
proven that regulators were not aggressive enough.
   Much of the testimony in the previous five all-day hearings has
concentrated on why Wall rejected a 1987 recommendation from
examiners in his regional office to seize Lincoln and put a stop to
unsound practices.
   Instead, Wall transferred the jurisdiction over Lincoln from San
Francisco to agency headquarters in Washington and ordered a second
examination, delaying Lincoln's seizure until April of this year.
   Gonzalez blames the regulator for the delay, which he says
ballooned the expected $2 billion cost of the failure.
   Wall's prepared testimony rejected that, saying his decisions,
at most, delayed action less than six months, adding, ``The
preponderance of the losses at Lincoln was embedded prior to the
time I became chairman of the bank board.''
   However, he admitted he should have insisted officials from the
San Francisco case participate in the second examination of
Lincoln, even though he still believes their first examination did
not turn up enough information to legally justify seizing Lincoln.
   ``The San Francisco examiners found smoke, but no fire,'' he
said.
   Meanwhile, a class-action federal lawsuit was filed in Los
Angeles on Monday by Lincoln investors seeking to freeze more than
$100 million in investor funds that they contend were illegally
transported overseas.
   The lawsuit contends Lincoln misled 22,000 investors into buying
nearly $200 million in nonrated high-risk securities. The suit
contends Keating and his family converted the funds to their own
use by investing them in banks and companies in Switzerland, the
Bahamas and Panama. A court hearing was scheduled for Dec. 4.
</TEXT>
