<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Narrowly Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as the
markets struggled to recover from Monday's weak close.
   Follow-through selling provided much of the downward pressure
but losses were limited by an Agriculture Department report that a
near-record amount of corn was inspected for export last week and
by a downward revision in a private estimate of U.S. stocks of
soybean oil.
   The USDA said late Monday it inspected 71.38 million bushels of
corn for export during the week ending last Thursday compared with
60.87 million the previous week and 46.41 million for the same week
a year ago.
   The National Oilseed Processers Association announced it had
revised its estimate of U.S. soybean oil stocks as of the end of
October to 378 million pounds from 442 million pounds.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1\ cents lower to } cent
higher with December at $4.09{ a bushel; corn futures were
unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $2.37\ a bushel; oats
were 1 cent lower to { cent higher with December at $1.44{ a
bushel; soybeans were { cent lower to 2 cents higher with January
at $5.84} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .25 cent higher with December at
75.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with November at 83.07 cents a pound; live hogs were .03
cent to .33 cent lower with December at 49.20 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .50 cent lower to .15 cent higher with February
at 62.40 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures were mixed on Monday while pork futures settled
lower.
</TEXT>
