<SECOND>PM-Georgia Gulf,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Gulf Says Not Interested in Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Gulf Corp. said today it has decided
against a merger with NL Industries, the Houston-based company
controlled by billionaire Harold Simmons that had made a $1.1
billion takeover offer.
   The Atlanta-based chemical manufacturing company said in a
statement that recapitalizing by borrowing more money would be the
best way to increase its stock value.
   Georgia Gulf had hired Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. to advise it on
options after NL made its initial offer in August. Alternatives
included recapitalization, a merger or some other transaction
involving a third party.
   NL made its latest offer, worth $50 a share, in October.
   Georgia Gulf said in the statement that ``its representatives
have concluded discussions with third parties who had indicated an
interest in a possible business combination with or acquisition of
Georgia Gulf.''
   No details of the possible recapitalization were disclosed. The
company said a special meeting of stockholders would be called once
the arrangements are worked out.
   J. Landis Martin, president of NL, was out of his office this
morning and could not be reached immediately for comment.
</TEXT>
