<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Jumps Above 400 Dollars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Tuesday to eight-month lows
against other major currencies in moderate European trading.
   Gold surged above $400 an ounce in London for the first time in
10 months.
   Dealers said the West German mark rose against all currencies
amid speculation by non-German investors that the opening of East
Germany's borders would boost economic growth in West Germany and
possibly force the Bundesbank to raise interest rates.
   But West German traders and economists said they doubted the
West German central bank would act soon on interest rates.
   Dealers said the dollar suffered from recent declines in U.S.
interest rates, dropping to its lowest level since late February
against the West German, French, Dutch and Italian currencies.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.24 Japanese yen to a closing 144.43
yen. Later, in London, it fell further to 143.95 yen.
   Other late dollar rates compared with late Monday's prices,
included: 1.8200 West German marks, down from 1.8360; 1.6200 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6315; 6.2000 French francs, down from 6.2465;
2.0537 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0760; 1,341.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,351.00; 1.1705 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1712.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5645 from $1.5595 late
Monday.
   Bullion dealers said gold benefited from the dollar's fall and
from the turmoil in Eastern Europe.
   Gold jumped more than $6 in London to a late bid price of
$402.75 a troy ounce, compared with $396.50 bid late Monday.
   In Zurich, the metal jumped to $399 bid from $396.65 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.21 to close at a bid $398.61.
   Silver fell in London to a late bid price of $5.71 a troy ounce,
down from $5.74 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
