<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     11-21 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0357</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was lower in afternoon trading
today, weighed down by new worries about inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 5.97 points at
2,626.07 at 2 pm EST, after being up slightly for most of the
trading session.
   Declining issues edged out advances by around 9-to-5 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 885 issues down, 504 up and 538 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 105.25 million shares.
   Analysts said an early advance ran out of steam when the market
took a closer look at a government report today on inflation that
was slightly worse than most analysts had been expecting.
   The Labor Department reported that consumer prices shot up 0.5
percent last month as higher gasoline and food costs gave the
country its biggest inflation surge since May.
   ``That obviously didn't help'' stock prices, said Bill Raftery,
an analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   The government blamed the rise on a jump in gasoline costs,
higher prices for new cars and a sharp turnaround in fruit and
vegetable prices.
   Much of today's selling focused on stocks of companies involved
in takeover attempts, analysts said.
   The market appeared to be shaky after Monday's 20.62-point drop
in the Dow average, caused by a selling wave that hit defense
contractors especially hard.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
fallen 0.72 to 187.31.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.80 at 370.68.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Philip Morris had lost
| to 40| and Texas Instruments had tumbled 1 point to 28{.
   Georgia Gulf had dropped 7[ to 45\. The chemical manufacturer
announced that it has decided against a merger with NL Industries,
the company controlled by billionaire Harold Simmons that had made
a $1.1 billion takeover offer.
   General Electric was up [ at 59\, McDonalds had risen | to 32
and Avon Products also was up |, at 36.
</TEXT>
