<FIRST>r f AM-CFTC-Monieson     11-21 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC-Monieson,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Close Case Against Former Merc Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government lawyers said Tuesday that former
Chicago Mercantile Exchange Chairman Brian Monieson knew that two
of his employees were bilking customers of thousands of dollars.
   But the statements contrasted with testimony by others,
including Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter, who said
Monieson enjoyed an unblemished reputation in the futures industry.
   Attorneys for the Commodity Futures Trading Comission, which
regulates the nation's commodity markets, said Monieson was aware
that two of his employees _ Ira P. Greenspon and Norman K. Furlett
_ at GNP Commodities Inc. of Chicago were cheating customers.
   Greenspon and Furlett, both now of Malibu, Calif., deny any
wrongdoing, as does Monieson, of Northbrook, Ill.
   The testimony came at a hearing before an administrative law
judge on a complaint against three men brought by the CFTC. If
found guilty, Monieson, Furlett and Greenspon could be permanently
barred from trading.
   ``What did he (Monieson) do? Sent Norm Furlett and Ira Greenspon
back to handle more orders,'' government attorney Patricia Donahue
said.
   Monieson's lawyer, Jerrold Salzman, acknowledged that traders
``may have injured customers,'' but said his client had no role and
did not supervise Furlett or Greenspon.
   ``The question is whether he failed to act in good faith,''
Salzman said. ``Mr. Monieson's conduct was appropriate.''
   ``He is chairman of the board, he is not the chief executive
officer. He has a right to rely'' on others to keep an eye on daily
operations, the attorney said.
   The government maintains Furlett and Greenspon engaged in
``allocated trades'' that defrauded customers. The term refers to
initiating futures contracts without the required customer account
numbers, then keeping profitable trades for themselves while
sticking customers with the losses.
   The government is not accusing Monieson of committing the
trades, but it claims he was told several times between June 1985
and May 1986 that Furlett and Greenspon were making bad deals.
   Futures are contracts to buy or sell commodities ranging from
orange juice to stocks at a specified price on a future date. The
contracts are traded either to lock in commodity prices in advance,
thereby reducing their financial risk, or to speculate on price
changes.
   Yeutter, who was president of the Merc when Monieson was Merc
chairman from 1983-85, was one of several character witnesses
called before Administrative Law Judge George Painter.
   ``Brian Monieson had an undisputed reputation as a man of
honesty and integrity,'' he said.
   Leo Melamed, chairman of the Merc's executive committee, said:
``I have no doubt about his integrity or his honesty. His general
reputation is very good.''
   Painter is to issue a ruling early next year after attorneys for
both sides submit final written statements.
   Melamed's decision to testify and Salzman's to defend Monieson
prompted former Sen. Thomas F. Eagleton of Missouri to resign from
the Merc's board of governors. Eagleton said Merc officials should
stay away from Monieson, not help bail him out. Salzman is the
Merc's outside counsel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
