<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-21 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices ended lower in fairly thin
trading Tuesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude,
declined 3 cents to $19.96 a barrel, after rising 16 cents in the
previous session. The February contract slipped 5 cents to $19.78
and March crude lost 7 cents to $19.58.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline for December delivery fell 0.26 cent to 51.96
cents a gallon and January lost 0.22 cent to 52.76 cents a gallon.
   No. 2 heating oil for December dipped 0.14 cent to 59.94 a
gallon and the January contract dropped 0.30 cent to 59.58 cents a
gallon.
   Analysts said trading volume was relatively light ahead of the
coming Thanksgiving Day holiday on Thursday.
   Overall, the market is holding relatively steady in anticipation
of the weekend meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, energy analysts said.
   ``The sense of the market is that there is a lack of news to go
on,'' said John H. O'Connell, analyst with Refco Inc. ``The market
is going to wait.''
   ``People are not looking for major events to come out of the
OPEC meeting given the narrow trading this week,'' said Bob Baker,
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   OPEC is expected to address the thorny issue of quota
reallocation as some of the 13 member nations press for higher
shares of the production pie. The ministers are scheduled to begin
meeting Saturday in Vienna, Austria.
</TEXT>
