<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAW-Chrysler     11-21 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW-Chrysler,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Demonstrates Outside Chrysler Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of United Auto Workers
union members chanting ``Lee lies'' paraded outside Chrysler Corp.
headquarters Tuesday to protest the closing of a car assembly plant.
   Chrysler earlier this month announced it would halt production
of Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon subcompact cars at its Jefferson
Avenue plant in early February and lay off about 1,700 workers.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca on Monday said further plant
closings may occur because of weak sales.
   ``This gives Lee Iacocca a black eye with his credibility,''
said Don Petty, chief steward of UAW Local 1264 at a Chrysler plant
in Sterling Heights.
   About 500 protesters marched behind a banner reading ``Iacocca
lied again.'' Among other signs was one picturing Iacocca as a
chicken smoking a cigar above a caption reading, ``Mr. No Show in
Louisville.''
   Iacocca has declined to attend the UAW's meeting next week in
Kentucky, the first time since 1986 he won't appear. Two Chrysler
executives are scheduled to replace Iacocca.
   The rally also gave indications that national contract
negotiations, which open next summer, could be acrimonious. UAW
contracts with Chrysler, General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
expire on Sept. 14, 1990.
   ``This is not just a rally for the Jefferson closing,'' said
Aaron Taylor, president of UAW Local 7 at the Jefferson Avenue
plant.
   Workers from Syracuse, N.Y., and Chrysler's Acustar plant in
Huntsville, Ala., joined Detroit-area workers at the march.
   ``It's a scary feeling,'' said Nancy Adams, who was laid off a
few weeks ago from Chrysler's transmission plant in Syracuse and
remains a member of Local 624.
   The company said the Jefferson Avenue plant closing is permitted
under its contract, which allows for shutdowns due to slow sales.
Omni and Horizon sales have been slumping.
   But union officials have said the move violates local and
national contracts and they are angry they were not notified about
the action before it appeared in the media.
   UAW Vice President Stan Marshall, head of the union's Chrysler
Department, said relations between the union and Chrysler are
strained because of the plant closing and Iacocca's statement in
Washington Monday that others could follow.
   UAW Region 1 Director Bob Lent said the conflict could continue
into contract negotiations.
   Said Marshall: ``I think that they are the ones trying to set
the atmosphere by Lee going out there and making all kinds of
statements, (like) well, we might have to close other assembly
plants and everything.''
</TEXT>
