<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Tops $400, Hits 10-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices topped $400 an ounce Tuesday for the first time in
nearly 10 months in a steady rise that quieted doubts about the
market's underlying strength. Other precious metals also rose.
   On other commodity markets, energy futures retreated; livestock
and meat futures were mostly higher; and grains and soybeans were
mixed.
   Gold futures settled $5.10 to $6 higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the contract for delivery in December at $404.40 a
troy ounce. The less heavily traded contract for November delivery
finished at $403.70.
   Gold futures last closed above $400 on Jan. 26.
   Silver settled 14.2 cents to 14.6 cents higher with November at
$5.834 a troy ounce.
   Analysts said they were impressed that the gold market neither
balked at the $400 level nor surged wildly after crossing it but
continued to exhibit the same quiet strength that has characterized
the market's resurgence during the past five weeks.
   ``It's been coming up gradually,'' said analyst Sharon Ziemian
of Citibank in New York.
   ``You haven't seen jumps of $20 at a pop, and those kinds of big
pops are things that tend to set the market back fairly quickly,
too,'' she said, referring to the selloffs that typically follow
sudden, sharp gains.
   Indeed, few recent buyers have taken profits in the 5{ weeks
since the gold market began rising from the $365-an-ounce area at
which it had traded for much of 1989.
   ``The holders of the metal believe its going to go higher and
that is the sign of a true bull market,'' said Don Mackay-Coghill,
chief executive officer of GoldCorp Australia, a state-owned
corporation established to market Australian precious metals.
   Mackay-Coghill, who is touring the United States to promote his
company's gold and platinum investment coins, said he was
``delighted'' with GoldCorp's sales volume.
   Investors seeking safety from the volatile stock market continue
to lead the gold rally, analysts said.
   Tuesday's government report that consumer prices rose 0.5
percent last month may have spurred the rise of the
inflation-sensitive gold market, they said. The report added one
more note of uncertainty to an already clouded economic outlook.
   ``I don't think people are looking to gold to make big gains,''
said Ms. Ziemian. ``I think people are looking to gold as a safe
haven.''
   Energy futures prices ended lower in fairly thin trading on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents to 24 cents
lower with January at $19.96 a barrel; heating oil was .14 cent to
.37 cent lower with December at 59.94 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .26 cent lower to .15 cent higher with December at
51.96 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures rose moderately on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, buoyed by expectations for higher cash
livestock prices Wednesday as packers gather inventory before
Thanksgiving interrupts the normal slaughter schedule.
   Live cattle settled .40 cent to .50 cent higher with December at
75.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .53 cent
higher with November at 83.22 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.50 cent higher with December at 49.97 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent to .35 cent higher with February at 63.05
cents a pound.
   Wheat futures slipped on the Chicago Board of Trade while corn
and soybean futures ended mostly higher.
   The wheat market opened lower and remained weak throughout the
session amid selling linked to a lack of significant new export
demand.
   The corn market was buoyed by the USDA's report late Monday of
an unexpectedly large amount of corn inspected for export last week.
   Wheat futures settled { cent to 1{ cents lower with December at
$4.09\ a bushel; corn futures were { cent lower to } cent higher
with December at $2.38 a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent
higher with December at $1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 2
cents higher with January at $5.85} a bushel.
</TEXT>
