<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Prices Cross $400 Mark; Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices soared past $400 an ounce Tuesday,
crossing that psychologically important barrier for the first time
since late January.
   Meanwhile, the dollar fell sharply amid speculation that
interest rates might rise in West Germany.
   Gold prices have been inching upward in recent weeks, but when
they crossed the $400 a troy ounce level Tuesday, buyers
enthusiastically began to snap up the metal.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, a troy ounce of gold
surged $5.50 to $403.70, while Republic National Bank quoted a late
bid of $403.50 for a troy ounce, also up $5.50 from late Monday.
   ``Gold and silver all of a sudden are back in favor,'' said
Steven Pepper, a precious metals analyst with Republic.
   Silver picked up 14.6 cents to close at $5.834 a troy ounce on
the Commodity Exchange, although it fell earlier in London to a
late bid price of $5.71 a troy ounce from late Monday's $5.74.
   In earlier overseas trading, dealers said gold benefited from
the dollar's fall and from the turmoil in Eastern Europe.
   Gold jumped more than $6 in London to a late bid price of
$402.75 a troy ounce, compared with $396.50 bid late Monday, and in
Zurich, the metal rose to a bid of $399 from late Monday's $396.65.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $2.21 to close at a bid $398.61 a troy
ounce.
   The dollar slumped as speculation grew that West Germany's
central bank, the Bundesbank, would be forced to raise interest
rates because the influx of East Germans into the country might
boost economic growth.
   When foreign interest rates rise and U.S. rates do not keep
pace, the dollar becomes less attractive to overseas investors.
Speculation that interest rates might go up abroad often sparks
selling of the U.S. currency.
   Overseas, the dollar reached its lowest level since late
February against the West German, French, Dutch and Italian
currencies. In New York, its tone was stronger because the domestic
market was reluctant to turn bearish on the U.S. currency, said
Linda McLaughlin, a trader at Chemical New York Capital Markets
Group.
   However, the dollar still suffered sharp losses on domestic
markets. Late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.81375 West German marks, down from 1.8338;
1.6130 Swiss francs, down from 1.62975; 6.1775 French francs, down
from 6.2435; 1,336.00 Italian lire, down from 1,350.00; and 1.16995
Canadian dollars, down from 1.17105.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.8200 West German marks, down from 1.8360;
1.6200 Swiss francs, down from 1.6315; 6.2000 French francs, down
from 6.2465; 2.0537 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0760; 1,341.00
Italian lire, down from 1,351.00; 1.1705 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1712.
   The dollar also fell against the British pound. One pound cost
$1.56975 in New York, compared with $1.5582 late Monday. In London
earlier, the pound rose to $1.5645 from $1.5595 late Monday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.24 Japanese yen to a closing 144.43
yen. Later, in London, it fell further to 143.95 yen, and in New
York, it declined to 143.555 yen, down from 144.355 late Monday.
</TEXT>
