<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing Bjt   11-21 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing, Bjt,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing, Machinists Making Plans To Get Back To Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto available</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. managers huddled Tuesday on how to
resume full operations, while Machinists members picked up a final
strike paycheck and prepared to resume work Wednesday following the
end of their 48-day strike.
   A spokesman for Boeing _ which already had an order backlog of
1,700 jetliners before the strike _ said the company may not be
able to resume full production until after the first of the year.
   Workers seemed mixed in their opinion of the three-year contract
ratified with 81.4 percent approval late Monday night, but most
said they were relieved to see an end to the second-longest strike
in Boeing's history.
   ``I think it's fair, but for the amount of days we were out we
could have done better,'' said Carl Olson, a jig builder at Boeing
Advanced Systems.
   ``I'm glad to get back to work but I voted against the
contract,'' said machinist Richard Duncalf. He said the union had
struck to get higher wage increases, but failed to get improvements
in that area over a contract rejected Oct. 3, the day before
machinists walked out.
   The offer ratified late Monday provides wage increases totaling
10 percent over three years, plus annual bonuses totaling 10
percent of gross pay over the first year, 5 percent the second and
4 percent the third.
   On Wednesday, most workers will receive a $500 advance on their
bonus.
   A cost-of-living adjustment formula will account for virtually
all of inflation. Workers will receive a 60-cent-per-hour
cost-of-living increase immediately and a 45 cents an hour base pay
increase to ake up for a 1986 adjustment that workers didn't get.
   The contract also reduces mandatory overtime to two consecutive
weekends and 144 hours per quarter with double-time pay after 160
hours. In the old contract, workers could be required to work 200
hours a quarter and four weekends in a row, a key consideration in
attempting to deal with Boeing's order backlog.
   ``I think it stinks,'' said Ronda Jones, a nine-year Boeing
worker. ``It's hardly any better than the contract first offered.''
   But she said that with the holidays approaching, people wanted
to be back at work.
   Boeing had record profits in its most recent quarter and has a
backlog of more than 1,700 planes worth about $85 billion, with
deliveries for those jets stretching past the year 2000. The
Machinists had received bonuses but no wage increases in the past
six years.
   Production was severely curtailed during the strike, athough
supervisors and non-striking personnel delivered 24 planes, many of
which had been virtually completed before the walkout began.
   Jack Gamble, a spokesman for Boeing Commercial Airplanes, said
managers and supervisors spent Tuesday planning ways to smooth the
strikers' return.
   On Wednesday, most of the day will be spent in crew meetings and
other discussions of what work needs to be done on different
projects, Gamble said. The work also has to be secured before the
start of the four-day Thanksgiving holiday weekend.
   Gamble said there are only four weeks after Thanksgiving before
the contract-mandated holiday period of Dec. 25 through Jan. 1, and
it was questionable whether production could be back at full speed
by then.
   Tom Baker, president of Machinists District Lodge 751 here, said
it may take time for the membership to get over bitterness from the
strike. Many workers ``always thought the company would take care
of them,'' Baker said Monday night. ``They found that was not the
case.''
   ``I don't think you're going to find many ill feelings,'' Gamble
said, adding that one reason for the crew meetings is to get any
such feelings out in the open.
   ``I think from what I've seen, people are all ready, eager and
willing to get back at work,'' he said.
   The last Boeing strike, in 1977, ended after 45 days. Its
longest walkout lasted 140 days in 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
