<FIRST>u f AM-MedicareReform 1stLd-Writethru f0212 11-21 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare Reform, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0212,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Backers Say Reimbursement Changes Could Stabilize Costs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to reword; subs 6th graf pvs, Though the, with 3 grafs
of more Rockefeller comment and detail of plan; subs 13th graf pvs, The
American, to CORRECT title of group and insert quote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of sweeping changes in the way
Medicare reimburses physicians said Tuesday the plan, if it becomes
law, will change the way medicine is practiced in the United States.
   The compromise plan, worked out by House and Senate negotiators
Monday as part of the budget reconciliation bill, would have no
immediately discernible impact on the 33 million elderly and
disabled Americans who receive Medicare.
   Over the longer term, however, supporters say the plan would
improve Medicare beneficiaries' access to medical services and
would help stabilize the costs of the program, which have been
climbing more than 15 percent a year and are expected to reach $44
billion this year.
   Congress was working toward final passage of the overall bill
Tuesday.
   ``It's the beginning of a fundamental change in physician
behavior patterns,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., an
architect of the plan.
   ``Within the next three or four years, there is really going to
be significant change ... in terms of procedures, volume of
procedures, which is what drive up the cost of Medicare,'' he said.
   The result, Rockefeller said, would be a greater emphasis on
less expensive primary care, including preventive care.
   Although the changes would begin with the Medicare program,
Rockefeller said private insurance companies, which also are trying
to rein in the costs of medical care, likely would implement the
changes eventually because ``medicine follows Medicare'' in the
United States.
   The American Medical Association supports the plan as a
cost-stabilizing measure. John Zapp, the association's director of
government relations, said beneficiaries probably wouldn't notice a
difference in care.
   Opponents, however, say the plan would lead to rationing of
health care and a decline in the quality of services. Edmund
Haislmaier, a health-care policy analyst at the conservative
Heritage Foundation, said that the plan may initially level out
costs but that it does not contain the incentives necessary to
control expenditures over the long term.
   Over time, it could lead to rationing of medical services, he
said, adding, ``It's not going to happen tomorrow, but you're
setting the stage for it.''
   The plan, to be phased in over five years beginning in 1992,
includes a new payment schedule for reimbursing physicians who
treat Medicare patients. Now, reimbursements are based on a
doctor's customary charges, which can have little relationship to
cost and can vary from region to region.
   The new rates would boost fees for family and general-practice
physicians and internists. Fees would be lowered for surgeons,
radiologists and other specialties that are procedure-based.
   The fees would be standardized by specialty, with geographic
adjustments designed to account for regional differences in costs.
   The American Society of Internal Medicine, the leading
professional organization for internists, backs the plan, saying
the fee schedule ``will neutralize incentives for physicians to
practice a very high-tech oriented style of medicine,'' helping to
moderate future increases in Medicare costs.
   A spokeswoman for the American College of Surgeons declined to
comment in detail until its officials read the final language of
the measure, but she said that ``right now, we're very favorable.''
   ``This group realizes the world is different and there's a
certain reality out there,'' said spokeswoman Linn Meyer. ``There's
a lot of concern with the costs of medicine ... (and) there has to
be belt tightening. All health-care sectors are going to be
affected.''
   Another part of the plan attempts to slow the increase in
payments to physicians and to control the volume of services they
provide by linking increases in physician payments to a Medicare
spending goal. If physician payments exceed the goal, reimbursement
rates could be cut.
   The plan also requires physicians to submit claims for
beneficiaries. Some now require the patient to pay the bill and
seek reimbursement from Medicare.
   Also, the plan continues but simplifies limits on how much
physicians can charge Medicare patients over the amount they will
be reimbursed by the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GeorgiaGulf 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Georgia Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Gulf Considering Recapitalization, Not Interested in Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to include fact that NL offer has expired
and UPDATE with NL statement and closing stock price; picks up 11th graf,
Raising the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Gulf Corp. said Tuesday it was
considering a debt-financed recapitalization, a defensive move
against NL Industries Inc.'s recent unsolicited $1.1 billion bid to
buy the chemical manufacturer.
   Georgia Gulf said in a vaguely worded statement it had decided a
recapitalization was the best way for the company to benefit its
stockholders.
   The company did not disclose any details of its plans. It said a
special shareholders meeting would be called once arrangements were
made.
   Georgia Gulf said it had considered other alternatives to NL's
$50 a share bid, which was announced Oct. 31 and has since expired.
Georgia Gulf said it had discussed the possibility of a business
combination with or acquisition of the chemical maker by third
parties who had expressed interest in the firm.
   ``A leveraged recapitalization, among the various transactions
under consideration, would be the most favorable to the company's
stockholders,'' Georgia Gulf said.
   Under a leveraged recapitalization, a company usually borrows a
significant amount of money and uses it to pay shareholders a
dividend or expand the business.
   Houston-based NL, which owns about 9.9 percent of Georgia Gulf's
25.6 million outstanding shares, offered last month to buy the rest
of the company for $1.1 billion. During the summer, Texas
billionaire Harold Simmons, who controls NL, said his holdings in
Georgia Gulf were no longer for the sole purpose of investment.
   NL said in a statement Tuesday it was willing to reinstate its
offer, and also said it would support the proposed recapitalization
if the deal would pay stockholders a higher amount than Simmons'
$50 a share bid.
   NL said it was leaving its options open, and would consider
either adding to or reducing its Georgia Gulf stake depending on
future events.
   John Garcia, an analyst with Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. in New
York, said the proposed recapitalization could result in the price
of Georgia Gulf's stock increasing to about $55 a share.
   But in the absence of any details about the recapitalization,
Georgia Gulf shares skidded in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading. The company's stock fell $6.12{ to $46.25 a share.
   Raising the stock price, and the value of his holdings, by
forcing a recapitalization may have been what Simmons wanted all
along, Garcia said.
   ``I think a recap at $55 ends the (takeover) story,'' said
Garcia, who previously characterized Simmons' bid as an attempt to
drive the stock price up. ``A recapitalization was the most likely
outcome in the first place.''
   Charles Rose, an analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co. in New York,
said Georgia Gulf's announcement was obviously a defensive step,
but he said it was too soon to say if the strategy would take NL
out of the picture. He noted that ``nothing has been disclosed''
about the terms of the recapitalization.
   Garcia said Georgia Gulf probably decided against a merger
because of antitrust considerations.
   Georgia Gulf was created in 1985 when Georgia-Pacific Corp.
divested itself of its commodity chemicals business. With 1988
sales of $1.06 billion, the company manufactures a variety of
chemicals and polymers, including aromatic, natural gas and
electrochemical products, as well as thermoplastic and
thermosetting resins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891121-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USAirElection     11-21 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir Election,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mediation Board Again Orders Teamsters Election at USAir</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency on Tuesday ordered an
election to determine whether an estimated 8,000 USAir fleet
service workers will be represented by the Teamsters union, the
third such election in eight years.
   The Federal Mediation Board said the new election was necessary
because many of the fleet service workers, who handle USAir's
baggage, catering and field operations, were non-union workers with
Piedmont Airlines prior to the August merger of the two carriers.
   ``It's disgraceful we have to go through this election again,''
William Genoese, the head of the Teamsters Airline division, said
in a statement. ``But we've beaten this company twice and we can do
it again.''
   Attempts to reach USAir for comment Tuesday were unsuccessful;
word of the decision was received after the airline's Virginia
headquarters had closed for the day.
   The Teamsters said the addition of the former Piedmont workers
would make it the largest union election in the private sector in
four years.
   The Teamsters won an election among the fleet service agents in
1981 but a new vote was ordered last year because of of USAir's
subsequent purchases of several smaller carriers. The Teamsters
again prevailed.
   In ordering the new election, the Mediation Board rejected
arguments by the Teamsters that since Piedmont'a work force was
smaller than the number of USAir workers already represented by the
Teamsters the new workers should have automatically fallen under
the union's jurisdiction.
   Genoese contended USAir sought the election because it hopes to
decertify the union and then contract out the work.
   Three other unions representing USAir workers, the Air Line
Pilots Association, the Association of Flight Attendants and the
International Association of Machinists gained representation
rights of the former Piedmont workers without elections.
   Pittsburgh and Charlotte, N.C., are the two cities with the
largest number of affected workers, about 1,100 in each city, both
of which are major USAir hubs. In all, approximately 8,000 workers
at 147 airports in virtually every state are eligible to vote in
the election.
   Ballots will be mailed out within 45 days and workers have 30
days to return them. Only those workers in favor of union
representation have to return the ballots; those not returned are
counted as ``no'' votes.
   The union must get votes from 50 percent a the work force,
approximately 4,000, to win the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
