<FIRST>r f BC-ManufacturersHanover-Charge     11-21 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Manufacturers Hanover-Charge,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Plans $50 Million Charge for Previously Disclosed Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. said Tuesday it
plans to take a $50 million pre-tax charge in the fourth quarter in
connection with allegations of fraud reported earlier at its
Geneva, Switzerland, office.
   The banking company, which also previously disclosed it had
dismissed an officer at the branch as a result of the allegations,
said an investigation was continuing and that the bank is working
with Swiss authorities.
   It said the charge, which amounts to $35 million after taxes,
resulted from losses on foreign exchange trading for customer
accounts, interest to be paid on such accounts and embezzlement.
   The bank's Geneva office is principally engaged in asset
management for individuals.
   Last month, Swiss police arrested a former Manufacturers Hanover
investment banker in connection with an embezzlement that they said
amounted to $2.2 million from the bank's Geneva office.
   Manufacturers Hanover declined to comment at the time on the
amount of money embezzled, but said that losses like those incurred
at the Geneva office are normally covered by insurance and do not
affect earnings.
   The bank said Tuesday it would seek to minimize the loss through
recoveries and insurance.
   Manufacturers Hanover earned $224 million, or $4.28 a share, in
the fourth quarter of 1988. That was an exceptionally strong
performance, however, as the results included $146 million in
past-due interest payments on loans to Brazil.
</TEXT>
