<FIRST>u f AM-GreatNorthern 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Northern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Tells Stockholdes to Turn Down Georgia-Pacific's Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs with Georgia-Pacific response, edits to
conform; picks up 8th graf, `We are ....</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Avon Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Northern Nekoosa Corp.'s board of
directors on Tuesday recommended that its stockholders reject
Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s sweetened $3.6 billion takeover bid, saying
it was still too low and was illegal.
   Georgia-Pacific, which on Sunday increased its offer to $63 a
share from $58 a share, responded that it would continue its
pursuit of the paper products company.
   In a letter Sunday to Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig,
Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn Jr. said the new offer
represented a 63 percent premium above Great Northern's share price
before Georgia-Pacific's original $3.1 billion offer was made Oct.
31.
   But Laidig, in a letter to shareholders Tuesday, said: ``The
modest increase in the price of Georgia-Pacific's offer, announced
on Nov. 19, has done nothing to change your board's determination
that the offer is not in the best interests of your company and its
shareowners.''
   Also, Laidig said his company's attorneys maintain the deal
would violate antitrust laws. He said the board has determined,
with the advice of the company's financial adviser, Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co., ``that the increased per- share price of the offer remains
inadequate.''
   Hahn disputed Laidig's contentions in a statement Tuesday. ``A
$5 increase certainly is not modest,'' he said.
   ``I wonder how many of Great Northern's shareholders agree that
a 63 percent premium above the unaffected market price is
inadequate,'' Hahn said.
   Georgia-Pacific said it would continue its effort to present the
bid to Great Northern stockholders.
   Great Northern rejected the first offer as too low, illegal on
antitrust grounds and potentially disastrous for the combined
company. Great Northern filed an antitrust suit in federal court.
   Hahn's Sunday letter disputed Great Northern's contentions about
the deal's financial implications. He also demanded a special
meeting of Great Northern shareholders and urged Laidig to meet
with him personally to discuss the proposal.
   ``We are prepared to consider an additional increase in price if
you come to the negotiating table early and demonstrate to our
satisfaction that greater value exists,'' he wrote.
   Prior to Great Northern's rejection announcement,
Georgia-Pacific filed an amended lawsuit against Great Northern in
U.S. District Court in Portland, Maine, accusing Great Northerns's
directors of shirking their duty to shareholders by ignoring the
tender offer.
   The lawsuit also accuses Great Northern directors of plotting to
thwart the takeover by setting up ``golden parachutes,'' to pay
hundreds of thousands of dollars to executives in the event they
lose their jobs in a takeover.
   Georgia-Pacific, which employs 44,000 people, had revenue of
$9.5 billion last year from sales of paper, other forest products
and building materials. It is based in Atlanta.
   Norwalk, Conn.-based Great Northern, with 20,000 workers and
1988 sales of $3.6 billion, makes paper, containers and envelopes.
   The amended lawsuit claims that after Georgia-Pacific made the
offer, Laidig ``refused to take even the minimal steps necessary to
begin to apprise himself of the potential benefits to shareholders
of a negotiated resolution (or even simply of further talks),
benefits about which he could not possibly have known, much less
conclusively evaluated.''
   It also accuses Great Northern of setting up a ``tin parachute''
plan that could cost millions of additional dollars in payments to
some 5,850 non-union employees who might lose their jobs in a
takeover.
   Laidig disputed the contention that extra compensation voted by
the board was a ``golden parachute'' plan.
   The original lawsuit, amended by Tuesday's filing, challenged
Great Northern's by-laws and Maine's anti-takeover statute, which
require hostile suitors to wait five years before they take over a
company, unless the directors of the target company approve the
deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
