<FIRST>r f BC-CFTC-NewContracts     11-21 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CFTC-New Contracts,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Contracts in 2-Year Treasury Notes, Differentials Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators on Tuesday approved a
request by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange to allow it to begin
trading options on Euro-rate differential futures contracts in the
British pound, Japanese yen and German mark.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission also approved a
proposal by the Amex Commodities Corp. to trade futures contracts
on two-year U.S. Treasury notes. Amex Commodities Corp. is a
subsidiary of the American Stock Exchange.
   The trading unit for Amex's new futures contract is a two-year
Treasury note with a face value of $1 million at maturity. The
contract will be settled through physical delivery.
   The single deliverable issue for a particular delivery month is
the two-year note auctioned by the Treasury in that month. Prices
will be quoted as a percentage of annualized yield-to-maturity.
   In the Chicago option contracts, holders will have the right to
buy or sell the relevent underlying Euro-rate differential _ known
as a DIFF _ futures contract. Each of the underlying DIFF futures
contracts is based on the difference between the interest rate on
Eurodollars _ U.S. currency held in foreign banks _ and the
interest rate on the particular foreign currency, either yen,
pounds or marks.
   So-called Eurocurrency, like Eurodollars, is money from one
country, such as Britain, deposited in the bank of another, such as
Italy or Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
