<FIRST>r f BC-AMIMove     11-21 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AMI Move,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Chain Flees Beverly Hills for Cheaper Dallas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical International, the
hospital operator recently taken private in a $1.67 billion deal,
said Tuesday it will relocate to Texas.
   AMI, the nation's third-largest hospital chain, said it will
move its corporate headquarters from this pricey Los Angeles suburb
to the Dallas area next September.
   ``Dallas represents significant cost savings over Beverly
Hills,'' AMI chairman Harry J. Gray said in a statement. ``It is
more central in relation to our hospitals, which are located across
the Sunbelt from the Southeastern states, including Florida, to
California.''
   Gray is a partner in IMA Holdings, an investment group that
teamed with First Boston Corp. to buy AMI with the backing of
Chicago's wealthy Pritzker family.
   The company, which has a total of 1,500 administrative
employees, said some of the 200 workers at its corporate
headquarters Hills would be moved to Dallas, while others would be
laid off.
   Employees at a data center near Marina del Rey and at an
insurance and benefits unit in Costa Mesa will keep their jobs at
those locations, AMI said.
   AMI has said it will lay off an undetermined number of its
40,000 employees worldwide and sell its 23 foreign hospitals and
some of its 48 hospitals in the United States as part of a
cost-cutting reorganization.
   AMI's relocation to the Dallas area follows an exodus of other
corporations to the area in recent years, including J.C. Penney Co.
Inc. and Exxon Corp.
</TEXT>
