<HEAD>Japanese Airline Orders Four Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southwest Air Lines of Okinawa, Japan, has
ordered four Boeing 737-400s and taken options on another four in a
deal worth about $160 million, Boeing Co. said Tuesday.
   Southwest would become the first Japanese carrier to operate the
737-400, a twin-engine jetliner that can seat 145 to 170 people.
The airline already has seven of the older-model 737-200s.
   Boeing has sold 180 737-400s to 23 customers since the model
entered commercial service in September 1988. In the two decades
since the 737 was introduced, 2,723 have been ordered, making it
the most popular commercial airplane in history.
   So far this year, Boeing has received firm orders for 882
commercial jets worth about $46.2 billion, both industry records.
