<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HuntBankruptcy     11-21 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunt Bankruptcy,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creditors' Agreement Staves Off Liquidation Order in Hunt Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former billionaires William Herbert Hunt and
Nelson Bunker Hunt on Tuesday filed a joint $105 million
reorganization plan approved by their major creditors, who have
been at odds for months.
   Attorneys for the Hunts and for Minpeco S.A. and Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co. of New York signed the plans and filed them in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Dallas. Other creditors have until Dec. 15
to file objections.
   The reorganization agreements could head off a bankruptcy
judge's threat to convert the brothers' bankruptcies from Chapter
11 reorganization to Chapter 7 liquidation of their assets.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold Abramson notified all parties two
weeks ago that without an agreement by Nov. 20 he would convert the
cases to Chapter 7 status.
   The agreements filed Tuesday were reached verbally Monday
following hours of closed-door meetings, after which Abramson said
he would defer the liquidation order until Dec. 15.
   Several of the attorneys said Tuesday the plan wouldn't have
come about without such pressure.
   ``It was a combination of the judge ordering conversion of
Herbert's case as well as the IRS telling us that if we didn't have
plans by the end of the year ... they would seek conversion of the
case,'' said Barbara Houser, a Dallas bankruptcy attorney
representing Minpeco, a mining company owned by the Peruvian
government.
   Under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act, a debtor is
allowed to continue to operate with protection from creditors'
claims while a debt repayment schedule is arranged. Under Chapter
7, assets are sold to pay creditors.
   According to bankruptcy court filings, William Herbert has $169
million in assets and Bunker has assets of $250 million.
   Under terms of the agreement, the IRS would get 70 percent of
William Herbert's estate, valued at $125 million, and unsecured
creditors would get another 30 percent.
   Nelson Bunker Hunt would pay 80 percent of his estate, valued at
$150 million, to the Internal Revenue Service and 20 percent to
unsecured creditors.
   The Hunts would be able to keep their personal effects, but
Abramson ordered an auction of a coin collection and antiques.
   Major creditors said they would have received nothing under a
fire-sale Chapter 7 liquidation, and most of the money from the
estates would have gone to the IRS.
   ``We couldn't be happier,'' said Stephen McCartin, head attorney
for Herbert Hunt, who had asked for a delay in Abramson's
conversion order.
   The compromise between Manufacturers Hanover and Minpeco
refocuses both cases away from liquidation.
   Minpeco and Manufacturers Hanover are each to receive 34.6
percent _ or $36.6 million _ of each brother's estate. The total of
all allowed claims is $105.8 million.
   Minpeco has been trying to collect a $132 million court judgment
against the brothers stemming from their alleged attempt in 1979-80
to corner the silver market, which ended with the collapse of
silver prices. With attorneys' fees and interest, the judgment has
swelled to more than $250 million.
   Other creditors _ led by Manufacturers Hanover, which is owed
$36 million _ have argued that Minpeco already has recovered its
silver losses from other third-party defendants and that the money
would be better spent paying other creditors.
   Abramson has allowed only $20 million of the Peruvian mining
concern's claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
